WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.640
[Amit Varma]: While chatting with my writing students the other day, I mentioned that I wished I had

00:00:08.640 --> 00:00:12.860
[Amit Varma]: done such a course when I was in my early 20s. Now, I wasn't praising the course as

00:00:12.860 --> 00:00:17.880
[Amit Varma]: much as I was making a confession about my past self. The 21-year-old Amit wanted to

00:00:17.880 --> 00:00:22.320
[Amit Varma]: write, but knew nothing about writing. He didn't know the craft, and more importantly,

00:00:22.320 --> 00:00:27.100
[Amit Varma]: he didn't know the importance of discipline, of building processes and writing habits.

00:00:27.100 --> 00:00:31.080
[Amit Varma]: He thought he understood life and the world around him, but that was just the arrogance

00:00:31.080 --> 00:00:36.560
[Amit Varma]: of youth. Like most people, I learnt whatever I know by making mistakes. Life gave me hard

00:00:36.560 --> 00:00:42.320
[Amit Varma]: knocks, I learnt. But if I had read more, had more humility, I could have learnt faster.

00:00:42.320 --> 00:00:47.540
[Amit Varma]: If the 47-year-old me could speak to the 21-year-old me, I could change his life, which leads us

00:00:47.540 --> 00:00:53.080
[Amit Varma]: into complicated science fiction territory because a 47-year-old me may not exist then.

00:00:53.080 --> 00:00:59.760
[Amit Varma]: But my point is this, life teaches all of us important lessons, but it's possible, with

00:00:59.760 --> 00:01:05.440
[Amit Varma]: the right attitude, to take shortcuts, to learn those lessons from others and as a result,

00:01:05.440 --> 00:01:10.280
[Amit Varma]: to live our lives better. That's why I find it important to constantly think about life

00:01:10.280 --> 00:01:15.560
[Amit Varma]: and writing and creating and all the things I do, and to try and build a framework around

00:01:15.560 --> 00:01:20.320
[Amit Varma]: whatever I have learnt, and to share that with others whenever I can. And the kind of

00:01:20.320 --> 00:01:39.520
[Unknown]: people I love chatting with on this show are those who do just that.

00:01:39.520 --> 00:01:43.760
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen. My guest today is Prakash Iyer, who is a man of multiple

00:01:43.760 --> 00:01:49.160
[Amit Varma]: careers, all of them successful. After doing an MBA in the early 1980s, he joined the corporate

00:01:49.160 --> 00:01:54.280
[Amit Varma]: world, where he went on to hold top positions at Hindustan Lever and Pepsi, among others.

00:01:54.280 --> 00:01:59.480
[Amit Varma]: As if being a corporate bigwig wasn't enough, he reinvented himself and became an author.

00:01:59.480 --> 00:02:04.040
[Amit Varma]: Driven by the urge to share his learnings and his life lessons, he wrote a series of

00:02:04.040 --> 00:02:09.960
[Amit Varma]: books, the latest of which is just out. It's called How Come No One Told Me That. And Prakash

00:02:09.960 --> 00:02:15.760
[Amit Varma]: further reinvented himself to become a leadership coach, a public speaker, a YouTuber, a modern

00:02:15.760 --> 00:02:21.160
[Amit Varma]: day creator. He is also an alteration tailor. What does that mean? You'll have to listen

00:02:21.160 --> 00:02:28.000
[Amit Varma]: to this episode to find out. But first, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:31.960
[Amit Varma]: Have you always wanted to be a writer, but never quite gotten down to it? Well, I'd love

00:02:31.960 --> 00:02:36.400
[Amit Varma]: to help you. Over the last year, I've enjoyed teaching my online course, the art of clear

00:02:36.400 --> 00:02:41.320
[Amit Varma]: writing, and an online community has now sprung up of all my past students. We have workshops,

00:02:41.320 --> 00:02:46.960
[Amit Varma]: a newsletter to showcase the work of students and vibrant interaction with much stimulation.

00:02:46.960 --> 00:02:51.120
[Amit Varma]: In the course itself, through four webinars spread out over four weekends, I share all

00:02:51.120 --> 00:02:56.640
[Amit Varma]: I know about the craft and practice of clear writing. There are many exercises, much interaction

00:02:56.640 --> 00:03:01.960
[Amit Varma]: and a lovely and lively community at the end of it. The course costs Rs 10,000 plus GST

00:03:01.960 --> 00:03:08.040
[Amit Varma]: or about $150 and the September classes begin on the 4th of September. So if you're interested,

00:03:08.040 --> 00:03:13.280
[Amit Varma]: head on over to register at indiauncut.com slash clear writing. That's indiauncut.com

00:03:13.280 --> 00:03:18.720
[Amit Varma]: slash clear writing. Being a good writer doesn't require God given talent, just the willingness

00:03:18.720 --> 00:03:26.760
[Amit Varma]: to work hard and a clear idea of what you need to do to refine your skills. I can help

00:03:26.760 --> 00:03:27.760
[Guest]: you.

00:03:27.760 --> 00:03:31.160
[Guest]: Prakash, welcome to the scene and the unseen. Thank you so much for having me here. It's

00:03:31.160 --> 00:03:35.120
[Amit Varma]: such a pleasure to be with you. Yeah, I mean, your books are of course incredibly famous.

00:03:35.120 --> 00:03:39.360
[Amit Varma]: I remember after you signed up for my course, some of the other participants were so surprised

00:03:39.360 --> 00:03:44.160
[Amit Varma]: that hey, there's you know, it's like we signed up for Atul Berede's class and we get Sachin

00:03:44.160 --> 00:03:50.520
[Amit Varma]: Tendulkar himself as one of the participants. So congratulations on your new book. But I'd

00:03:50.520 --> 00:03:55.480
[Amit Varma]: like to start not by talking about your books, all the life lessons you've shared, but just

00:03:55.480 --> 00:04:01.040
[Amit Varma]: your life to begin with, which is so incredibly fascinating to me that you spend all these

00:04:01.040 --> 00:04:05.520
[Amit Varma]: years in the corporate world. And then you sort of become a leadership coach and you

00:04:05.520 --> 00:04:10.320
[Amit Varma]: know, and in a sense transform just the way that you kind of look at the world and look

00:04:10.320 --> 00:04:15.440
[Amit Varma]: at yourself. But take me back to your childhood. Where were you born? Where did you grow up?

00:04:15.440 --> 00:04:18.520
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I know that you spend a certain part of your childhood in Jaipur where you learn

00:04:18.520 --> 00:04:23.820
[Amit Varma]: to fly kites and you started learning leadership lessons from that point on when you were five

00:04:23.820 --> 00:04:28.560
[Amit Varma]: years old. But in general, take me back to your childhood. Where did your dad work? What

00:04:28.560 --> 00:04:31.680
[Amit Varma]: were your parents like? How was that childhood?

00:04:31.680 --> 00:04:37.360
[Guest]: So yes, I was born in Jaipur, Amit. And my dad used to be working in a steel rolling

00:04:37.360 --> 00:04:44.200
[Guest]: mill in Jaipur. And I was born in our house in Jaipur. And there's a little story attached

00:04:44.200 --> 00:04:48.560
[Guest]: to that because we went back several years later with my wife and I showed her the house

00:04:48.560 --> 00:04:52.360
[Guest]: where we were born. But I'll come to that some other time maybe. So I was born in Jaipur.

00:04:52.360 --> 00:04:57.800
[Guest]: Dad used to be, you know, a huge influence on my life. As I look back, my father was

00:04:57.800 --> 00:05:02.920
[Guest]: a huge influence. He left home when he was 18 from a small town called Perimbavur in

00:05:02.920 --> 00:05:07.920
[Guest]: Kerala and came to Mumbai, Bombay at that time to work with the railways and came here

00:05:07.920 --> 00:05:13.640
[Guest]: and then kind of educated himself and got a diploma in engineering. But more importantly,

00:05:13.640 --> 00:05:18.840
[Guest]: here was this man who probably spoke only Tamil and Malayalam, who comes and a bit of

00:05:18.840 --> 00:05:23.200
[Guest]: English perhaps at that time and comes to Bombay and learns Hindi and becomes so good

00:05:23.200 --> 00:05:27.800
[Guest]: at it that he starts teaching Hindi at the Bombay Tamil Sangam, which is really meant

00:05:27.800 --> 00:05:31.720
[Guest]: to help all these people who come from the south to work in Bombay and don't know Hindi.

00:05:31.720 --> 00:05:35.760
[Guest]: So he's actually out there teaching Hindi. And I say this because in many ways, that's

00:05:35.760 --> 00:05:39.400
[Guest]: a memory that kind of stays with me to say, wow, you know, it takes a certain kind of

00:05:39.400 --> 00:05:44.080
[Guest]: person to do this. And as I look at myself and my children now, I wonder if we have the

00:05:44.080 --> 00:05:51.160
[Guest]: ability to pick up languages like perhaps another generation did. A very nice and comfortable

00:05:51.160 --> 00:05:57.560
[Guest]: childhood, very fond memories of flying kites, of going to school, of going to St. Xavier's

00:05:57.560 --> 00:06:03.880
[Guest]: in Jaipur and having the headmaster look at my shoes and say, shining shoes. And I still

00:06:03.880 --> 00:06:07.440
[Guest]: remember that. And I keep thinking that if you're in a meeting and if you're in anything

00:06:07.440 --> 00:06:13.000
[Guest]: formal, hey, make sure your shoes are shining. We moved from Jaipur to Delhi to Bombay. My

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:17.440
[Guest]: father used to be in, was in private service, tried some business, which looked like the

00:06:17.440 --> 00:06:21.360
[Guest]: best time of our life because suddenly we had like, you know, cars and we had bought

00:06:21.360 --> 00:06:24.760
[Guest]: a house. But he was in business, which also meant that suddenly we found everything was

00:06:24.760 --> 00:06:30.960
[Guest]: going away and, you know, tough times. But overall, very, very fond memories of growing

00:06:30.960 --> 00:06:35.400
[Guest]: up, of time spent in Jaipur. Let me tell you a little other small memory that I have from

00:06:35.400 --> 00:06:42.900
[Guest]: Jaipur again, which is my father used to be part of the Dakshin Bharatiya Samiti in Jaipur.

00:06:42.900 --> 00:06:46.920
[Guest]: So one of the things they would do is these cultural events of some kind. And I remember

00:06:46.920 --> 00:06:52.880
[Guest]: featuring in one of these little performances. It was a play which my dad had written. And

00:06:52.880 --> 00:06:59.360
[Guest]: the whole thing was in Tamil, but it was songs sung in Tamil set to very popular Hindi film

00:06:59.360 --> 00:07:05.240
[Guest]: music. So, you know, I played a Mantri in that little as a six-year-old or a five-year-old

00:07:05.240 --> 00:07:11.360
[Guest]: at that time. And the song I had was set to the tune of, Chod Gaye Balam, Hai Mujhe, you

00:07:11.360 --> 00:07:15.200
[Guest]: know, Saath Hamara Chod Gaye, whatever that song was, very popular Hindi songs. And I'm

00:07:15.200 --> 00:07:20.240
[Guest]: saying this because as I now look at the things I've done in my life, I like this idea that

00:07:20.240 --> 00:07:26.680
[Guest]: you can take a popular Hindi song and set it to Tamil lyrics and make it work. And that

00:07:26.680 --> 00:07:32.560
[Guest]: you don't have to listen to a Hindi film song the way it was. So one of my favorite past

00:07:32.560 --> 00:07:40.700
[Guest]: times as a young kid was to set, you know, to translate Hindi songs into English. So

00:07:40.700 --> 00:07:45.560
[Guest]: I would sing very confidently, my life is a plain paper, plain it remained because,

00:07:45.560 --> 00:07:51.640
[Guest]: you know, Mera jeevan kora kaagaz kora hi reh gaya. And maybe I'm trying to attribute

00:07:51.640 --> 00:07:56.720
[Guest]: too much to it, but it perhaps got me started on this journey of not of looking at things

00:07:56.720 --> 00:08:00.720
[Guest]: and saying, maybe there's another interesting way to do it. Maybe there's something else

00:08:00.720 --> 00:08:03.880
[Guest]: happening over here. And my father, as you might have guessed by now, because he did

00:08:03.880 --> 00:08:09.000
[Guest]: theater and stuff like that. So he was, you know, he was fairly creative in many senses.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:14.200
[Guest]: He got me onto this journey of, of let's say, feeling confident about being in an elocution

00:08:14.200 --> 00:08:18.860
[Guest]: contest in school or being in a debate in school. And that again, gave me the confidence

00:08:18.860 --> 00:08:22.480
[Guest]: to say, maybe this is something that I can do reasonably well. And I still remember as

00:08:22.480 --> 00:08:27.960
[Guest]: a little kid, I would write letters to the editor. And in those days, there used to be

00:08:27.960 --> 00:08:33.440
[Guest]: sports week. And I would write like this, you know, superbly creative piece of work,

00:08:33.440 --> 00:08:37.920
[Guest]: which would be something like, you know, congratulations, Sunny for scoring a ton at Melbourne, keep

00:08:37.920 --> 00:08:43.360
[Guest]: it up. And guess what, you know, God bless Khaled Ansari, he would actually publish it

00:08:43.360 --> 00:08:48.120
[Guest]: in sports week. And I would find that my name was appearing in that last page, you know,

00:08:48.120 --> 00:08:52.920
[Guest]: with those three lines attributed to me, I would be walking up to a newspaper stall in

00:08:52.920 --> 00:08:58.040
[Guest]: Mumbai. And I would actually sneakily peek into the last page of sports week before deciding

00:08:58.040 --> 00:09:02.080
[Guest]: whether I want to spend a rupee on buying it. And if my name was there, I would pick

00:09:02.080 --> 00:09:07.000
[Guest]: it up and I would come home. And I think my parents felt so good. But at least my recall

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:10.120
[Guest]: is my parents said, wow, what a good thing. And if there was a guest at home, they would

00:09:10.120 --> 00:09:15.080
[Guest]: show that to people to say, hey, look, here's something that our son has written. And maybe

00:09:15.080 --> 00:09:20.120
[Guest]: these things got me interested, excited. So I'd write a bit, went to school, I, you know,

00:09:20.120 --> 00:09:25.560
[Guest]: would be would debate a fair bit and did reasonably well at that, would write essays in school.

00:09:25.560 --> 00:09:30.120
[Guest]: And again, and I'm just looking back to say that as you write an essay, and I remember

00:09:30.120 --> 00:09:36.800
[Guest]: class eight or nine, we were asked to write an essay about a person I admire. Okay, and

00:09:36.800 --> 00:09:43.160
[Guest]: so you can imagine most essays in class were like, you know, Mahatma Gandhi or stuff like

00:09:43.160 --> 00:09:49.840
[Guest]: that. And here I am, I wrote about my brother, my older brother, as the person I admire.

00:09:49.840 --> 00:09:53.480
[Guest]: And the teacher thought it was pretty cool. My parents thought it was pretty cool. My

00:09:53.480 --> 00:09:59.200
[Guest]: brother, of course, thought it was very, very cool. And these, I guess, were interesting

00:09:59.200 --> 00:10:02.880
[Guest]: memories for me, did reasonably well in school. And when I was graduating, here's another

00:10:02.880 --> 00:10:09.760
[Guest]: memory. My physics teacher, a kind gentleman called Mr. Venugopal, he, you know, sees says

00:10:09.760 --> 00:10:14.240
[Guest]: well done and, you know, I've done reasonably well in school. And so he says, so what are

00:10:14.240 --> 00:10:19.320
[Guest]: you going to do now? Now, if you're a South Indian boy from a middle class home, and you've

00:10:19.320 --> 00:10:23.880
[Guest]: done reasonably well at school, it's a given that you have to do science and then become

00:10:23.880 --> 00:10:29.080
[Guest]: an engineer or a doctor. I mean, you cannot think of anything else. And I remember my

00:10:29.080 --> 00:10:36.520
[Guest]: physics teacher telling me, I think you should do arts. Okay, but I'm now this is what 1977,

00:10:36.520 --> 00:10:40.280
[Guest]: you don't do arts. Arts is for those, you know, especially if you live in Bombay, maybe

00:10:40.280 --> 00:10:44.440
[Guest]: if you lived in Delhi, there's a St. Stephen's and you start thinking of stuff like that,

00:10:44.440 --> 00:10:49.360
[Guest]: but it never even crossed my mind or within the family to say I should do arts. I did

00:10:49.360 --> 00:10:54.080
[Guest]: science quickly figured that engineering is not the kind of thing I want to do, but luckily

00:10:54.080 --> 00:11:00.560
[Guest]: found statistics and loved it. So I actually did a BSc, which would have more arts courses

00:11:00.560 --> 00:11:06.080
[Guest]: than science. I did economics, statistics and math. And really, as I look back, I think

00:11:06.080 --> 00:11:09.520
[Guest]: one of the better things I did in my life was to have done statistics in college because

00:11:09.520 --> 00:11:16.520
[Guest]: I think it's hugely useful as a skill to have as compared to perhaps doing several other

00:11:16.520 --> 00:11:21.840
[Guest]: things you could do. So that's like a, you know, a quick recap of what early years in

00:11:21.840 --> 00:11:27.280
[Amit Varma]: my life might have been. Yeah, many, many strands I want to follow up on. And one of

00:11:27.280 --> 00:11:31.400
[Amit Varma]: them which comes to mind is, you know, when you describe your father sort of migrating

00:11:31.400 --> 00:11:37.320
[Amit Varma]: to the north from Kerala, and then learning Hindi and then teaching Hindi to his community.

00:11:37.320 --> 00:11:43.960
[Amit Varma]: And it seems to me that there is a sort of the best aspect of how we can think about

00:11:43.960 --> 00:11:48.400
[Amit Varma]: community in India, that you go somewhere else, but you're not insular when you connect

00:11:48.400 --> 00:11:53.720
[Amit Varma]: with your community. Instead, you help them adapt to what the wider society which in his

00:11:53.720 --> 00:11:59.440
[Amit Varma]: case he did by teaching Hindi or by you know, having those interesting crossover musical

00:11:59.440 --> 00:12:05.000
[Amit Varma]: experiments, and so on and so forth. And in recent times, especially there is also an

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:09.680
[Amit Varma]: uglier side to it. Like, of course, this side of it is also a side that lends itself well

00:12:09.680 --> 00:12:14.200
[Amit Varma]: to globalization. And we see it all across the world where our identities are broadening

00:12:14.200 --> 00:12:20.520
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that we hold on to those aspects of our past with pride and with joy, but also

00:12:20.520 --> 00:12:25.240
[Amit Varma]: we open ourselves to the outside world. But equally in our modern politics, there is also

00:12:25.240 --> 00:12:32.760
[Amit Varma]: this strain of becoming more and more insular of these sort of divisions kind of sharpening.

00:12:32.760 --> 00:12:38.720
[Amit Varma]: Now in your experience from the 70s, 80s, 90s to now, when you look back on this entire

00:12:38.720 --> 00:12:45.200
[Amit Varma]: span of time, what is your sense of the movement of things? Like, you know, when I look at

00:12:45.200 --> 00:12:50.440
[Amit Varma]: the way that I grew up, probably a decade younger than you or so, and when I look at

00:12:50.440 --> 00:12:57.280
[Amit Varma]: the way that I grew up, it was a very cloistered, elite English speaking kind of existence where

00:12:57.280 --> 00:13:02.960
[Amit Varma]: you received the idea of India was all of these sort of feel good, Nehruvian things

00:13:02.960 --> 00:13:07.760
[Amit Varma]: and all of that. But today, it seems that the reality all along may have been something

00:13:07.760 --> 00:13:14.480
[Amit Varma]: else entirely. What is your sense of that? Because what your work also took you out into

00:13:14.480 --> 00:13:20.880
[Amit Varma]: doing was just interacting with a lot of people who were outside your immediate social circles,

00:13:20.880 --> 00:13:24.960
[Amit Varma]: per se, and in the kind of marketing roles that you would have done in companies like

00:13:24.960 --> 00:13:30.640
[Amit Varma]: HLL. Also, therefore, having to understand kind of the pulse of the country. Have we

00:13:30.640 --> 00:13:34.760
[Amit Varma]: changed fundamentally? Were we always like this? And were we missing something then?

00:13:34.760 --> 00:13:38.520
[Guest]: What are your sort of observations? As I look back, maybe there are two things

00:13:38.520 --> 00:13:41.880
[Guest]: that are happening or two things that come to my mind. The first, of course, is I think

00:13:41.880 --> 00:13:47.920
[Guest]: childhood influences, parental influences, I think are very strong for all of us. And

00:13:47.920 --> 00:13:51.440
[Guest]: I'd like to believe that a lot of the way I might look at the world, the way I might

00:13:51.440 --> 00:13:58.200
[Guest]: have seen things was born out of what I might have seen at home. And in that sense, I guess

00:13:58.200 --> 00:14:02.600
[Guest]: I was lucky that whatever is the lottery that we are all supposed to have been lucky at

00:14:02.600 --> 00:14:05.760
[Guest]: in terms of saying that, you know, we were lucky to be born where we were. And I think

00:14:05.760 --> 00:14:11.360
[Guest]: it's been a privilege that I think has a huge impact. And as I look at a lot of other people,

00:14:11.360 --> 00:14:19.040
[Guest]: I've often felt that you come across people who are probably much smarter, have had far

00:14:19.040 --> 00:14:23.760
[Guest]: more opportunities to do great things in life, but perhaps missed out on some of those early

00:14:23.760 --> 00:14:31.000
[Guest]: lessons on staying grounded, on respecting other people, on valuing differences of opinion

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:36.440
[Guest]: and not trying to, you know, foist your views onto everybody else. And maybe that's something

00:14:36.440 --> 00:14:42.520
[Guest]: that has had an impact. I certainly think that it was a much nicer, easier world. And

00:14:42.520 --> 00:14:49.440
[Guest]: even if I look at it from a professional standpoint, my early career was spent in sales. And therefore,

00:14:49.440 --> 00:14:54.440
[Guest]: a large part of the early years would mean going to Tirupur and selling something or

00:14:54.440 --> 00:14:59.840
[Guest]: going to Asansol and trying to sell more Pepsi or soap or whatever it was. What that does

00:14:59.840 --> 00:15:05.360
[Guest]: is it just opens your eyes to the diversity of the country. People are different. You

00:15:05.360 --> 00:15:10.760
[Guest]: learn not to stereotype people. You learn not to prejudge. And you often realize that

00:15:10.760 --> 00:15:18.160
[Guest]: now that you are in Saharanpur or, you know, God forbid, you are in, you know, in the neck

00:15:18.160 --> 00:15:22.600
[Guest]: of the woods in Azamgarh, you suddenly realize that you are actually at the mercy of your

00:15:22.600 --> 00:15:28.680
[Guest]: distributor or your salesperson. And you better learn to respect who they are and what they

00:15:28.680 --> 00:15:34.120
[Guest]: do. And you can't be expecting them to be like you or to necessarily say that, look,

00:15:34.120 --> 00:15:40.240
[Guest]: I'm senior, I will tell you what to do. So I think it builds a sense of, I'm not, I think

00:15:40.240 --> 00:15:45.320
[Guest]: modesty is the right word, but a sense of just appreciating the fact that you may be

00:15:45.320 --> 00:15:49.880
[Guest]: who you are, but learn to value other people, learn to value what they might bring to the

00:15:49.880 --> 00:15:54.640
[Guest]: table. And very often what they bring to the table is not a function of how much, which

00:15:54.640 --> 00:15:59.720
[Guest]: college they went to or what level of seniority they might have in the organization. So I

00:15:59.720 --> 00:16:04.040
[Guest]: think that's something else that's become very strong for me. And I sometimes worry

00:16:04.040 --> 00:16:09.280
[Guest]: that as we become more and more insular, as we start to think or spend more time in echo

00:16:09.280 --> 00:16:15.960
[Guest]: chambers with people like ourselves, we start to imagine that that's the world and that

00:16:15.960 --> 00:16:21.080
[Guest]: we have all the answers and that's the way everybody is. And we forget that there's actually

00:16:21.080 --> 00:16:25.600
[Guest]: still a large part of our country, a large part of our people who are very, very different.

00:16:25.600 --> 00:16:30.840
[Guest]: Something else, Amit, that might be interesting here is that my kids, and I often think about

00:16:30.840 --> 00:16:37.120
[Guest]: my children, and they went to 11 schools by the time they finished class 10. And this

00:16:37.120 --> 00:16:41.880
[Guest]: is largely because I was enrolled, which required me to move from one city to another, to another.

00:16:41.880 --> 00:16:46.720
[Guest]: And every time we moved, the wife was pretty clear, the kids, the family will move with

00:16:46.720 --> 00:16:50.440
[Guest]: me. So it was never an option to say, oh my goodness, we've just come here, you go, we'll

00:16:50.440 --> 00:16:55.400
[Guest]: stay here. So there was a feeling that as a family, we must stay together, which again,

00:16:55.400 --> 00:17:00.800
[Guest]: feels a bit like maybe an outdated, more or a value to say, hey, why did you do that?

00:17:00.800 --> 00:17:04.640
[Guest]: You know, your kids could have spent their time in one school, maybe they would have

00:17:04.640 --> 00:17:09.840
[Guest]: done better, got better grades, probably got into an IIT, which they didn't. But as I look

00:17:09.840 --> 00:17:13.880
[Guest]: back, I think it's a good thing. And the kids think it's a damn good thing. They had to

00:17:13.880 --> 00:17:17.920
[Guest]: make new friends every year, they were in a new school every year. And I think they

00:17:17.920 --> 00:17:24.160
[Guest]: just learned to adjust a lot more, a lot better. And to me, that's a fabulous skill to have.

00:17:24.160 --> 00:17:28.040
[Guest]: This ability to say, I'll go anywhere, I'll still make new friends. I don't have to worry

00:17:28.040 --> 00:17:32.520
[Guest]: about, oh my goodness, this has changed. This is not how it used to be. And maybe there's

00:17:32.520 --> 00:17:35.040
[Amit Varma]: value in that too.

00:17:35.040 --> 00:17:38.600
[Guest]: That's a very interesting observation. So how old are your kids? What do they do now?

00:17:38.600 --> 00:17:46.560
[Guest]: They're twins, Amit. They are 31 and therefore 31. And they both work. My daughter works

00:17:46.560 --> 00:17:53.760
[Guest]: in HR with OYO, with the OYO hotel group. And my son is with Star Sports. He does marketing

00:17:53.760 --> 00:17:54.760
[Guest]: for the Kabaddi League.

00:17:54.760 --> 00:18:01.200
[Amit Varma]: Oh, okay. So the same kind of love for sports as you had. So a few interesting strands from

00:18:01.200 --> 00:18:05.520
[Amit Varma]: what you were speaking about earlier. Like one, obviously that, hey, you were a South

00:18:05.520 --> 00:18:10.640
[Amit Varma]: Indian boy, good at science, good at studies, all of that. You were expected to do engineering,

00:18:10.640 --> 00:18:16.040
[Amit Varma]: become an engineer or a doctor, etc, etc. All of those things. Or maybe the IAS has

00:18:16.040 --> 00:18:19.240
[Amit Varma]: a fallback option, but you chose a private sector.

00:18:19.240 --> 00:18:24.120
[Amit Varma]: Another interesting thing here is that today it's perfectly natural for everybody to want

00:18:24.120 --> 00:18:29.720
[Amit Varma]: a job in a multinational and so on and so forth. But back in the day, from what I remember,

00:18:29.720 --> 00:18:34.880
[Amit Varma]: it wasn't. It was almost kind of looked upon with suspicion. And you know, the respectable

00:18:34.880 --> 00:18:39.680
[Amit Varma]: professions are the ones we spoke about, doctor, engineer, IAS, and so on. People would spend

00:18:39.680 --> 00:18:44.720
[Amit Varma]: years and years giving entrance exam after entrance exam for the UPLC. And I also did

00:18:44.720 --> 00:18:49.560
[Amit Varma]: arts by the way in college, which was also looked upon at that time, as a very unusual

00:18:49.560 --> 00:18:53.720
[Amit Varma]: decision. And people were like, oh, you're only doing it because your class will be full

00:18:53.720 --> 00:18:59.280
[Amit Varma]: of girls, which which it was that the ratio even in the late 80s, when I opted for that

00:18:59.280 --> 00:19:05.000
[Amit Varma]: was kind of like that. So how did the choice to then you know, enter the private sector

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:10.680
[Amit Varma]: and do all of that kind of come about as it did? Was it easier for you? Because you did

00:19:10.680 --> 00:19:16.080
[Amit Varma]: not have that ingrained sort of sense of hierarchy as as in the rest of society where the private

00:19:16.080 --> 00:19:20.480
[Amit Varma]: sector comes low down because your dad after all was an entrepreneur and did all of these

00:19:20.480 --> 00:19:24.960
[Amit Varma]: things. How did that shift happen in your life?

00:19:24.960 --> 00:19:29.280
[Guest]: I'm not sure if I can find a moment in time. It's probably a continuum of saying that my

00:19:29.280 --> 00:19:34.320
[Guest]: parents probably felt that, hey, here's a kid who seems to be doing all right, seems

00:19:34.320 --> 00:19:40.240
[Guest]: to be enjoying what he's doing. When I was in college in Bombay, I spent afternoons writing

00:19:40.240 --> 00:19:46.000
[Guest]: copy for an ad agency. There was a fairly strong interest in advertising as a possible

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:52.480
[Guest]: career. And therefore, maybe that might have in some sense led me to think of heroes. And

00:19:52.480 --> 00:19:55.960
[Guest]: I remember going to an ad club Bombay meeting where I suddenly see there's a guy called

00:19:55.960 --> 00:20:00.680
[Guest]: Arun Nanda, who at that time looked like, you know, was really very hot. Rediff Fusion,

00:20:00.680 --> 00:20:06.040
[Guest]: which is the agency started was was making waves. And I also happened to hear the then

00:20:06.040 --> 00:20:12.080
[Guest]: marketing director of Hindustan Lever, a guy called Shunnu Sen. He and he was speaking

00:20:12.080 --> 00:20:16.920
[Guest]: at an event and he was so funny and he had so much knowledge coming out of everything

00:20:16.920 --> 00:20:21.640
[Guest]: that he was saying. He was funny. He was interesting. And suddenly, maybe at some level, you start

00:20:21.640 --> 00:20:26.080
[Guest]: thinking of these people and saying, I think there's a hero I can see over here or there's

00:20:26.080 --> 00:20:31.160
[Guest]: a role model that I might want to kind of follow in the footsteps off. And then an MBA

00:20:31.160 --> 00:20:35.120
[Guest]: looked like an interesting thing to do at that stage. And one got familiar with the

00:20:35.120 --> 00:20:38.520
[Guest]: fact that if you were in school and college at that time, so in Mumbai particularly, I

00:20:38.520 --> 00:20:43.320
[Guest]: think there was a fair bit of noise around saying MBA could be an interesting option.

00:20:43.320 --> 00:20:47.360
[Guest]: And that's how I guess I got into into business school and having gotten to business school

00:20:47.360 --> 00:20:51.480
[Guest]: then and then Hindustan Levers, which is the first company that I, you know, that I went

00:20:51.480 --> 00:20:56.080
[Guest]: to work with, became a natural progression to say, if you want to do sales and marketing

00:20:56.080 --> 00:20:59.800
[Guest]: and if you get a chance to work with Hindustan Lever, take it. And maybe I must tell you

00:20:59.800 --> 00:21:04.000
[Guest]: a little sidelight here, Amit, which is again, how perhaps some of our decisions in life

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:09.520
[Guest]: are. I mentioned, I went and wrote copy for an ad agency and I really enjoyed it. And

00:21:09.520 --> 00:21:13.000
[Guest]: I love the fact that I would do something which would then appear in midday the next

00:21:13.000 --> 00:21:17.960
[Guest]: evening or whatever. At the Institute, I had spent my summer working with Hindustan Lever

00:21:17.960 --> 00:21:21.040
[Guest]: and there was a reasonable chance that if I had done a reasonable job, I might have

00:21:21.040 --> 00:21:24.880
[Guest]: got to get a chance to work with them again. But I was very keen to look at advertising

00:21:24.880 --> 00:21:31.760
[Guest]: as an option. And David Ogilvie was this God for me. And I said, I want to work with Ogilvie.

00:21:31.760 --> 00:21:37.120
[Guest]: But Ogilvie wasn't an agency that would come on campus. So what do I do? I actually write

00:21:37.120 --> 00:21:42.360
[Guest]: to a gentleman called Mani Iyer, spelled with an A-Y-E-R, who used to run Ogilvie at that

00:21:42.360 --> 00:21:47.240
[Guest]: time and tell him that I want to, I'd love to work for, in advertising and I'd love to

00:21:47.240 --> 00:21:52.660
[Guest]: work with Ogilvie. And this is days of snail mail. So I've sent it off and nothing happens

00:21:52.660 --> 00:21:56.960
[Guest]: and you don't lose heart. Unlike in current days, where if you don't get a response within

00:21:56.960 --> 00:22:00.560
[Guest]: a few hours, you start thinking, you know, maybe the guy's not interested. But after

00:22:00.560 --> 00:22:03.440
[Guest]: a couple of weeks, I get a response saying, you know, great, why don't you come and see

00:22:03.440 --> 00:22:07.080
[Guest]: me? And I say, you know, I can only come on a weekend, because I have classes through

00:22:07.080 --> 00:22:11.680
[Guest]: the week. And he says, come. So Saturday morning, 11 o'clock at his residence. And I go and

00:22:11.680 --> 00:22:17.560
[Guest]: meet him. And long story short, four weeks later, I get a letter from Ogilvie saying

00:22:17.560 --> 00:22:23.220
[Guest]: that we'd love to hire you into the agency. And around that time, I've also now got into

00:22:23.220 --> 00:22:28.120
[Guest]: placement season at Ahmedabad and I get Hindustan Lever. And you know what the clincher might

00:22:28.120 --> 00:22:34.720
[Guest]: have been for me? Two things. The more public view was that I thought to myself that, hey,

00:22:34.720 --> 00:22:38.520
[Guest]: Arun Nanda went to Hindustan Lever first and then started Rediffusion. So maybe that's

00:22:38.520 --> 00:22:43.000
[Guest]: the route to take. Go into Hindustan Lever, work there and then get into advertising whenever

00:22:43.000 --> 00:22:48.920
[Guest]: you want to. The actual big reason was that Ogilvie wouldn't give me housing. And living

00:22:48.920 --> 00:22:53.920
[Guest]: in Bombay on 1800 rupees a month would have been a challenge. Whereas Hindustan Lever

00:22:53.920 --> 00:22:58.840
[Guest]: have these chamaris and even as a young manager, you would get a place to stay. And that suddenly

00:22:58.840 --> 00:23:03.680
[Guest]: looked like a pretty solid reason to say maybe Hindustan Lever is a good place to go to get

00:23:03.680 --> 00:23:07.800
[Guest]: started and then you can always try and make a move later on. But I've often felt that,

00:23:07.800 --> 00:23:13.640
[Guest]: you know, advertising is that that bus that I let go off, which, you know, I might have

00:23:13.640 --> 00:23:14.640
[Guest]: enjoyed being in.

00:23:14.640 --> 00:23:19.960
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's the counterfactual is always interesting. You make these small decisions

00:23:19.960 --> 00:23:24.120
[Amit Varma]: and suddenly, you know, 30 years later, you wonder what your life would have been if you

00:23:24.120 --> 00:23:28.960
[Amit Varma]: had kind of taken the other one. So you're kind of one of the early MBAs, in a sense,

00:23:28.960 --> 00:23:34.160
[Amit Varma]: you went to IIMA, right? So, which is pretty elite right now, but was even way more elite

00:23:34.160 --> 00:23:39.160
[Amit Varma]: back then because there were sort of so few places in India where you could do an MBA.

00:23:39.160 --> 00:23:43.080
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things that they say is that the big deal about going to an elite management

00:23:43.080 --> 00:23:47.560
[Amit Varma]: school is not just what you learn, but also the networks that you form. So the question

00:23:47.560 --> 00:23:51.920
[Amit Varma]: that just comes to my mind now is, when you look back at your classmates and all of that,

00:23:51.920 --> 00:23:55.720
[Amit Varma]: is there some truth to that? Where are they all? Was it an exceptionally bright one just

00:23:55.720 --> 00:24:01.520
[Amit Varma]: because of the selection effect that, you know, so few people actually get in there?

00:24:01.520 --> 00:24:07.760
[Guest]: Yeah. So certainly, I think one of the highlights of being in an institute like that is the

00:24:07.760 --> 00:24:12.440
[Guest]: kind of people you get to spend time with, the people you find yourself in the company

00:24:12.440 --> 00:24:17.600
[Guest]: of. And for me, that's been a huge part of my life. I must add that a batch senior to

00:24:17.600 --> 00:24:22.120
[Guest]: mine was also a fabulous batch. And I made lots of friends with people out there as much

00:24:22.120 --> 00:24:26.400
[Guest]: as I might have with people in my own batch or the batch junior to mine. So that's really,

00:24:26.400 --> 00:24:30.760
[Guest]: you get to interact with three sets of people. It's very humbling, Amit, at one level, you

00:24:30.760 --> 00:24:36.240
[Guest]: get into a place like that and you think, it's natural to think you might have arrived

00:24:36.240 --> 00:24:40.880
[Guest]: that wow. And then you promptly get into a course called Maths and Stats for Management

00:24:40.880 --> 00:24:45.320
[Guest]: and you get a D and you realize that, hey, this is going to be tough. And if you thought

00:24:45.320 --> 00:24:50.240
[Guest]: getting in was tough, getting out might actually be tougher. And that starts to kind of hit

00:24:50.240 --> 00:24:55.840
[Guest]: you. But Ahmedabad was also a place where I suddenly realized that everybody has their

00:24:55.840 --> 00:25:01.680
[Guest]: own strengths and I would never be, I could not have become a topper at Ahmedabad. I figured

00:25:01.680 --> 00:25:05.520
[Guest]: that pretty quickly, but I also figured that, you know what, there's a great idea we've

00:25:05.520 --> 00:25:11.080
[Guest]: got going here, which is to start a Sunday morning rag on campus. And we started something

00:25:11.080 --> 00:25:15.760
[Guest]: called Synchrony and, you know, with a couple of seniors and a couple of us from my batch

00:25:15.760 --> 00:25:21.000
[Guest]: and we started it. And suddenly, Prakash here, along with a few other people, was not just

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:24.720
[Guest]: one of those middling people in class, but was actually the guy who brought out that

00:25:24.720 --> 00:25:30.060
[Guest]: rag, which everybody tried to make fun of, but couldn't pick up, couldn't stop themselves

00:25:30.060 --> 00:25:33.320
[Guest]: from picking up and reading because they were all worried, what would we say about them

00:25:33.320 --> 00:25:39.320
[Guest]: or what were we saying about something else? So I think in some ways, Ahmedabad also taught

00:25:39.320 --> 00:25:44.240
[Guest]: me that there are lots of smart people in this world and you learn from a lot of them.

00:25:44.240 --> 00:25:48.520
[Guest]: They'll challenge you, they'll push you to do better. But at the end of it, we all have

00:25:48.520 --> 00:25:55.240
[Guest]: something about ourselves that we shouldn't lose sight of. And just playing to your strengths

00:25:55.240 --> 00:26:00.320
[Guest]: can become, you know, can become a route, a ticket to success and happiness too. So

00:26:00.320 --> 00:26:05.120
[Guest]: I could have spent those two years wishing that I was in the top 15 or I was in the top

00:26:05.120 --> 00:26:11.560
[Guest]: 10 or, you know, I was a scholar. Now I scoll as they call them. I wasn't, but I have lots

00:26:11.560 --> 00:26:17.540
[Guest]: to look back and say, wow, I made some fantastic friends. I managed to do a bit of writing.

00:26:17.540 --> 00:26:21.040
[Guest]: In those days, I would write for the Sunday Observer. And that was pretty cool again.

00:26:21.040 --> 00:26:24.660
[Guest]: So suddenly you'd find outside the classroom on a Monday, there's a newspaper cutting put

00:26:24.660 --> 00:26:28.880
[Guest]: up on the notice board where usually you would have grades and all those people who've done

00:26:28.880 --> 00:26:33.360
[Guest]: cool work at work, but you'd also find some chappie who's written a piece for Sunday Observer.

00:26:33.360 --> 00:26:39.720
[Guest]: So I think as I look back, fond memories, but surely humbling. And to your point, does

00:26:39.720 --> 00:26:44.880
[Guest]: the network matter? I think it matters at two levels. One, I think it inspires you.

00:26:44.880 --> 00:26:48.840
[Guest]: You see a lot of people and there are some people who've done extremely well for themselves

00:26:48.840 --> 00:26:53.800
[Guest]: and you feel, wow, so good about it. You learn another lesson, which is that there isn't

00:26:53.800 --> 00:26:59.040
[Guest]: a very strong correlation between those rankings at the end of your business school and how

00:26:59.040 --> 00:27:03.040
[Guest]: people might have done for themselves in their lives. There are, of course, a few people

00:27:03.040 --> 00:27:07.880
[Guest]: who have managed to continue to kind of do extremely well, but there are enough examples

00:27:07.880 --> 00:27:12.120
[Guest]: of people who will surprise you. People who might have been at the tail of the class at

00:27:12.120 --> 00:27:17.360
[Guest]: some level, but who go on to do extremely well in the corporate world or indeed as entrepreneurs.

00:27:17.360 --> 00:27:22.760
[Guest]: So that's something else that's an interesting lesson to keep.

00:27:22.760 --> 00:27:26.120
[Amit Varma]: And another strand I want to pick up on is you said earlier that you're very glad you

00:27:26.120 --> 00:27:31.360
[Amit Varma]: did statistics, that it made a very big difference. And it also kind of strikes me in my own life

00:27:31.360 --> 00:27:37.440
[Amit Varma]: that I wish I had studied math much earlier because I think, you know, I began to apply

00:27:37.440 --> 00:27:42.320
[Amit Varma]: mathematical principles and think of the world using math only after I became a professional

00:27:42.320 --> 00:27:47.280
[Amit Varma]: poker player in some ways. And that kind of taught me a lot of humility. It improved my

00:27:47.280 --> 00:27:52.880
[Amit Varma]: decision making, it just made me a different kind of person. Because once you internalize

00:27:52.880 --> 00:27:58.160
[Amit Varma]: some of those lessons, and especially most importantly, the probabilistic way of thinking,

00:27:58.160 --> 00:28:03.840
[Amit Varma]: which teaches you something that is a big part of even this book of yours, the whole

00:28:03.840 --> 00:28:09.160
[Amit Varma]: lesson of humility, where you know, you realize how much of your whatever has happened in

00:28:09.160 --> 00:28:13.560
[Amit Varma]: your life is determined by luck. So you don't let you know, you don't let your successes

00:28:13.560 --> 00:28:18.720
[Amit Varma]: get to your head, you don't let your failures get you down. As I kind of keep stressing,

00:28:18.720 --> 00:28:24.080
[Amit Varma]: I'm intrigued by what are the many different aspects in which you meant when you said,

00:28:24.080 --> 00:28:28.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, learning statistics made a big impact on you.

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:33.440
[Guest]: As I think of what else I could have done, and I'm just thinking of it. A lot of the

00:28:33.440 --> 00:28:38.800
[Guest]: stuff that you might otherwise learn in a science curriculum doesn't necessarily find

00:28:38.800 --> 00:28:44.800
[Guest]: application in day to day work, unless you get to work on that specific science. So for

00:28:44.800 --> 00:28:50.280
[Guest]: instance, if you did chemistry, and you went to work with organics or chemicals, you would

00:28:50.280 --> 00:28:53.880
[Guest]: apply some of this some of the stuff that you might have learned in chemistry, in the

00:28:53.880 --> 00:29:00.940
[Guest]: work that you do. I think statistics is probably a slightly more universal subject, and has

00:29:00.940 --> 00:29:07.300
[Guest]: application across potential jobs, industries, and it's it's almost agnostic to which industry

00:29:07.300 --> 00:29:13.640
[Guest]: you might be in learning the principles of probability. And perhaps more than just the

00:29:13.640 --> 00:29:18.600
[Guest]: principles are trying to say, do I understand how I might calculate the probability, I think

00:29:18.600 --> 00:29:25.640
[Guest]: learning to think with numbers, learning to think on the on what could go wrong, understanding

00:29:25.640 --> 00:29:31.840
[Guest]: probability, understanding why 10 tosses of a coin and what happens when you do a 10 times,

00:29:31.840 --> 00:29:36.880
[Guest]: you know, and what how people might actually make mistakes in their in their thinking around

00:29:36.880 --> 00:29:41.600
[Guest]: around something as simple as that. I think that's, that's really what I think has been

00:29:41.600 --> 00:29:47.960
[Guest]: very, very useful. It also makes you comfortable with numbers. And I, I still say this, and

00:29:47.960 --> 00:29:52.560
[Guest]: I say this to everybody that no matter what you do, it's a good idea to get comfortable

00:29:52.560 --> 00:29:57.520
[Guest]: with numbers. And this is not to suggest that all of us have to be have supremely solid

00:29:57.520 --> 00:30:03.360
[Guest]: numeric ability or any such thing, but just being comfortable with numbers is a is a fabulous

00:30:03.360 --> 00:30:07.880
[Guest]: life skill to have. And then to be able to think in numbers and to think in probability

00:30:07.880 --> 00:30:13.360
[Guest]: and to have that, not have to consciously dive into it to say, oh, I know what to do.

00:30:13.360 --> 00:30:17.660
[Guest]: I remember reading this in a textbook in statistics, or this was in my second year in statistics.

00:30:17.660 --> 00:30:23.400
[Guest]: But just having that at the back of your mind, as a process or a structure that just kind

00:30:23.400 --> 00:30:29.840
[Guest]: of becomes default, and allows you to think, you know, and I think that's useful whether

00:30:29.840 --> 00:30:34.000
[Guest]: you're driving a car and trying to take a turn into a blind alley or taking decisions

00:30:34.000 --> 00:30:40.080
[Guest]: in business or evaluating, you know, should we buy this business or not? Should we sell

00:30:40.080 --> 00:30:44.140
[Guest]: it or not? You know, do we hire? I think everything that you do, there is an element of statistics

00:30:44.140 --> 00:30:48.920
[Guest]: and probability that can come in. So that's how I think it's usually valuable.

00:30:48.920 --> 00:30:53.480
[Amit Varma]: So you've already kind of mentioned the chamarys, which were the deciding factor in your choosing

00:30:53.480 --> 00:30:59.500
[Amit Varma]: HLL over Ogilvy. So tell me more about your time at HLL. Like, what were the impressions

00:30:59.500 --> 00:31:04.720
[Amit Varma]: you went in with? What were your early learnings? Like one of the things that I love about your

00:31:04.720 --> 00:31:08.880
[Amit Varma]: books is that they're peppered with stories from your own life, which carry all of these

00:31:08.880 --> 00:31:14.640
[Amit Varma]: excellent lessons. But it strikes me that a lot of this is you looking back and in hindsight,

00:31:14.640 --> 00:31:19.120
[Amit Varma]: being able to draw these lessons out from what happened to you back then. But what were

00:31:19.120 --> 00:31:23.920
[Amit Varma]: you actually learning back then in real time? Like if you had to look back on, say, the

00:31:23.920 --> 00:31:28.840
[Amit Varma]: big TIL moments on your early years in HLL, you know, what were they like? Tell me a bit

00:31:28.840 --> 00:31:30.360
[Amit Varma]: about those.

00:31:30.360 --> 00:31:33.960
[Guest]: So the first one that I learned was that if someone says TIL and you don't know, today

00:31:33.960 --> 00:31:38.720
[Guest]: I learned is what it stands for, ask. So, you know, never take it for granted. And I

00:31:38.720 --> 00:31:41.480
[Guest]: think you get comfortable with saying that there'll be lots of jargon thrown around.

00:31:41.480 --> 00:31:45.060
[Guest]: There'll be words being thrown around. If you don't know, just ask and get comfortable

00:31:45.060 --> 00:31:51.600
[Guest]: with not knowing. I think a lot of the early years in Levers were also about understanding

00:31:51.600 --> 00:31:59.600
[Guest]: the reality of a marketplace, understanding the power and dignity of a sales profession.

00:31:59.600 --> 00:32:04.940
[Guest]: If you went to business school and you wanted to be a marketing person, and I often talk

00:32:04.940 --> 00:32:09.400
[Guest]: about this, I thought that I would get into Hindustan Lever and have this great opportunity

00:32:09.400 --> 00:32:16.360
[Guest]: to decide advertising campaigns and be out there winning an ad club award. And I go into

00:32:16.360 --> 00:32:22.200
[Guest]: Hindustan Lever and they send me off to sell soap in small town Tamil Nadu and just going

00:32:22.200 --> 00:32:28.800
[Guest]: out there and living on 26 rupees a day allowances, staying in hotels or lodges, which would cost

00:32:28.800 --> 00:32:33.360
[Guest]: like 13 rupees, which is where your salesman stayed and learning to live like a salesman,

00:32:33.360 --> 00:32:37.680
[Guest]: work like a salesman, travel like a salesman. I think it was very, very powerful. So at

00:32:37.680 --> 00:32:44.160
[Guest]: one level, there was disappointment because after six months, your investment banker friend

00:32:44.160 --> 00:32:49.240
[Guest]: was talking about how, you know, it's the airport in Singapore is so nice. The internet

00:32:49.240 --> 00:32:51.680
[Guest]: is, you know, I don't even know if the internet was there, but, you know, they're talking

00:32:51.680 --> 00:32:57.780
[Guest]: about international travel, boardrooms, big deals, and you're talking about, you know,

00:32:57.780 --> 00:33:02.440
[Guest]: how the distributor in Pollachi is going bust and what do you do about it? And you start

00:33:02.440 --> 00:33:07.720
[Guest]: wondering, do I really need to learn this? Is this what I went to business school for?

00:33:07.720 --> 00:33:11.840
[Guest]: To be out there in Pollachi selling soap? It teaches you that, look, that's very important.

00:33:11.840 --> 00:33:16.440
[Guest]: Once you get that bit right, once you understand what's actually happening in the marketplace,

00:33:16.440 --> 00:33:21.160
[Guest]: once you understand what does a salesperson do, how do consumers buy our products in stores?

00:33:21.160 --> 00:33:25.280
[Guest]: If you understand that, then that stays with you for the rest of your life. And as you

00:33:25.280 --> 00:33:30.740
[Guest]: start to make bigger decisions and you start trying to formulate strategy, those strategies

00:33:30.740 --> 00:33:37.840
[Guest]: and decisions are founded on fairly robust basics. And I think that's a powerful lesson

00:33:37.840 --> 00:33:45.160
[Guest]: that I might've got out of Hindustan Lever, just to understand how business really operates.

00:33:45.160 --> 00:33:48.300
[Guest]: Something else that influenced me at Hindustan Lever is how the management trainee program

00:33:48.300 --> 00:33:53.320
[Guest]: at Hindustan Lever sends you through various functions. Six months after being out there

00:33:53.320 --> 00:33:57.760
[Guest]: selling soap, you suddenly find yourself in a soap factory trying to understand how is

00:33:57.760 --> 00:34:01.520
[Guest]: soap manufactured. You then find yourself in a role where you're playing, you know,

00:34:01.520 --> 00:34:04.820
[Guest]: you're calling up truckers and saying, you know, I need six trucks and no, no, I want

00:34:04.820 --> 00:34:08.660
[Guest]: a seventh one today, it's the last day of the month, have to dispatch. And then negotiating

00:34:08.660 --> 00:34:12.600
[Guest]: with him to say, give me that same price, don't charge me more. And then you suddenly

00:34:12.600 --> 00:34:18.080
[Guest]: find yourself spending two months in a small town in UP, in a village in UP, in Ita district,

00:34:18.080 --> 00:34:21.800
[Guest]: where Hindustan Lever used to do a lot of rural development work. So the expectation

00:34:21.800 --> 00:34:26.320
[Guest]: was that all of us as young management trainees will go out there and make a difference to

00:34:26.320 --> 00:34:32.760
[Guest]: the people in that village. And just spending eight weeks in a village, living in that village

00:34:32.760 --> 00:34:38.000
[Guest]: with the village dairy head who used to handle our milk business for us over there, carrying

00:34:38.000 --> 00:34:42.760
[Guest]: a little can, not even a dalda can, smaller one actually, and going into the field every

00:34:42.760 --> 00:34:47.520
[Guest]: morning. It teaches you a lot about what's happening and how a large part of our country

00:34:47.520 --> 00:34:52.560
[Guest]: lives. Again, very, very powerful. Hindustan Lever also, you know, gave me the foundation

00:34:52.560 --> 00:34:58.000
[Guest]: to say that understand how things work. And sometimes the benefit of being in a large

00:34:58.000 --> 00:35:04.400
[Guest]: organization like Lever's was that you saw great processes at work. You saw good people

00:35:04.400 --> 00:35:10.160
[Guest]: operating them. And therefore you suddenly understood what gold standard looks like.

00:35:10.160 --> 00:35:15.600
[Guest]: And perhaps later in my life, it's easy to start saying, you know, yeah, but the people

00:35:15.600 --> 00:35:20.480
[Guest]: here are not as good or they're not as smart. But you learn to work with what you have,

00:35:20.480 --> 00:35:27.720
[Guest]: but you also learn the importance of then putting in place good systems, robust systems,

00:35:27.720 --> 00:35:31.960
[Guest]: which will then stand you in good stead. And I think that's something else that I might

00:35:31.960 --> 00:35:35.520
[Guest]: have learned over there. I also, of course, learned another lesson. So I used to be brand

00:35:35.520 --> 00:35:40.240
[Guest]: manager on Sunlight in my early years. And it was interesting. And in those days, Piyush

00:35:40.240 --> 00:35:45.320
[Guest]: Pandey used to be our creative person from Ogilvy who would be coming in and telling

00:35:45.320 --> 00:35:49.880
[Guest]: us about, you know, aur phir kya hoga, you know, and then he'd tell. So here are the

00:35:49.880 --> 00:35:52.640
[Guest]: two interesting things that I learned from Piyush. One, of course, is that as a creative

00:35:52.640 --> 00:35:56.640
[Guest]: person, he would only think in Hindi, you know, and everything that he told you was

00:35:56.640 --> 00:36:00.520
[Guest]: in Hindi. And here you were thinking, this is my positioning statement. This is my advertising

00:36:00.520 --> 00:36:05.080
[Guest]: brief. And this is what I'm saying. And it was fascinating to see someone turn all of

00:36:05.080 --> 00:36:09.440
[Guest]: that into saying, hey, this is what it does. And I still remember a simple thing. I'll

00:36:09.440 --> 00:36:15.160
[Guest]: give you an example. On Sunlight, we were trying to say how we are very good for colors,

00:36:15.160 --> 00:36:19.400
[Guest]: you know, and how typically, therefore, the problem we had understood was that if you

00:36:19.400 --> 00:36:25.320
[Guest]: use detergent on colored clothes, over time, colors fade. And then, you know, you feel

00:36:25.320 --> 00:36:28.760
[Guest]: that, look, this is not a good detergent. And with Sunlight, we said, we've put color

00:36:28.760 --> 00:36:32.920
[Guest]: guard in it, so it'll protect your colors. And guess what Piyush comes and tells us,

00:36:32.920 --> 00:36:38.520
[Guest]: you know, and he says, yaad hai hum kaise karte the same pinch. Agar maine neeli shirt

00:36:38.520 --> 00:36:42.320
[Guest]: pehni hai aur aapne neeli shirt pehni hai, and I'll say, same pinch. And she said, haan,

00:36:42.320 --> 00:36:48.120
[Guest]: aapne bhi kal khari thi, nahi nahi meri shirt, toh yeh chaar saal purani hai. So, same pinch

00:36:48.120 --> 00:36:52.720
[Guest]: with Sunlight, because even though your shirt is four years old, it still looks like new.

00:36:52.720 --> 00:36:58.600
[Guest]: Okay. And I think it was so fascinating for me as a young kid to see somebody turn a brief,

00:36:58.600 --> 00:37:03.920
[Guest]: a fairly boring brief, I might have thought, into a creative idea, to think in local, into

00:37:03.920 --> 00:37:09.320
[Guest]: in the vernacular, to think in local idiom. Again, I think gives you, allows you a chance

00:37:09.320 --> 00:37:15.280
[Guest]: to respect a lot of other people who do things very differently from you, but do them well.

00:37:15.280 --> 00:37:19.880
[Amit Varma]: On the one hand, it's kind of interesting that, you know, you learn statistics, and

00:37:19.880 --> 00:37:23.600
[Amit Varma]: a big company, if you're looking at a top down view, would look at all of its market

00:37:23.600 --> 00:37:29.360
[Amit Varma]: as basically numbers. And what this experience does is that it helps you humanize the numbers

00:37:29.360 --> 00:37:33.240
[Amit Varma]: and get much deeper insight into what they actually mean and what they come from. As

00:37:33.240 --> 00:37:37.040
[Amit Varma]: you rise up the ladder, number one, do you find that that stays with most people? Or

00:37:37.040 --> 00:37:42.320
[Amit Varma]: once they get more and more away from it, the thinking kind of goes back to thinking

00:37:42.320 --> 00:37:47.640
[Amit Varma]: broadly in numbers again, like, does one have to remind oneself all the time that that the

00:37:47.640 --> 00:37:51.720
[Amit Varma]: market out there isn't homogenous, that every individual is different, that some of the

00:37:51.720 --> 00:37:55.840
[Amit Varma]: things that you speak about in your book that don't make assumptions, you know, always look

00:37:55.840 --> 00:38:00.560
[Amit Varma]: for new explanations and new sort of ways to do things.

00:38:00.560 --> 00:38:05.600
[Guest]: So good leaders, I think, learn to do that. And as you see other good leaders in action,

00:38:05.600 --> 00:38:11.840
[Guest]: you probably learn to do that. I again go back perhaps to early influences. And I think

00:38:11.840 --> 00:38:17.160
[Guest]: it was an important grounding for leaders in Hindustan Lever or in Unilever, that you

00:38:17.160 --> 00:38:23.240
[Guest]: had to spend those first few months or first year out there with salespeople understanding

00:38:23.240 --> 00:38:27.800
[Guest]: how it works. And that tells you that there is a reality out there which might be different

00:38:27.800 --> 00:38:32.920
[Guest]: from what you might have assumed. And I think that stays with you. And it's probably one

00:38:32.920 --> 00:38:37.840
[Guest]: of those good practices that companies like Unilever have that even now, the chairman

00:38:37.840 --> 00:38:42.880
[Guest]: of that company will go on market visits, will go out and will not go in thinking he

00:38:42.880 --> 00:38:47.840
[Guest]: knows the answers. He will go in saying, I don't know, tell me what's happening. And

00:38:47.840 --> 00:38:53.680
[Guest]: he'll want to learn from what's happening over there. And I think having both an open

00:38:53.680 --> 00:39:00.920
[Guest]: mind not having assumed that you have all the answers, recognising that I want to learn,

00:39:00.920 --> 00:39:06.880
[Guest]: that I don't know, I want to learn. And third, also recognising that the world is changing

00:39:06.880 --> 00:39:13.640
[Guest]: very, very quickly. And what you might have thought, you know, oh, I know this, I've done

00:39:13.640 --> 00:39:19.200
[Guest]: this before, I was there, right? Just doesn't work. And you will discover that if you thought

00:39:19.200 --> 00:39:22.840
[Guest]: like that, you will suddenly discover that you missed the bus, but you assumed that people

00:39:22.840 --> 00:39:28.240
[Guest]: were still stuck in shopping the way they were. And you don't realise that your maid

00:39:28.240 --> 00:39:33.360
[Guest]: is actually now saying, I bought this on Amazon. So if she's doing that, she's no longer saying,

00:39:33.360 --> 00:39:37.640
[Guest]: I don't understand digital or I don't, I have to go back to my neighbourhood kirana store.

00:39:37.640 --> 00:39:43.120
[Guest]: The world is changing and changing rapidly. And just being aware of that, I think helps.

00:39:43.120 --> 00:39:47.120
[Guest]: Amit, I must also add, maybe there's something else about, you know, sometimes it also helps

00:39:47.120 --> 00:39:51.800
[Guest]: to be not the smartest guy in class or, you know, and I don't think I, so like I said,

00:39:51.800 --> 00:39:55.840
[Guest]: when I was in Ahmedabad, I was a middling kind of person. And then when I went to Hindustan

00:39:55.840 --> 00:40:00.880
[Guest]: Deewar, someone one year, my junior was a man who I thought was such a bright guy, you

00:40:00.880 --> 00:40:05.200
[Guest]: know, fantastic. I went on to actually become chairman of Hindustan Deewar, great guy. And

00:40:05.200 --> 00:40:12.080
[Guest]: I think you learn to respect people for their abilities, their skills. And you also tell

00:40:12.080 --> 00:40:15.840
[Guest]: yourself that there's space for everybody. There's room for all of us. You don't have

00:40:15.840 --> 00:40:21.240
[Guest]: to grudge people their successes or their greatness. You can in fact celebrate along

00:40:21.240 --> 00:40:25.720
[Guest]: with them and feel good about it. And actually you can learn a little bit by just looking

00:40:25.720 --> 00:40:31.120
[Guest]: at other people and saying, hmm, what might I learn from this person? And maybe it helps

00:40:31.120 --> 00:40:36.560
[Guest]: to not have been on the top of the ladder as it were very early and then say, look,

00:40:36.560 --> 00:40:40.760
[Guest]: I know it all. So maybe that's just a natural corollary of that.

00:40:40.760 --> 00:40:44.200
[Amit Varma]: You were mentioning working with Piyush Pandey on your advertising. And that reminded me

00:40:44.200 --> 00:40:47.720
[Amit Varma]: of one of the most delightful anecdotes in your book, where you talk about how as a young

00:40:47.720 --> 00:40:51.280
[Amit Varma]: brand manager, when you would interact with the advertising team, you would always be

00:40:51.280 --> 00:40:56.080
[Amit Varma]: saying isko zyada blue karo, isko tinker karo, font aisa karo, all of those kind of things.

00:40:56.080 --> 00:41:01.360
[Amit Varma]: And at one point, your boss kind of called you in and said that, listen, don't do this.

00:41:01.360 --> 00:41:04.840
[Amit Varma]: Your job is just to create a brief, they are specialists, they know what they are doing

00:41:04.840 --> 00:41:09.600
[Amit Varma]: better than you do. And then this beautiful quote, where he said, quote, why keep a dog

00:41:09.600 --> 00:41:14.240
[Amit Varma]: and bark yourself, a stop quote. And that's lovely. And what this story also tells us

00:41:14.240 --> 00:41:20.200
[Amit Varma]: with great humility is a little bit about your own journey of learning to get past that

00:41:20.200 --> 00:41:26.520
[Amit Varma]: youthful hubris, where on the one hand, and I say this, because it perhaps took me longer

00:41:26.520 --> 00:41:32.160
[Amit Varma]: than you to get past it myself, where on one hand, you have that hubris that I'm so bloody

00:41:32.160 --> 00:41:35.240
[Amit Varma]: good, there's that thing of I'm so good, and I can do this. And that's a Dunning-Kruger

00:41:35.240 --> 00:41:41.080
[Amit Varma]: effect at work at one level. At another level, it's a level of you have power over people,

00:41:41.080 --> 00:41:45.320
[Amit Varma]: right. And therefore, at some level, you want to tell them what to do, because you're the

00:41:45.320 --> 00:41:49.600
[Amit Varma]: one with the power, you want to tell them you want to show your authority. And that

00:41:49.600 --> 00:41:55.320
[Amit Varma]: lesson which you pointed out in your own life is sort of about stepping out of the way.

00:41:55.320 --> 00:41:59.600
[Amit Varma]: You know, when you look back on the young Prakash Iyer, the young version of you, what

00:41:59.600 --> 00:42:05.480
[Amit Varma]: were the things that changed in him on this journey, especially in the early years, and

00:42:05.480 --> 00:42:09.120
[Amit Varma]: made him eventually the person that you are today?

00:42:09.120 --> 00:42:14.600
[Guest]: I think a lot of a lot of lessons learned early in life, and maybe I was kind of built

00:42:14.600 --> 00:42:18.280
[Guest]: in a way by which I said, let me try and learn this or let me try and understand how can

00:42:18.280 --> 00:42:22.520
[Guest]: I get better on this one. And you're right, maybe it's it's a lot more of now looking

00:42:22.520 --> 00:42:28.600
[Guest]: back and thinking that, wow, that's something that I learned. But some things just stayed

00:42:28.600 --> 00:42:35.080
[Guest]: with me. And an example, you know, which is about how I had a boss called Suman Sinha,

00:42:35.080 --> 00:42:39.280
[Guest]: who was my boss at Hindustan Lever for a while. And then I went and worked at Pepsi with him,

00:42:39.280 --> 00:42:44.600
[Guest]: who's been a huge influence on my life and has been a mentor in more ways than one. I

00:42:44.600 --> 00:42:48.800
[Guest]: remember how one of the things that he taught us was that, you know, he showed us an org

00:42:48.800 --> 00:42:53.400
[Guest]: chart for the organization at PepsiCo. And he said he put up a chart. And these are those

00:42:53.400 --> 00:42:58.000
[Guest]: days of those carousel slides, those 35 slides, which you had to carefully put in upside down

00:42:58.000 --> 00:43:02.040
[Guest]: for it to be projected right in the projector. And I remember how he put up a slide which

00:43:02.040 --> 00:43:08.040
[Guest]: showed the org chart upside down. And I thought, you know, some trainee is going to lose her

00:43:08.040 --> 00:43:12.480
[Guest]: job for having done this wrong. And Suman actually went on to explain that it's not

00:43:12.480 --> 00:43:16.840
[Guest]: wrong. This is the organization I'm trying to build. It's an upside down organization

00:43:16.840 --> 00:43:21.320
[Guest]: where the person at the top of this business is our frontline salesperson. He's closest

00:43:21.320 --> 00:43:25.280
[Guest]: to our customer. He will decide what this business will do. He will tell us what's the

00:43:25.280 --> 00:43:29.880
[Guest]: right thing. And below him is a manager whose job is to support him. And below him is a

00:43:29.880 --> 00:43:34.760
[Guest]: vice president whose job is to make sure that the entire function is doing what the salesman

00:43:34.760 --> 00:43:39.720
[Guest]: needs to succeed. And he would say, you know, at the bottom of this pyramid is me. I'm just

00:43:39.720 --> 00:43:45.520
[Guest]: here to make sure this entire organization is focused on our front, on our customers.

00:43:45.520 --> 00:43:49.520
[Guest]: And I think that just stayed with me. And I thought, wow, what a powerful idea this

00:43:49.520 --> 00:43:54.760
[Guest]: is because you suddenly start realizing that you don't have power over other people. You

00:43:54.760 --> 00:44:00.640
[Guest]: don't have people reporting to you. But you start seeing them as saying, man, I'm responsible

00:44:00.640 --> 00:44:05.480
[Guest]: for them. I'm responsible for their success. I need to do whatever it takes to help them

00:44:05.480 --> 00:44:12.200
[Guest]: succeed because if they succeed, I'm OK. I'll be taken care of. You know, that's been a

00:44:12.200 --> 00:44:17.120
[Guest]: pretty powerful little influence in my life to say every time I've had to lead a team

00:44:17.120 --> 00:44:23.120
[Guest]: and I must confess, I've been sometimes blown away by the by the smart people I've had the

00:44:23.120 --> 00:44:28.680
[Guest]: privilege of leading. And I say, wow, what a fantastic person this is. And I'd be damned

00:44:28.680 --> 00:44:33.120
[Guest]: if I tried to tell that planner, you know, how to get it right, because, you know, he

00:44:33.120 --> 00:44:38.960
[Guest]: was he was so good. My job then was to ensure that I could leverage that planner, get him

00:44:38.960 --> 00:44:42.760
[Guest]: to deliver and help everybody else in the team to say, OK, now we need to take a decision.

00:44:42.760 --> 00:44:48.760
[Guest]: So my job was to get everybody else together. And I was very happy not being the smartest

00:44:48.760 --> 00:44:52.840
[Guest]: person in the room. And that usually meant that every time you were discussing something

00:44:52.840 --> 00:44:57.200
[Guest]: and if it was something, let's say, to do with manufacturing or technical, I was not

00:44:57.200 --> 00:45:01.360
[Guest]: a technical guy and there was somebody else who was smart. My job was to ensure I knew

00:45:01.360 --> 00:45:05.800
[Guest]: how to ask the right questions, maybe ensure we were giving them support that they needed,

00:45:05.800 --> 00:45:10.320
[Guest]: making sure that people working together. But my job was not to be the smartest techie

00:45:10.320 --> 00:45:15.200
[Guest]: or the smartest finance person or the smartest marketing guy in the room. And that, I think,

00:45:15.200 --> 00:45:23.520
[Guest]: has been a huge, almost a transformative piece, I think, for me to say that. Stop worrying

00:45:23.520 --> 00:45:28.880
[Guest]: about you. Stop worrying about saying I must be the smart guy. I must be the guy getting

00:45:28.880 --> 00:45:36.560
[Guest]: credit. People must say, wow, what a bright guy this is. I don't think that's what drove

00:45:36.560 --> 00:45:42.920
[Guest]: me as much as saying, gosh, can I just make sure that as a team we get this right? Can

00:45:42.920 --> 00:45:48.800
[Guest]: we ensure that our collective intelligence, can we harness that to make sure that more

00:45:48.800 --> 00:45:52.480
[Guest]: often than not, we're doing the right thing rather than the wrong one? And there would

00:45:52.480 --> 00:45:56.360
[Guest]: be times when we'd still call wrong. There'd be times when there would be debate and discussion

00:45:56.360 --> 00:45:59.800
[Guest]: and I'd still have to, as a leader, take a call. But I would try very hard to ensure

00:45:59.800 --> 00:46:04.720
[Guest]: that I had kind of got other people together. And to come back to your point, therefore,

00:46:04.720 --> 00:46:11.720
[Guest]: that this whole idea of thinking that you have power over other people, I think that

00:46:11.720 --> 00:46:15.880
[Guest]: hasn't been the way I might have looked at it. And that's another lesson that I learned.

00:46:15.880 --> 00:46:20.360
[Guest]: And this was something else about an orbit line I might have read somewhere, but that

00:46:20.360 --> 00:46:24.840
[Guest]: kind of got me thinking, which was how there's apparently a bunch of professors in Ireland

00:46:24.840 --> 00:46:29.200
[Guest]: who did some research on Champions League footballers. And they found that footballers

00:46:29.200 --> 00:46:34.760
[Guest]: who are two-footed earn something like 27, 28% more than footballers who are good with

00:46:34.760 --> 00:46:42.280
[Guest]: one foot. Okay. And that set me thinking, and I figured later that there's actually

00:46:42.280 --> 00:46:46.680
[Guest]: a school in Scotland called the Other Foot Soccer School, where they teach young children

00:46:46.680 --> 00:46:51.520
[Guest]: to kick with both feet. Because once you're a senior footballer, then you can't be taught

00:46:51.520 --> 00:46:55.960
[Guest]: to kick with the other foot. You've got to learn that early in your life. When it's okay

00:46:55.960 --> 00:46:59.320
[Guest]: to kick with the wrong foot and find the ball is flying somewhere else, it doesn't matter.

00:46:59.320 --> 00:47:03.880
[Guest]: You're okay with it. And because you're okay with failing, you gradually strengthen that

00:47:03.880 --> 00:47:07.760
[Guest]: foot and you become good with both feet. And I think in many ways, in the corporate world,

00:47:07.760 --> 00:47:12.760
[Guest]: it's great. It's a great idea for us to try and say, can we be two-footed? And when you're

00:47:12.760 --> 00:47:16.600
[Guest]: two-footed, you suddenly realize you're not so good with one foot. You're not so good

00:47:16.600 --> 00:47:21.800
[Guest]: with another function, with another discipline, but you learn to respect other people who

00:47:21.800 --> 00:47:26.240
[Guest]: are very good at that. And I think having that humility might be a big word, but just

00:47:26.240 --> 00:47:30.480
[Guest]: having that realization that, you know what, there are other people who will be better

00:47:30.480 --> 00:47:35.320
[Guest]: than you in a given subject area. That's okay. Just learn to work with them. Just learn to

00:47:35.320 --> 00:47:39.880
[Guest]: leverage them and be grateful that you've got good people helping you to get it right.

00:47:39.880 --> 00:47:43.520
[Amit Varma]: In your book, you've actually mentioned, I think, Suman Sena in multiple places, including

00:47:43.520 --> 00:47:48.400
[Amit Varma]: where you spoke about this upside down organizational chart, which sounds beautiful. And, you know,

00:47:48.400 --> 00:47:52.680
[Amit Varma]: you give leadership sessions and seminars to companies and all of that, and where you

00:47:52.680 --> 00:47:57.360
[Amit Varma]: teach all of this, which also sounds great. But the way most people look at companies

00:47:57.360 --> 00:48:02.800
[Amit Varma]: is that, look, companies have a lot of politics. They think that, you know, to get ahead in

00:48:02.800 --> 00:48:06.840
[Amit Varma]: the corporate world, it's not about how good you are at your job, but it's about how good

00:48:06.840 --> 00:48:11.000
[Amit Varma]: you are at managing your seniors and all of that. Even in your book, you know, there are

00:48:11.000 --> 00:48:16.440
[Amit Varma]: bits about the importance of dressing well, and, you know, how the exterior matters, wearing

00:48:16.440 --> 00:48:21.920
[Amit Varma]: a tie matters, all of those things kind of matter. Equally, along with the politics,

00:48:21.920 --> 00:48:25.560
[Amit Varma]: there is also that thing that I often say about, you know, politics in the real world,

00:48:25.560 --> 00:48:30.640
[Amit Varma]: in the case of the state, that power always corrupts. Now, the thing is that, obviously,

00:48:30.640 --> 00:48:35.560
[Amit Varma]: there are more checks and balances within a private company and the incentives are better.

00:48:35.560 --> 00:48:41.120
[Amit Varma]: But there is power that, you know, till the checks and balances kick in, you know, till

00:48:41.120 --> 00:48:45.680
[Amit Varma]: accountability kicks in, even if it's much more than, say, in public life, you know,

00:48:45.680 --> 00:48:52.640
[Amit Varma]: it can kind of corrupt. So many people therefore have a very sceptical view of what corporate

00:48:52.640 --> 00:48:59.120
[Amit Varma]: cultures are like in many places, like, you know, when MeToo broke a couple of years back,

00:48:59.120 --> 00:49:04.080
[Amit Varma]: there was much talk and quite correctly, I think, of how toxic many advertising workplaces

00:49:04.080 --> 00:49:09.560
[Amit Varma]: are, for example, for women and all those corrosive cultures kind of going through.

00:49:09.560 --> 00:49:13.640
[Amit Varma]: So on the one hand, I see that you've not only mentioned Mr. Sinha, you've shared your

00:49:13.640 --> 00:49:17.840
[Amit Varma]: own insights, you've spoken about other leaders through your journey from whom you've learned

00:49:17.840 --> 00:49:23.160
[Amit Varma]: a lot. So there's a lot of talk of all these wonderful principles. But somebody from the

00:49:23.160 --> 00:49:28.280
[Amit Varma]: outside could argue that, yeah, they sound great. But the reality of corporate India

00:49:28.280 --> 00:49:33.400
[Amit Varma]: is kind of something different. And therefore, the assumption is that people like you who

00:49:33.400 --> 00:49:38.080
[Amit Varma]: are trying to improve the culture, like at one point, I think, you quote Drucker saying

00:49:38.080 --> 00:49:42.880
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, culture eats strategy for breakfast. Now, people like you, who are trying

00:49:42.880 --> 00:49:47.600
[Amit Varma]: to improve the culture in these places, improve the way people work, you know, build in all

00:49:47.600 --> 00:49:52.960
[Amit Varma]: these qualities, like humility and upside down org charts and all that, aren't you pushing

00:49:52.960 --> 00:49:57.560
[Amit Varma]: against the tide in a way? And aren't you also pushing against human nature and the

00:49:57.560 --> 00:50:02.840
[Amit Varma]: natural incentives at play. So in the course of your career, you know, if one is to read

00:50:02.840 --> 00:50:07.240
[Amit Varma]: your book, one would just sing that, oh, Mr. Iyer's career has been so remarkable. He has

00:50:07.240 --> 00:50:11.920
[Amit Varma]: been learning these great lessons all the time, and building these enlightened workplaces.

00:50:11.920 --> 00:50:15.960
[Amit Varma]: But there's a bit of selection bias in there, because that's just what you're choosing to

00:50:15.960 --> 00:50:20.960
[Amit Varma]: write about. Is there the other side also, what is your experience with it? Are there

00:50:20.960 --> 00:50:25.280
[Amit Varma]: times you were disheartened about it, say, maybe corporate politics or whatever? Are

00:50:25.280 --> 00:50:30.000
[Amit Varma]: there times where as a leader, you had to figure out ways to change the culture? What

00:50:30.000 --> 00:50:37.560
[Guest]: were those struggles like? So yeah, several strands in that in the set of questions, Amit.

00:50:37.560 --> 00:50:41.520
[Guest]: So maybe let me start by saying a couple of things which have perhaps influenced the way

00:50:41.520 --> 00:50:47.760
[Guest]: I look at the world. I'm hugely positive. I'm a huge optimist. And for me, the default

00:50:47.760 --> 00:50:52.280
[Guest]: always is it's a good place, it's a good world before it starts to get proved otherwise.

00:50:52.280 --> 00:50:58.120
[Guest]: So that's certainly a huge one for me. And I often encourage other people to try and

00:50:58.120 --> 00:51:03.200
[Guest]: think that way. And you're right. Sometimes it can be, you know, personal experiences

00:51:03.200 --> 00:51:08.480
[Guest]: can be to the contrary, you can start thinking it's a bad place. And are there organizations

00:51:08.480 --> 00:51:14.120
[Guest]: and office setups which are political, politicized? Of course there are. And like you referenced,

00:51:14.120 --> 00:51:19.200
[Guest]: were there toxic work cultures? Of course there were. But does that allow us to say

00:51:19.200 --> 00:51:23.840
[Guest]: that therefore the whole world is like that? The answer is no. And here's what I think.

00:51:23.840 --> 00:51:29.560
[Guest]: A, you've got to believe that that's not necessarily true. And the second thing you've got to believe

00:51:29.560 --> 00:51:35.760
[Guest]: is you can make a difference. And I often say this to young leaders about our culture.

00:51:35.760 --> 00:51:41.600
[Guest]: So it's easy to say, my organization culture is like this, right? Or we are such a, it's

00:51:41.600 --> 00:51:46.520
[Guest]: a terrible place or it's so bad and all of that. And my answer to that would be, if you

00:51:46.520 --> 00:51:53.080
[Guest]: have two people working for you, for them, their organization culture is what you do.

00:51:53.080 --> 00:51:58.800
[Guest]: It's not what HR does. It's not what the global CEO is saying. It's not what's happening in

00:51:58.800 --> 00:52:04.240
[Guest]: some other parts of your organization. For them, our culture is what you as a leader

00:52:04.240 --> 00:52:08.880
[Guest]: do. So my point would be, if you are the leader and you've got two people working for you,

00:52:08.880 --> 00:52:14.440
[Guest]: set the culture right for those two people, right? And here's where it starts mattering

00:52:14.440 --> 00:52:19.680
[Guest]: that don't blame it now on the environment. Don't say the organization is like that. It's

00:52:19.680 --> 00:52:24.120
[Guest]: a cop out, right? You need to take ownership for it and say, you can make a difference.

00:52:24.120 --> 00:52:28.840
[Guest]: So A, be positive about it. I think start with an assumption that things are good things.

00:52:28.840 --> 00:52:33.320
[Guest]: And that's just the way I am. But I'd like to say that's the way we could all benefit

00:52:33.320 --> 00:52:37.760
[Guest]: by being. The incentives are better if you do that. The second one, of course, is to

00:52:37.760 --> 00:52:41.680
[Guest]: take ownership for what's happening and say, look, I can make a difference here. Now, what

00:52:41.680 --> 00:52:45.400
[Guest]: are some of the challenges that we can have an organization start to get, you know, become

00:52:45.400 --> 00:52:51.080
[Guest]: bad? I think young people coming into work today don't want to take anything which, you

00:52:51.080 --> 00:52:57.120
[Guest]: know, they have options. They will not take rubbish from a boss. The world is changing.

00:52:57.120 --> 00:53:01.120
[Guest]: They will speak out. There is no fear. There are options available. They will, you know,

00:53:01.120 --> 00:53:04.920
[Guest]: if they don't like a job, the distance between an argument with the boss and a resignation

00:53:04.920 --> 00:53:09.040
[Guest]: letter is really getting shorter by the day. This is a great place to be because these

00:53:09.040 --> 00:53:14.400
[Guest]: young people want to change the world. And if something is happening that's not right,

00:53:14.400 --> 00:53:18.120
[Guest]: they're saying, come on, I want to take the power. I want to change the world. And if

00:53:18.120 --> 00:53:23.720
[Guest]: organizations can learn to harness that power and say, let's get this right, let's try and

00:53:23.720 --> 00:53:26.560
[Guest]: get people to kind of change it. And I'll give you a couple of examples of what might

00:53:26.560 --> 00:53:30.680
[Guest]: have happened. In one of the businesses where I worked, we had a practice where you had

00:53:30.680 --> 00:53:36.480
[Guest]: to swipe your card to come in. OK, and that marked your attendance, it marked your time.

00:53:36.480 --> 00:53:40.520
[Guest]: And of course, you know, good old HR would have policies like four times in a month you're

00:53:40.520 --> 00:53:44.480
[Guest]: allowed to come 10 minutes late. But other than that, you will take half day off and

00:53:44.480 --> 00:53:51.040
[Guest]: another repeat will mean a full day off. Now, this isn't quite anybody's idea of a great

00:53:51.040 --> 00:53:55.120
[Guest]: organization, but most factories were built this way. And very often what happens is that

00:53:55.120 --> 00:53:59.280
[Guest]: you start looking for contrary evidence then and you suddenly realize that if you were

00:53:59.280 --> 00:54:03.320
[Guest]: to relax it like I thought I would, and you suddenly start wondering, are there a lot

00:54:03.320 --> 00:54:07.240
[Guest]: other people who are willing to take advantage of it? Are you suddenly discovering that on

00:54:07.240 --> 00:54:11.520
[Guest]: every time that you have a meeting at 10 o'clock, there are four people who have had work in

00:54:11.520 --> 00:54:15.400
[Guest]: a school or a bank and are not there in the meeting that day? You know, so why does this

00:54:15.400 --> 00:54:20.760
[Guest]: happen? But you've got to kind of now understand that this was culture from the past. It may

00:54:20.760 --> 00:54:27.640
[Guest]: not work. And how do I now start thinking of it from that young millennial's perspective

00:54:27.640 --> 00:54:31.360
[Guest]: and say, what's the culture that will work for them? How do I get this person to feel

00:54:31.360 --> 00:54:36.000
[Guest]: the need to be in office at time, to feel the need to ensure that discipline of some

00:54:36.000 --> 00:54:41.960
[Guest]: kind matters. So I think you have a chance to change culture. If you're willing to also

00:54:41.960 --> 00:54:46.680
[Guest]: adapt yourself, you can't be saying culture is what I've decided. You try and figure how

00:54:46.680 --> 00:54:51.080
[Guest]: it, how does this work for younger people? You try and take them in to that journey.

00:54:51.080 --> 00:54:54.520
[Guest]: And you try and say, look, what can I do to make it work? One of the bigger mistakes you

00:54:54.520 --> 00:54:59.180
[Guest]: can make as a leader is to also think that this culture is terrible. My previous organization

00:54:59.180 --> 00:55:03.460
[Guest]: got it right. And you then try and come into a business and try and say, let me try and

00:55:03.460 --> 00:55:06.280
[Guest]: change everything over here. And that's something else that I refer to perhaps in one of those

00:55:06.280 --> 00:55:10.760
[Guest]: stories that I talk about, you know, setting out to drive early morning with your headlights,

00:55:10.760 --> 00:55:14.480
[Guest]: you know, you get out in the morning at 6.30, as I did one morning. And I didn't think that

00:55:14.480 --> 00:55:19.640
[Guest]: headlights were needed. And I go out on the street and I see lots of cars with their headlights

00:55:19.640 --> 00:55:25.840
[Guest]: on. And I start to think, why does this man have his headlights on? And then I see another

00:55:25.840 --> 00:55:29.980
[Guest]: car with headlights on. And then my wife says, you know, maybe they left home much earlier.

00:55:29.980 --> 00:55:33.080
[Guest]: So for them, they had left home at a time and they needed the lights and they've still

00:55:33.080 --> 00:55:37.000
[Guest]: got it on because they still think the light is not good enough. Whereas you came in later

00:55:37.000 --> 00:55:41.740
[Guest]: and you didn't think there was a need for it. And I think this is so true for organizations.

00:55:41.740 --> 00:55:45.920
[Guest]: Leader comes from outside and he starts wondering, why are people doing things this way? You

00:55:45.920 --> 00:55:50.000
[Guest]: know, why is this man driving with his lights on? We forget that there's a good reason why

00:55:50.000 --> 00:55:53.680
[Guest]: they're doing it. That's the way it is. That's the way they've been. And if you want to drive

00:55:53.680 --> 00:55:58.040
[Guest]: change, the idea is not to try and say, you know what, just switch off all your lights,

00:55:58.040 --> 00:56:03.760
[Guest]: but to try and understand why do we do things the way we do. And I also feel eventually

00:56:03.760 --> 00:56:09.600
[Guest]: that organizations have been built in such a way that if there is a problem, it gets

00:56:09.600 --> 00:56:14.640
[Guest]: thrown out of the system. And that's what a good organization will do. It does not allow

00:56:14.640 --> 00:56:20.080
[Guest]: this foreign body or this virus to stay for too long. There will be a bunch of antibodies

00:56:20.080 --> 00:56:24.440
[Guest]: that will come in and fight that virus and throw it out. Maybe that's how good organizations

00:56:24.440 --> 00:56:30.120
[Guest]: are built. Maybe that's what we all need to try and do to try and get it right.

00:56:30.120 --> 00:56:33.680
[Guest]: One last point, Amit, which is a big one, I think is around this whole idea of power

00:56:33.680 --> 00:56:39.360
[Guest]: corrupting. And I think that's a real risk. And that's something that I think we all need

00:56:39.360 --> 00:56:43.480
[Guest]: to guard against. And we need to find systems and processes within an organization where

00:56:43.480 --> 00:56:49.200
[Guest]: this gets called out. There are some checks and balances in place to ensure that behavior,

00:56:49.200 --> 00:56:54.480
[Guest]: which is not right, is called out. And I think the mistake organizations make is to condone

00:56:54.480 --> 00:57:00.160
[Guest]: this behavior early on and say, it's all right, because, you know, he's such a powerful sales

00:57:00.160 --> 00:57:04.080
[Guest]: guy. He gets, you know, he's beating his targets every month. Oh, my goodness. He has such

00:57:04.080 --> 00:57:07.960
[Guest]: fabulous relationships with those key accounts. If he goes away, those accounts will go away

00:57:07.960 --> 00:57:15.280
[Guest]: with him. And we then start to condone behavior, which is clearly not right. And then we expect

00:57:15.280 --> 00:57:18.480
[Guest]: that when this person becomes senior, then the person will change. And the person just

00:57:18.480 --> 00:57:22.120
[Guest]: thinks that, hey, if I could get away with it as a junior person, sure, this is the way

00:57:22.120 --> 00:57:25.640
[Guest]: of the world. I will get away with it. The other challenge you have in organizations

00:57:25.640 --> 00:57:30.800
[Guest]: is people tend to follow the leader. And therefore, you will find in an organization, if the leader

00:57:30.800 --> 00:57:37.960
[Guest]: is this abusive, short-tempered, foul-mouthed person, young managers start modeling themselves

00:57:37.960 --> 00:57:41.800
[Guest]: on that. They think that's the way to succeed in this organization. And you will find them

00:57:41.800 --> 00:57:47.040
[Guest]: being disrespectful of other people, vendors, partners, consultants. And you suddenly realize

00:57:47.040 --> 00:57:51.080
[Guest]: that there's a problem over here. And very often the problem, the rot starts at the top

00:57:51.080 --> 00:57:54.720
[Guest]: and it's the culture that flows from there. And that's something else that, you know,

00:57:54.720 --> 00:57:59.320
[Amit Varma]: maybe organizations need to try and set right. In your book, you've given lots of examples

00:57:59.320 --> 00:58:03.440
[Amit Varma]: of leaders who've led from the front very well. Like there is this HLL person you describe

00:58:03.440 --> 00:58:07.280
[Amit Varma]: who visits a small village and they're looking at products in a store and there is a tin

00:58:07.280 --> 00:58:12.120
[Amit Varma]: of dalda that has dust all over it. And he takes out his own white handkerchief and he

00:58:12.120 --> 00:58:17.200
[Amit Varma]: cleans that little bit of dust. And you've given a bunch of examples like that. But just

00:58:17.200 --> 00:58:21.400
[Amit Varma]: now when you were speaking so eloquently about the dangers of power corrupting, about, you

00:58:21.400 --> 00:58:25.000
[Amit Varma]: know, leaders getting away with stuff when they were juniors, and therefore those bad

00:58:25.000 --> 00:58:29.440
[Amit Varma]: practices carrying on with them, and then everybody looking at them as an example, you

00:58:29.440 --> 00:58:33.320
[Amit Varma]: said it with such conviction that it seemed that those are things you've come across in

00:58:33.320 --> 00:58:38.240
[Amit Varma]: your own career. So without naming names or companies or whatever, have you been in situations

00:58:38.240 --> 00:58:42.360
[Amit Varma]: where you have seen that happening, where you faced a kind of dilemma that do I just

00:58:42.360 --> 00:58:48.320
[Amit Varma]: get on with my own career or do I try to do something about this? And which is more widespread

00:58:48.320 --> 00:58:54.800
[Amit Varma]: these kind of bad toxic leaders who are engaged in this constant, seemingly ubiquitous political

00:58:54.800 --> 00:58:59.280
[Amit Varma]: struggle to get ahead within a company or the kind of inspirational leader you speak

00:58:59.280 --> 00:59:03.760
[Amit Varma]: about who sets a culture by example from the top?

00:59:03.760 --> 00:59:10.240
[Guest]: Again, it might just be the optimist in me speaking, but I think that this toxic bad

00:59:10.240 --> 00:59:17.800
[Guest]: leader is really a relic of the past, is probably not quite the norm anymore. I think there

00:59:17.800 --> 00:59:21.600
[Guest]: are two or three things happening. One, there are no hiding places. Earlier, perhaps you

00:59:21.600 --> 00:59:25.680
[Guest]: could get away with some of this stuff. And, you know, today, if you put your hand in the

00:59:25.680 --> 00:59:30.440
[Guest]: till, you're going to be caught before you do it. And I've seen this. I've seen this

00:59:30.440 --> 00:59:34.860
[Guest]: in the sense that, you know, I've come across situations where perhaps there have been accusations

00:59:34.860 --> 00:59:38.280
[Guest]: of people being in it and they've been found to be true, that there were people who are

00:59:38.280 --> 00:59:42.560
[Guest]: making a mistake. But I think that the strength of the organization has got to be in the fact

00:59:42.560 --> 00:59:49.080
[Guest]: that if it comes to light, action is taken. The bigger problem is not that somebody's

00:59:49.080 --> 00:59:55.540
[Guest]: got his hand in the till, but that it is allowed to continue. That I think is the bigger problem.

00:59:55.540 --> 01:00:00.000
[Guest]: So something I've learned and struggled with, I'll give you an example. There was a situation

01:00:00.000 --> 01:00:05.200
[Guest]: in a business where somebody had fudged an expense statement. And it was like some, I

01:00:05.200 --> 01:00:12.360
[Guest]: think, 80 rupees spent on taxi fare to go from place A to place B, where the controller

01:00:12.360 --> 01:00:16.640
[Guest]: in the business said that, actually, I gave that person a lift in my car. So they couldn't

01:00:16.640 --> 01:00:22.160
[Guest]: have spent 80 bucks on a cab. And this became a bit of an issue. And here's this person

01:00:22.160 --> 01:00:29.080
[Guest]: who was doing very well for us, you know, good colleague, nice person. And I didn't

01:00:29.080 --> 01:00:34.520
[Guest]: think this called for the person to be sacked. But my boss insisted that we sack the person.

01:00:34.520 --> 01:00:37.960
[Guest]: And we actually ended up sacking the person. So I protested a little bit. And then of course,

01:00:37.960 --> 01:00:41.640
[Guest]: my boss was horrified that I might even protest it. But I think I learned a lesson there,

01:00:41.640 --> 01:00:49.120
[Guest]: that if you let this pass, you're setting the wrong example. And now it's no longer

01:00:49.120 --> 01:00:56.080
[Guest]: about was it 80 rupees or was it 8 crore? If it's wrong, it's wrong. And sometimes you

01:00:56.080 --> 01:01:02.680
[Guest]: need to take these hard decisions just to get the message across that that's the organization,

01:01:02.680 --> 01:01:07.680
[Guest]: that's the culture. Now, I think that's, again, a good one. And I've seen, I've been in organizations

01:01:07.680 --> 01:01:14.920
[Guest]: where fairly senior people have been asked to have been let go of almost overnight because

01:01:14.920 --> 01:01:21.280
[Guest]: they did something which violated the code of conduct. Now, it doesn't necessarily mean

01:01:21.280 --> 01:01:26.120
[Guest]: that that person was all bad. And it's not as if the person was a complete rogue or a

01:01:26.120 --> 01:01:30.480
[Guest]: villain. It's just that in a moment of weakness, maybe the person has done the wrong thing.

01:01:30.480 --> 01:01:34.200
[Guest]: But I think organizations, they need to set an example to say, if it's the wrong thing,

01:01:34.200 --> 01:01:39.760
[Guest]: it has no place over here. Too bad. We need to set an example. Out you go. That I think

01:01:39.760 --> 01:01:45.000
[Guest]: is what will help us to ensure that organizations stay on track. And this is where I'm now coming

01:01:45.000 --> 01:01:51.360
[Guest]: to that in the good old days, maybe there was a little more of this hierarchy. A boss was all

01:01:51.360 --> 01:01:57.400
[Guest]: powerful. I still remember joining a business where, you know, I commented on a car. I just

01:01:57.400 --> 01:02:00.600
[Guest]: got into the business and I looked at my factory manager and I said, you have a nice car there.

01:02:00.600 --> 01:02:04.640
[Guest]: And he said, you know, actually, the previous boss gave it to him. Now, the previous boss

01:02:04.640 --> 01:02:08.680
[Guest]: didn't give it to him. The organization gave it to him because he earned it. He deserved it.

01:02:08.680 --> 01:02:14.160
[Guest]: But this feeling that previous boss gave it to me, my boss gave it to me, my boss is all

01:02:14.160 --> 01:02:20.840
[Guest]: powerful. I think that also caused a few problems for us where everything the boss did was all right.

01:02:20.840 --> 01:02:25.560
[Guest]: So if the boss made, you know, did a few of the things which are not all correct, let it go,

01:02:25.560 --> 01:02:31.680
[Guest]: let it pass. That has changed, I think, today, increasingly in organizations. And I use Suman

01:02:31.680 --> 01:02:34.720
[Guest]: Sinha as a great example because when I used to work with him in Hindustan, he was sir,

01:02:34.720 --> 01:02:39.680
[Guest]: he was Mr. Sinha. And then you move to Pepsi a few years later and he's Suman. And even the

01:02:39.680 --> 01:02:44.960
[Guest]: truck driver calls him Suman, you know, so that's just a culture change. But I think it's so important

01:02:44.960 --> 01:02:50.560
[Guest]: for you to have a situation where the boss is not sir, God, he's not God, he's just another person.

01:02:50.560 --> 01:02:54.240
[Guest]: And we need to be able to tell him if there's a problem. And I don't know if you saw that little

01:02:54.240 --> 01:02:59.600
[Guest]: news item, I think a couple of days back, where Air India Express have said that the pilot will

01:02:59.600 --> 01:03:05.040
[Guest]: not be called sir in the cockpit. And the whole idea here is that they found that from one of

01:03:05.040 --> 01:03:07.920
[Guest]: those accidents that they might have, one of the several accidents that Air India Express might

01:03:07.920 --> 01:03:13.760
[Guest]: have had, that the problem was that the co-pilot is deferring to the captain and is so respectful

01:03:13.760 --> 01:03:18.160
[Guest]: that when the captain is making a mistake, the co-pilot is not calling it out. Because,

01:03:18.160 --> 01:03:22.080
[Guest]: sir, if you don't mind, sir, would you mind considering that you are actually losing

01:03:22.080 --> 01:03:27.440
[Guest]: altitude is not the best way to say it, saying, Bhaga, we are in trouble, do something, right?

01:03:27.440 --> 01:03:33.600
[Guest]: And I think having a culture which allows us to create more equals, to break the hierarchy,

01:03:33.600 --> 01:03:38.400
[Guest]: to call out bad behavior. And I think increasingly across organizations,

01:03:39.120 --> 01:03:46.320
[Guest]: things like having a hotline or having an ombudsman or having systems in place,

01:03:46.320 --> 01:03:49.520
[Guest]: where if you have a problem, you can call it out, which didn't exist earlier.

01:03:49.520 --> 01:03:56.240
[Guest]: So my submission would be, I don't think that the corporate world is full of toxic, bad apples.

01:03:57.120 --> 01:04:02.080
[Guest]: And if anything, it's gotten a lot better now with a new bunch of people coming into work,

01:04:02.080 --> 01:04:04.320
[Guest]: and indeed more systems and processes coming into play.

01:04:05.680 --> 01:04:09.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and that's a that's a wonderful story about your colleague with his hand in the till,

01:04:09.600 --> 01:04:13.520
[Amit Varma]: as it were, over the taxi journey. And the moment you said that story, I said, okay,

01:04:13.520 --> 01:04:17.760
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I would just sack him no matter who it is. And that's the call that your boss took.

01:04:17.760 --> 01:04:23.120
[Amit Varma]: And it reminds me of this old story by, I don't know who, this is probably apocryphal,

01:04:23.120 --> 01:04:26.960
[Amit Varma]: no matter who it is about. But I think it's probably George Bernard Shaw, therefore,

01:04:26.960 --> 01:04:31.600
[Amit Varma]: because most apocryphal stories are about him, or Oscar Wilde, whoever, yeah,

01:04:31.600 --> 01:04:35.680
[Amit Varma]: one of these two where this person asked a lady at a party that will you sleep with me for a million

01:04:35.680 --> 01:04:40.000
[Amit Varma]: dollars? And she said, a million dollars, you know, taking it as a thought experiment and said,

01:04:40.000 --> 01:04:45.120
[Amit Varma]: yes. So he said that, you know, will you sleep with me for $1? And she says, what do you think

01:04:45.120 --> 01:04:48.880
[Amit Varma]: I am? And he says, I think we've already established that now we are just haggling

01:04:48.880 --> 01:04:54.080
[Amit Varma]: over the price. And it therefore strikes me that this is, you know, this case of,

01:04:54.080 --> 01:04:58.640
[Amit Varma]: you know, an 80 rupee taxi voucher is exactly the same thing. It's a principle that matters

01:04:58.640 --> 01:05:02.800
[Amit Varma]: that today if some guy is willing to do something unethical for 80 bucks,

01:05:02.800 --> 01:05:08.160
[Amit Varma]: tomorrow he'll do it for 80 crore bucks. So you have to sort of set your culture there.

01:05:08.160 --> 01:05:15.680
[Guest]: Yeah, but here's where I think it matters where you manage, you know, what your early years are.

01:05:15.680 --> 01:05:20.640
[Guest]: And I think sometimes it's a privilege to be able to work with a good boss or a good organization

01:05:20.640 --> 01:05:25.760
[Guest]: because you learn these lessons early. And I dare say there are several organizations where you

01:05:25.760 --> 01:05:30.960
[Guest]: might say, oh, come on, it's only 80 rupees, right? You don't sack a person for that. And come on,

01:05:30.960 --> 01:05:34.000
[Guest]: you know, if that's the case, the whole organization will get sacked. For example,

01:05:34.000 --> 01:05:37.600
[Guest]: that's the kind of thinking that can happen. And I think I love it when you said, for instance,

01:05:37.600 --> 01:05:42.320
[Guest]: that for you, this was a no brainer, right? You said if it's 80 bucks or 800 doesn't matter,

01:05:42.320 --> 01:05:48.960
[Guest]: the person goes. And I think getting that value in early in your career is really what makes a

01:05:48.960 --> 01:05:54.480
[Guest]: difference. If you grew up in a culture, in an organization where it's all right, I think this

01:05:54.480 --> 01:05:58.640
[Guest]: can become a problem. And I often find this, Amit, when I speak to corporates, I often,

01:05:59.520 --> 01:06:03.120
[Guest]: if I feel that there's, you know, if one of the things they want to talk about is this whole

01:06:03.120 --> 01:06:09.360
[Guest]: thing about integrity and culture, I will often use an example where I will talk about what do

01:06:09.360 --> 01:06:14.720
[Guest]: you do when you see a traffic light? If the traffic light is red, what happens? And everybody

01:06:14.720 --> 01:06:19.200
[Guest]: says we'll stop. And I say, what do you do when it's red? Everybody says we'll stop. And then I

01:06:19.200 --> 01:06:24.000
[Guest]: say, but you know, are there situations where you've seen people not stopping? Or you yourself,

01:06:24.000 --> 01:06:29.440
[Guest]: have you seen that it's a red light and you've gone on? And suddenly that entire room which said

01:06:29.440 --> 01:06:35.360
[Guest]: I stop when I see a red light will now say, yeah, if I'm in a hurry, yeah, if there's no traffic,

01:06:35.360 --> 01:06:40.400
[Guest]: if it's late in the night, if there's no cop, right? And then I ask the question,

01:06:40.400 --> 01:06:43.840
[Guest]: if you had a chance to steal a million dollars, would you steal from your company? And the answer

01:06:43.840 --> 01:06:47.280
[Guest]: is everybody says, no, no, no, no, I wouldn't. And then you ask them, what if it's the middle

01:06:47.280 --> 01:06:55.520
[Guest]: of the night? What if the CFO is not looking? And suddenly people realize that, look, where

01:06:55.520 --> 01:07:00.160
[Guest]: is this going? And I think the rule is that if you see a red light, stop. It doesn't matter whether

01:07:00.160 --> 01:07:03.520
[Guest]: there's a cop or no cop. It doesn't matter what time of the day it is. It doesn't matter that

01:07:03.520 --> 01:07:07.680
[Guest]: everybody else is doing it. None of that is relevant. Yeah. So I try and make this point

01:07:07.680 --> 01:07:12.080
[Guest]: to say that, you know, whether it's eight bucks, 80 bucks or 8 million, get the principle right,

01:07:12.080 --> 01:07:15.920
[Guest]: and you will never make a mistake. You'll never find yourself in trouble. And I've often found

01:07:15.920 --> 01:07:20.880
[Guest]: when I say this to some organizations, right, they almost look at me as saying,

01:07:21.920 --> 01:07:25.360
[Guest]: from which planet is this person coming? He doesn't understand the reality of our world,

01:07:25.360 --> 01:07:31.040
[Guest]: because, you know, how can you work in this world without greasing a few palms, without

01:07:31.040 --> 01:07:34.720
[Guest]: bribing that purchase guy in that other organization, without doing something which

01:07:34.720 --> 01:07:40.960
[Guest]: is incorrect? So I think that's still a challenge, but change will happen. Change is slow, but it

01:07:40.960 --> 01:07:46.800
[Guest]: needs to happen. And I'm a big believer that hey, eventually, that's what should win. So I read about

01:07:46.800 --> 01:07:51.040
[Amit Varma]: what you just said in the traffic light chapter in your book, and I have a slight kind of quibble

01:07:51.040 --> 01:07:54.560
[Amit Varma]: with that. But before that, a couple of clarifications. And one clarification, of course,

01:07:54.560 --> 01:08:00.560
[Amit Varma]: is that, like that apocryphal story implies that that woman was somehow doing something wrong and

01:08:00.560 --> 01:08:05.440
[Amit Varma]: Shaw or Wilde or whoever it was that caught her out. I don't think there is anything wrong with,

01:08:05.440 --> 01:08:08.640
[Amit Varma]: you know, making a voluntary decision to sleep with someone for money, for example,

01:08:08.640 --> 01:08:14.720
[Amit Varma]: that's just one of those traditional moralistic notions that we have. I think sex work is as

01:08:14.720 --> 01:08:19.840
[Amit Varma]: legitimate a profession as a podcasting or writing. The other clarification is that when I was in my

01:08:19.840 --> 01:08:24.320
[Amit Varma]: early 20s, I might well have, you know, made a taxi voucher like that myself. Because I think

01:08:24.320 --> 01:08:28.240
[Amit Varma]: at that time, it was just everything was chalta hai and these are small things and what difference

01:08:28.240 --> 01:08:34.000
[Amit Varma]: does it make? So it is convenient for me today when I don't work for anyone to sit and kind of

01:08:34.000 --> 01:08:38.560
[Amit Varma]: make these judgments. But what do you do in the moment? Do people get second chances in life? And

01:08:38.560 --> 01:08:43.120
[Amit Varma]: all of that? I think those are larger questions. So I don't want to be too definitive about this.

01:08:43.120 --> 01:08:47.520
[Amit Varma]: But here's my disagreement about the traffic light and ceiling a million dollars thing

01:08:47.520 --> 01:08:51.680
[Amit Varma]: that the argument with traffic lights and I make this argument often about say,

01:08:51.680 --> 01:08:56.720
[Amit Varma]: speed limits at the early ceiling, which are 80 km but the convention is everybody goes above that

01:08:56.720 --> 01:09:02.400
[Amit Varma]: and it's perfectly safe and the road is empty to go above 80 km on on that particular ceiling

01:09:02.400 --> 01:09:09.520
[Amit Varma]: is that many of these laws, so to say, don't actually make that much rational sense,

01:09:09.520 --> 01:09:13.280
[Amit Varma]: you know, there is an emergent order, which is a conventional way in which people do things,

01:09:13.280 --> 01:09:16.800
[Amit Varma]: which doesn't harm anyone else, which has evolved, like a particular speed at which

01:09:16.800 --> 01:09:22.160
[Amit Varma]: people go through a road, and there is a sort of an imposed order. Now, where in my mind,

01:09:22.160 --> 01:09:26.400
[Amit Varma]: breaking a traffic light at midnight when there is nobody there is different from stealing a

01:09:26.400 --> 01:09:31.760
[Amit Varma]: million dollars is this, that when you break a traffic light at midnight, when there is absolutely

01:09:31.760 --> 01:09:37.040
[Amit Varma]: nobody there, you're not harming anybody else, you're not infringing on someone's rights, right,

01:09:37.040 --> 01:09:42.000
[Amit Varma]: that convention exists, traffic lights exist for a reason, and people follow it during the day.

01:09:42.000 --> 01:09:46.080
[Amit Varma]: But at this moment in time, it doesn't harm anyone, where you're not doing something morally

01:09:46.080 --> 01:09:50.400
[Amit Varma]: wrong by breaking a traffic light when the entire road is empty. However, you are obviously doing

01:09:50.400 --> 01:09:54.720
[Amit Varma]: something morally wrong by taking a million dollars, even if you'll get away with it,

01:09:54.720 --> 01:09:58.720
[Amit Varma]: like you correctly pointed out in your chapter values are basically what you do when no one's

01:09:58.720 --> 01:10:04.640
[Amit Varma]: looking, which is a striking way of thinking about it. And this is again, on the one hand,

01:10:04.640 --> 01:10:09.840
[Amit Varma]: on the other hand, kind of thing, because at one level, I'm saying that no, this comparison

01:10:09.840 --> 01:10:14.560
[Amit Varma]: doesn't make sense, because traffic light, I can understand. In fact, I was in New York a few years

01:10:14.560 --> 01:10:18.720
[Amit Varma]: ago, and I was staying at New Jersey with my good friend Yazad Jal, who's been on the show,

01:10:18.720 --> 01:10:23.520
[Amit Varma]: and I was driving his car at night, because I was like, let me see how it feels to drive in America.

01:10:23.520 --> 01:10:27.440
[Amit Varma]: And I broke a traffic light because there was no one on the road. And Yazad just, you know,

01:10:27.440 --> 01:10:32.160
[Amit Varma]: completely panicked and of course, got billed for it and all of that. So I didn't know the convention

01:10:32.160 --> 01:10:37.680
[Amit Varma]: in that place. And the Bombay guy in me is just saying, you know, there's no one on the road.

01:10:37.680 --> 01:10:42.640
[Amit Varma]: But the other way of looking at it is that at a normative level, if you just follow all rules,

01:10:42.640 --> 01:10:46.720
[Amit Varma]: if you just follow all conventions, it's a good thing to do at a normative level,

01:10:46.720 --> 01:10:52.720
[Amit Varma]: don't seek out exceptions and all of that, just at a normative level. If you remain on the straight

01:10:52.720 --> 01:10:56.640
[Amit Varma]: and narrow, then you can never make a mistake. So I just thought I'll share this kind of

01:10:56.640 --> 01:11:00.560
[Amit Varma]: contradictory notion and this argument about your traffic light metaphor.

01:11:01.840 --> 01:11:06.320
[Guest]: A fair point. And this is not to suggest for a moment that I've never jumped a red light.

01:11:06.320 --> 01:11:10.080
[Guest]: Okay. And but I would very confidently say that I wouldn't want to do the other part of what I

01:11:10.080 --> 01:11:16.000
[Guest]: might be talking about. But I've certainly the point I want to make here is about decide which

01:11:16.000 --> 01:11:20.960
[Guest]: are those red lights in your life that you want to really hold on to what's really important.

01:11:20.960 --> 01:11:27.200
[Guest]: And the point here is that no one suddenly steals $10 million from a business. No one suddenly goes

01:11:27.200 --> 01:11:33.840
[Guest]: to, you know, takes Nissan into where it went. And we've seen heroes in our lives who after a

01:11:33.840 --> 01:11:38.160
[Guest]: board meeting have gone and shared data or sensitive data and then found themselves in

01:11:38.160 --> 01:11:43.680
[Guest]: jail after having done some fantastic work all through their lives. And why does this happen?

01:11:43.680 --> 01:11:49.920
[Guest]: And my point over here is that it doesn't happen overnight. It happens because long back,

01:11:49.920 --> 01:11:54.320
[Guest]: long back, there was this red light that you didn't stop at. And what was the equivalent of

01:11:54.320 --> 01:12:00.720
[Guest]: that? And whether it's that if Volkswagen and what allowed a small factory engineer to tamper

01:12:00.720 --> 01:12:05.360
[Guest]: data, right? Because it was all right. It's a monthly report. How does it matter? It doesn't

01:12:05.360 --> 01:12:09.920
[Guest]: and to your point, it doesn't violate anybody else's rights. It didn't cause any harm to anyone

01:12:09.920 --> 01:12:16.480
[Guest]: else. But damn, it cost that company $50 billion or more because, you know, they tampered with

01:12:16.480 --> 01:12:21.760
[Guest]: pollution data, which was wrong, and they got caught out doing it. And my point here is, figure

01:12:21.760 --> 01:12:26.080
[Guest]: out what are those red lights in your life? What are those rules that you want to live by? What are

01:12:26.080 --> 01:12:31.920
[Guest]: those principles that you hold dear? And once you have that, try and ensure that you don't say it's

01:12:31.920 --> 01:12:39.760
[Guest]: okay. It's only today. Because that will take you down a slippery slope, I think, you know,

01:12:39.760 --> 01:12:44.960
[Amit Varma]: and that's really the point I want to make. Absolutely. Very wise words. I agree with that.

01:12:44.960 --> 01:12:49.680
[Amit Varma]: Another question about something that you haven't really addressed in your writings or your YouTube

01:12:49.680 --> 01:12:54.000
[Amit Varma]: talks or whatever that I haven't at least come across. But since we were talking about corporate

01:12:54.000 --> 01:13:00.400
[Amit Varma]: culture, and since I happen to mention me too, also, and one of the things that strikes me is

01:13:00.400 --> 01:13:07.440
[Amit Varma]: how so much corporate culture is sexist in very subtle ways, for example, air conditioning,

01:13:07.440 --> 01:13:12.080
[Amit Varma]: right? You know, the norms for what the air conditioning temperature was was set in the 50s,

01:13:12.080 --> 01:13:16.720
[Amit Varma]: where most people who worked in offices were men. And therefore, they were set at whatever level is

01:13:16.720 --> 01:13:21.920
[Amit Varma]: optimal for men and they're comfortable with. But the truth is that women's body temperature

01:13:21.920 --> 01:13:26.560
[Amit Varma]: are sort of modulated differently, and they feel colder, which is why it is incredibly common that

01:13:26.560 --> 01:13:31.200
[Amit Varma]: at a temperature where a man is comfortable, the woman will be feeling cold and putting a sweater

01:13:31.200 --> 01:13:37.440
[Amit Varma]: or a shawl around herself. And to me, this is also a great metaphor for everything in our society,

01:13:37.440 --> 01:13:43.440
[Amit Varma]: just the way that it's designed with men in mind and for the comfort of men. And I'm using it now

01:13:43.440 --> 01:13:49.600
[Amit Varma]: in a metaphorical sense as well, that, you know, a lot of women would say corporate culture might

01:13:49.600 --> 01:13:54.560
[Amit Varma]: be more open, you can take your boss's name by their first name and all of those things.

01:13:54.560 --> 01:14:00.400
[Amit Varma]: But this stuff remains, it's invisible, like one common complaint that women make, and I have seen

01:14:00.400 --> 01:14:05.120
[Amit Varma]: it for myself happening in this way, is that in a meeting where there are men and there are women,

01:14:05.120 --> 01:14:09.600
[Amit Varma]: and a woman will say something. And everybody will just listen, not react. And then a man will

01:14:09.600 --> 01:14:13.760
[Amit Varma]: say the same thing in different words. And everybody will be like, what an idea Amit,

01:14:13.760 --> 01:14:21.360
[Amit Varma]: kya bola hai, isko podcast dete hai, and so on. And a lot of this stuff, these invisible ways in

01:14:21.360 --> 01:14:27.840
[Amit Varma]: which cultures, not just corporate cultures, but around us are biased against women. These were

01:14:27.840 --> 01:14:33.360
[Amit Varma]: unseen to me. And over the last few years, maybe some of these layers have started peeling away,

01:14:33.360 --> 01:14:39.600
[Amit Varma]: and one starts trying to actually see what all of these are. Is this stuff that you notice during

01:14:39.600 --> 01:14:44.880
[Amit Varma]: your corporate time? Or, you know, in your corporate life rather? And is this stuff that

01:14:44.880 --> 01:14:49.920
[Amit Varma]: you wanted to do something about? Do you think that there are being things done about this?

01:14:49.920 --> 01:14:53.360
[Amit Varma]: What are the sort of barriers to this? What are your impressions?

01:14:54.320 --> 01:15:00.720
[Guest]: I think this is an area where things are changing very quickly, and not quickly enough. Over the

01:15:00.720 --> 01:15:07.920
[Guest]: last several years, the corporate world that I got into was still very, very different. And

01:15:07.920 --> 01:15:14.160
[Guest]: I think the problem with biases, like the sexist biases that we've had, is that we didn't realize

01:15:14.160 --> 01:15:18.880
[Guest]: it. We don't even realize that it happened. And I must tell you that around the time when

01:15:19.920 --> 01:15:27.200
[Guest]: I was a young sales manager in Hindustani, we hired women into sales management. There

01:15:27.200 --> 01:15:31.360
[Guest]: weren't too many women. There were like maybe a handful, two or three or four women who might have

01:15:31.360 --> 01:15:36.000
[Guest]: been management trainees in sales. So the thing was, if you hired a management trainee who was

01:15:36.000 --> 01:15:40.800
[Guest]: a woman into Hindustani, in those days, she would either end up in marketing, HR or finance,

01:15:40.800 --> 01:15:46.000
[Guest]: but not in sales. And the argument and the thinking would be stuff like, you know,

01:15:46.000 --> 01:15:49.360
[Guest]: how will you travel into those villages? How will you go and deal with the distributors?

01:15:49.360 --> 01:15:53.280
[Guest]: And you have to go and spend time in the evening with the sales guys. What will you do? And all

01:15:53.280 --> 01:15:59.120
[Guest]: of that. So I think there's, as you look back today, a load of rubbish. Okay. But I'm just

01:15:59.120 --> 01:16:05.360
[Guest]: trying to say that this was so deeply ingrained in minds and workplaces tended to be far more male

01:16:05.360 --> 01:16:10.560
[Guest]: dominated than they are today. And I think right from the time, if I look at the last 20 years or

01:16:10.560 --> 01:16:15.280
[Guest]: so, I think the world has changed dramatically and the corporate world is trying hard. Some

01:16:15.280 --> 01:16:19.360
[Guest]: companies more than others. And I certainly think PepsiCo, Unilever, great examples of

01:16:19.360 --> 01:16:25.200
[Guest]: trying to drive equality in the workplace. I also remember, and I hate to say it, but I remember how

01:16:25.200 --> 01:16:30.800
[Guest]: as men, we've often felt, oh my goodness, why are they doing this? You know, I remember very clearly

01:16:30.800 --> 01:16:34.960
[Guest]: a situation where we thought there was a friend of ours who was in line for the CFO's job.

01:16:35.760 --> 01:16:40.400
[Guest]: And the bad joke, and I can say it now that the bad joke was that, you know, we were trying to

01:16:40.400 --> 01:16:44.240
[Guest]: say that if he has to get that job, he has to change his sex because there's a great attempt

01:16:44.240 --> 01:16:49.920
[Guest]: to try and bring in a woman in that role. Now, I think this is just telling you how bad it was.

01:16:49.920 --> 01:16:54.320
[Guest]: And the fact that there is far more awareness, and I must say this, that I think the world has

01:16:54.320 --> 01:16:59.920
[Guest]: changed dramatically. And I know as I look at workplaces and policies, the conversation has

01:16:59.920 --> 01:17:05.360
[Guest]: shifted. I must tell you this, that I try very hard in everything that I'm doing to make sure

01:17:05.360 --> 01:17:10.560
[Guest]: that I'm not seeing him naturally. I try very hard to make sure that if I'm talking about a boss,

01:17:10.560 --> 01:17:15.520
[Guest]: I'm saying, and then she said, you know, and these are small things, but I think they all matter.

01:17:16.080 --> 01:17:20.640
[Guest]: And there are times when subconsciously I might, I might have made a statement. I'll give you an

01:17:20.640 --> 01:17:25.360
[Guest]: example. Not so long ago, I referred to something about doing something at work when I was trying

01:17:25.360 --> 01:17:31.760
[Guest]: to do something while the wife, and I said, while the wife was on Netflix, and I actually got a

01:17:31.760 --> 01:17:37.280
[Guest]: friend writing into me to say, not a good thing to say. You know, why are you assuming that it's

01:17:37.280 --> 01:17:40.480
[Guest]: only your wife who watches Netflix? Maybe a lot of men are watching Netflix through the day while

01:17:40.480 --> 01:17:44.880
[Guest]: the women are out there working and without realizing it, like I said, but I think the

01:17:44.880 --> 01:17:49.280
[Guest]: good news is, and I thought I saw a bit of that just now, Amit, I love the way you kind of came

01:17:49.280 --> 01:17:53.600
[Guest]: back on that Bernard Shaw joke, because that might've been funny 30 years ago. It's not so

01:17:53.600 --> 01:17:59.600
[Guest]: funny today, right? The world is changing. And I think we all need to acknowledge that. And,

01:18:00.160 --> 01:18:05.120
[Guest]: and I think there are lots of women out there in the workforce today who are driving that change.

01:18:05.120 --> 01:18:10.160
[Guest]: There are progressive organizations. You know, I think just having loo's reflecting the number

01:18:10.160 --> 01:18:14.000
[Guest]: of men and women there are, you know, very often you'll find organizations where there's like this

01:18:14.000 --> 01:18:17.600
[Guest]: one tiny room, which becomes a women's loo. And there's this massive place, which is the men's

01:18:17.600 --> 01:18:22.080
[Guest]: loo. Why? Because in the good old days, there were so many more men at work that needs to change.

01:18:22.080 --> 01:18:27.440
[Guest]: I think just the air conditioning, not a great example. I think just being respectful of what

01:18:27.440 --> 01:18:33.200
[Guest]: women might need, just being respectful of their needs like anybody else's. And also I think being

01:18:33.200 --> 01:18:38.080
[Guest]: sensitive to the differences and creating that sensitivity and calling it out and saying,

01:18:38.080 --> 01:18:44.400
[Guest]: it is not acceptable. I still see situations where there is a leader who will crack this

01:18:44.400 --> 01:18:50.320
[Guest]: not so okay joke, right? Especially in mixed company, it's not acceptable.

01:18:50.320 --> 01:18:52.880
[Guest]: And yet there'll be this nervous laughter around the room. And those people say,

01:18:52.880 --> 01:18:55.760
[Guest]: the boss has said it must laugh. And there'll be a woman sitting over there

01:18:55.760 --> 01:18:59.360
[Guest]: wondering what's going on here. And I think that will change. And that woman is changing

01:18:59.360 --> 01:19:04.080
[Guest]: the world and she's making sure that that boss doesn't get away with it. And I think this is a

01:19:04.080 --> 01:19:08.800
[Guest]: big change happening. And like I said, I think there's a lot that's happening. Is it enough?

01:19:08.800 --> 01:19:16.560
[Guest]: Maybe not. Certainly a lot more needs to be done, but I think it's such a deep rooted malaise.

01:19:16.560 --> 01:19:21.520
[Guest]: And I'd like to believe that particularly for some of us who've grown up in cities,

01:19:21.520 --> 01:19:27.200
[Guest]: who have been privileged to have women around us, spouses, daughters, friends, girlfriends,

01:19:27.200 --> 01:19:32.240
[Guest]: we've learned to respect them. And this is still different and challenging perhaps for a bunch of

01:19:32.240 --> 01:19:38.320
[Guest]: men coming into work from another part of our country, another part of society where it's still,

01:19:38.320 --> 01:19:42.480
[Guest]: you know, where women are not being respected. If you grew up in a home where your dad did not

01:19:42.480 --> 01:19:46.960
[Guest]: respect your mom, you will struggle with this, I think, in the early years of your life.

01:19:46.960 --> 01:19:52.800
[Guest]: And I think we just need to kind of enable that change and recognize that in this continuum,

01:19:52.800 --> 01:19:58.800
[Guest]: we are all perhaps at different points. The destination is clear, but we are at different

01:19:58.800 --> 01:20:02.080
[Guest]: points in that journey. And we just need to try and say, how can we take people along and make

01:20:02.080 --> 01:20:07.520
[Guest]: sure that we're making it easier for the other half of the world? So, you know, taking off from

01:20:07.520 --> 01:20:12.960
[Amit Varma]: your point about this being a deep rooted malaise, which I sort of agree with, there's another very

01:20:12.960 --> 01:20:18.640
[Amit Varma]: nuanced point that your book makes, which I find relevant to this. Because while we were talking

01:20:18.640 --> 01:20:24.560
[Amit Varma]: about this, it also struck me that this sexism doesn't come from malice, it comes from blindness,

01:20:24.560 --> 01:20:29.440
[Amit Varma]: that people simply aren't aware. There are jokes I would have cracked 20 years ago, which I would

01:20:29.440 --> 01:20:34.640
[Amit Varma]: not crack today, or that might reflexively come into my head now, but I have that filter, which

01:20:34.640 --> 01:20:40.240
[Amit Varma]: stops me from actually saying it. And in your book, you speak, of course, about Hanlon's razor,

01:20:40.240 --> 01:20:44.320
[Amit Varma]: which I keep talking about all the time in the context of politics, which is never attribute to

01:20:44.320 --> 01:20:50.480
[Amit Varma]: malice, what can be adequately explained by stupidity. And or in this case, the guy just

01:20:50.480 --> 01:20:55.120
[Amit Varma]: doesn't know the guy has just never experienced this way of thinking, he doesn't realize that

01:20:55.120 --> 01:21:01.120
[Amit Varma]: it's kind of wrong. Like a friend of mine runs this mailing list where one of the guiding principles

01:21:01.120 --> 01:21:05.920
[Amit Varma]: there is assume goodwill. And the idea being someone says something that you don't agree with,

01:21:05.920 --> 01:21:11.360
[Amit Varma]: don't assume they're coming from a bad place that they're malicious, you know, one, they may be

01:21:11.360 --> 01:21:16.240
[Amit Varma]: ignorant about something two, they may be right and you may be wrong. And just assume at least

01:21:16.240 --> 01:21:22.240
[Amit Varma]: that the intention is good. And then you can explore that further. But leaving that aside,

01:21:22.240 --> 01:21:25.840
[Amit Varma]: you know, your optimism is quite lovely. I haven't been in the corporate world for like a decade and

01:21:25.840 --> 01:21:31.280
[Amit Varma]: a half. So your optimism is sort of lovely to hear. Tell me now about I mean, we'll come back

01:21:31.280 --> 01:21:36.000
[Amit Varma]: to the principles in your book and the life lessons and all that a little later after the break,

01:21:36.000 --> 01:21:40.480
[Amit Varma]: but I want to go on with your personal journey for a moment. Take me through your corporate

01:21:40.480 --> 01:21:46.560
[Amit Varma]: journey. What was it like? Number one was a job something that you loved doing people think of

01:21:46.560 --> 01:21:51.200
[Amit Varma]: corporate jobs as Oh, it is drudgery and I have to do this and have to earn a living and I'm shifting

01:21:51.200 --> 01:21:56.240
[Amit Varma]: city so many times. In your case, was it something that you love doing? And a supplementary question

01:21:56.240 --> 01:22:02.640
[Amit Varma]: to that would be that were you all the time getting meta about your job and formulating

01:22:02.640 --> 01:22:07.200
[Amit Varma]: all your learnings from there because what you've done after the corporate part of your career ended

01:22:07.200 --> 01:22:12.720
[Amit Varma]: is, you know, brought out all these learnings, you know, from your career, and I would say improved

01:22:12.720 --> 01:22:17.200
[Amit Varma]: at least 1000s of lives by sharing them with the world and by teaching people. But what's that

01:22:17.200 --> 01:22:22.640
[Amit Varma]: process of actually formulating those lessons, those guidelines, those principles for yourself?

01:22:22.640 --> 01:22:25.760
[Amit Varma]: Was it a process that was on while you were in your corporate journey?

01:22:27.120 --> 01:22:31.840
[Guest]: It's hard to, it's hard to be able to put a finger and say, yeah, that's that it was always the case.

01:22:31.840 --> 01:22:36.080
[Guest]: And I completely buy into your point about how some of these things work so well, when you look

01:22:36.080 --> 01:22:40.400
[Guest]: back and you can connect the dots and say, that's how it worked for you. But what was true, Amit,

01:22:40.400 --> 01:22:47.760
[Guest]: is, is perhaps two things. First, I actually feel that what is it about that little boy from Jaipur?

01:22:47.760 --> 01:22:51.600
[Guest]: How did he manage to kind of, you know, get into these funny roles and do reasonably,

01:22:51.600 --> 01:22:58.320
[Guest]: reasonably important enough work or in in seemingly important roles? How did this happen?

01:22:58.320 --> 01:23:03.040
[Guest]: And I think the answer to that could possibly be that, you know, I kept learning a little bit

01:23:03.040 --> 01:23:08.000
[Guest]: from other people, kept getting looking at other people and saying, wow, how does this work here?

01:23:08.000 --> 01:23:11.600
[Guest]: What can I learn from this person? And I think that that has been a common thread, perhaps in

01:23:11.600 --> 01:23:18.080
[Guest]: my life where I have been maybe a bit of that optimist slash positive guy also where I might

01:23:18.080 --> 01:23:21.840
[Guest]: see someone who might be having lots of other problems here, but I'll still try and figure

01:23:21.840 --> 01:23:25.440
[Guest]: despite those problems, he's doing something, something is right here. So let's try and figure

01:23:25.440 --> 01:23:30.400
[Guest]: what's right. What can we learn from this person? And so maybe I kept looking at it in that sense.

01:23:30.400 --> 01:23:34.880
[Guest]: The second thing that happened was that very early in my life, I perhaps figured that

01:23:34.880 --> 01:23:39.440
[Guest]: without realizing it and without giving it a term or a label, I figured that stories are powerful.

01:23:40.960 --> 01:23:47.040
[Guest]: And that being able to use stories or tell stories can help you to get your message across.

01:23:47.840 --> 01:23:54.160
[Guest]: So as a young area sales manager running a monthly meeting with eight salespeople in a small hotel

01:23:54.160 --> 01:23:56.800
[Guest]: somewhere, well, you know, you can keep telling them,

01:23:56.800 --> 01:24:01.680
[Guest]: you know, have to get our target. It's looking impossible, but, you know, we will get there.

01:24:01.680 --> 01:24:05.280
[Guest]: You can keep saying it, nothing happens. But maybe if you can tell them a little story,

01:24:06.240 --> 01:24:11.760
[Guest]: suddenly the mood in the room seems to lift. And then later that night when everyone's having a

01:24:11.760 --> 01:24:17.120
[Guest]: beer, suddenly that story gets referenced again. And you realize that, you know, you had spent so

01:24:17.120 --> 01:24:22.640
[Guest]: much time trying to tell them, no one seemed to get it. And now you've told them a story and that

01:24:22.640 --> 01:24:30.880
[Guest]: has stuck with people. So I think this tendency or this habit of then using stories started to

01:24:30.880 --> 01:24:35.280
[Guest]: become something that I would do. And maybe that in some ways is, if I was to look at my career

01:24:35.280 --> 01:24:38.720
[Guest]: and say, how do I remember some of those little things, maybe that's, that might have helped

01:24:38.720 --> 01:24:44.160
[Guest]: to make that happen. It also kind of moved into another part of my life. Very often I would read

01:24:44.160 --> 01:24:50.720
[Guest]: an entire book and after finishing, you know, 340 pages, I would remember this one little story

01:24:50.720 --> 01:24:55.840
[Guest]: tucked away somewhere, which is a story that I said, wow, that was very cool. So there is a lot

01:24:55.840 --> 01:25:01.600
[Guest]: of good stuff in those 350 pages, but that little story would stick out for me. My kids would often

01:25:01.600 --> 01:25:06.480
[Guest]: say this, that they know what I'm reading by the story I'm telling them at dinner time, you know,

01:25:06.480 --> 01:25:10.160
[Guest]: and I would probably, I can't wait. I have to tell you that, you know what, I read this really

01:25:10.160 --> 01:25:13.920
[Guest]: cool thing and it still happens. I would have come across something interesting and I'll want to

01:25:13.920 --> 01:25:18.480
[Guest]: share it in as much as I talked about Air India Express and, you know, saying that don't call sir.

01:25:18.480 --> 01:25:23.920
[Guest]: I just saw it and I said, hey, this is such a cool story. And maybe that's really what has kind

01:25:23.920 --> 01:25:29.600
[Guest]: of stayed with me through this entire process to say that there are lessons that we can learn.

01:25:29.600 --> 01:25:38.080
[Guest]: And I, how do I put it? I think I was lucky. I was lucky that I got to work in some reasonably

01:25:38.080 --> 01:25:42.480
[Guest]: good business. I'm guessing if I had worked in a business where values weren't so important,

01:25:42.480 --> 01:25:47.200
[Guest]: where the culture was politicized, where they were favorites and people were doing all kinds

01:25:47.200 --> 01:25:50.160
[Guest]: of funny things, maybe I would have been a different person. I may not have been the person

01:25:50.160 --> 01:25:55.200
[Guest]: I am. I might have struggled with it perhaps, but I may not have learned so much. And because I

01:25:55.200 --> 01:26:00.640
[Guest]: learned some of these things, I've often felt, hey, sometimes you see lots of bright people

01:26:01.360 --> 01:26:06.880
[Guest]: getting it wrong, you know, and I think, wow, I wish they also would get to, you know,

01:26:06.880 --> 01:26:11.040
[Guest]: learn some of this stuff. And maybe that's really what gets me going to say, perhaps there's a

01:26:11.040 --> 01:26:15.360
[Guest]: lesson that I might have learned, which can help someone else. You know, it may be a tiny lesson.

01:26:15.360 --> 01:26:19.040
[Amit Varma]: I'm totally with you on the value of stories. Like I keep telling my,

01:26:19.040 --> 01:26:22.640
[Amit Varma]: sort of the participants of my writing course as well, that, you know, go for the concrete,

01:26:22.640 --> 01:26:26.640
[Amit Varma]: the abstract to take care, but go for the concrete. And that really makes an impact.

01:26:26.640 --> 01:26:29.920
[Amit Varma]: At which point I am going to ask you to go for the concrete. Like at one point,

01:26:29.920 --> 01:26:33.200
[Amit Varma]: you mentioned the hypothetical example, the sales meeting chal raha hai,

01:26:33.200 --> 01:26:37.440
[Amit Varma]: and I tell them a story and it comes back to me. Do you remember any such interesting story,

01:26:37.440 --> 01:26:41.440
[Amit Varma]: which you, you know, told back in the day where you were actually a sales manager that, you know,

01:26:41.440 --> 01:26:49.760
[Guest]: that worked? Yeah. So I'll tell you a story that we used many years ago. So I used to be in PepsiCo.

01:26:49.760 --> 01:26:55.440
[Guest]: Okay. And soft drinks was a very seasonal business. So if you were in UP, for example,

01:26:55.440 --> 01:27:00.960
[Guest]: dukaane band ho jati hain, it's cold and they really start opening in after Holi. So March,

01:27:00.960 --> 01:27:07.280
[Guest]: April is when the season will start. So Jan, Feb, March is a washout as far as soft drink

01:27:07.280 --> 01:27:13.200
[Guest]: sales are concerned. And as a company, I remember the boss, you know, we had decided that what can

01:27:13.200 --> 01:27:18.560
[Guest]: we do to try and flatten seasonality, which meant, can we do something to sell more soft drinks in

01:27:18.560 --> 01:27:23.920
[Guest]: Jan, Feb, March? Now, given that our targets and our accounting year was Jan, December,

01:27:24.560 --> 01:27:28.320
[Guest]: it was a terrible sight to see that the first three months you were doing nothing,

01:27:28.320 --> 01:27:32.320
[Guest]: you were losing money because, you know, your costs were all in place, not getting enough

01:27:32.320 --> 01:27:37.760
[Guest]: revenue. So we said, what can we do to sell more soft drinks in that first quarter of the year?

01:27:38.400 --> 01:27:44.880
[Guest]: And therefore, I think the theme was to try and say, let's be fast off the block to get Jan,

01:27:44.880 --> 01:27:49.120
[Guest]: Feb, March off to a great start. And the way the company looked at it was to say that, you know

01:27:49.120 --> 01:27:52.400
[Guest]: what, let's get it off to a great start, Jan, Feb, March, we have an opportunity, let's make it

01:27:52.400 --> 01:27:56.960
[Guest]: happen. If you do that, if, you know, four can become 6%, six, eight percent, we are off to a

01:27:56.960 --> 01:28:01.760
[Guest]: great start, the year will be great. I don't think it was working too well. And that's when I, you

01:28:01.760 --> 01:28:06.080
[Guest]: know, I'm a bit of a cricket fan, so I came up with this whole thing about how in the good old

01:28:06.080 --> 01:28:13.760
[Guest]: days, in 50 overs cricket, the belief was that you start slowly, keep your wickets intact, and then,

01:28:13.760 --> 01:28:18.240
[Guest]: you know, you have the slog overs and then you start to say that that's when you start hitting,

01:28:18.240 --> 01:28:23.200
[Guest]: right? And I talked about how Jaisurya and Kaluvitarna actually changed that for us and

01:28:23.200 --> 01:28:28.640
[Guest]: Mark Greatbatch perhaps another level and how just changing the rules can catch your opposition

01:28:28.640 --> 01:28:32.080
[Guest]: by surprise, you can catch them off guard. And if he were to suddenly start doing stuff in Jan,

01:28:32.080 --> 01:28:37.120
[Guest]: Feb, March, just wake up to the opportunity that might be there. And suddenly we might discover

01:28:37.120 --> 01:28:42.400
[Guest]: that we've set a platform from which we can now launch into an even higher plane. And therefore,

01:28:42.400 --> 01:28:46.800
[Guest]: a little cricketing story actually got us off to saying that, you know what, Jan, Feb, March could

01:28:46.800 --> 01:28:54.640
[Guest]: be very different in a soft drinks calendar year. And it's not as if it became the norm and

01:28:54.640 --> 01:29:00.240
[Guest]: everything changed, etc, etc. But it helped us to land the message that, you know what,

01:29:00.240 --> 01:29:04.240
[Guest]: there is an idea here, let's try and make Jan, Feb, March much bigger than it is. And there's

01:29:04.240 --> 01:29:08.480
[Guest]: no rule which says it has to be that Jan, Feb, March mein kuch nahin hoga and the slog overs

01:29:08.480 --> 01:29:09.600
[Guest]: will start only in April.

01:29:12.080 --> 01:29:17.200
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and that cricketing analogy is great. And in a sense, it also illustrates another lesson

01:29:17.200 --> 01:29:22.000
[Amit Varma]: that you have in your book, which is that don't assume that the way things were done are still

01:29:22.000 --> 01:29:25.760
[Amit Varma]: the right way to do them, that you have to look at new paradigms. And of course, that happened

01:29:25.760 --> 01:29:30.240
[Amit Varma]: with ODI cricket, because if you look at run rates through the 70s, 80s, 90s, 2000s, up to the

01:29:30.240 --> 01:29:35.200
[Amit Varma]: modern day, where England have taken it another level ahead, that they've just gone up because

01:29:35.200 --> 01:29:39.520
[Amit Varma]: you change the way of playing. Earlier, you followed a kind of a more test matchy structure,

01:29:39.520 --> 01:29:44.800
[Amit Varma]: and then later on the structure evolved. And I think in T20, many teams still haven't figured

01:29:44.800 --> 01:29:50.240
[Amit Varma]: out the optimal structure, where when T20 cricket began at the end of the last decade, at the end

01:29:50.240 --> 01:29:56.400
[Amit Varma]: of the aughties rather, you know, they transplanted the ODI format that you slog at the start,

01:29:56.400 --> 01:30:00.400
[Amit Varma]: pinch it at the start, then you consolidate, then you slog at the end. But the truth is,

01:30:00.400 --> 01:30:05.280
[Amit Varma]: because you have the same number of batting resources, but now spread out over 20 overs

01:30:05.280 --> 01:30:11.200
[Amit Varma]: instead of 50, the expected value, the EV of aggression, as it were, just goes up massively.

01:30:11.200 --> 01:30:17.840
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, that old structure kind of becomes redundant. So that's still a lesson that I see

01:30:17.840 --> 01:30:23.040
[Amit Varma]: that many teams haven't got. In fact, elsewhere in your book, you speak about how when you're

01:30:23.040 --> 01:30:26.640
[Amit Varma]: building a team, you don't want to pick a team with the 11 best players, you want to figure out

01:30:26.640 --> 01:30:31.600
[Amit Varma]: the best team and you give the examples of, you know, Kohli's Royal Challengers with Kohli and

01:30:31.600 --> 01:30:36.560
[Amit Varma]: de Villiers and Gale and all that and the example of the early Rajasthan Royals. But I think the big

01:30:36.560 --> 01:30:42.640
[Amit Varma]: mistake that Kohli has consistently made as a T20 captain, and which is why Bangalore have kind of

01:30:42.640 --> 01:30:47.760
[Amit Varma]: not managed to dominate the IPL despite the riches, is a strategic mistake that they simply

01:30:47.760 --> 01:30:52.880
[Amit Varma]: haven't figured out that you need to kind of front load the hitting and just keep going. That

01:30:52.880 --> 01:30:58.560
[Amit Varma]: period of consolidation is perhaps overrated. Sorry, that was a digression.

01:30:58.560 --> 01:31:03.680
[Guest]: But I hope that book is coming Amit. You have so much to talk about as far as, you know, getting

01:31:03.680 --> 01:31:08.080
[Guest]: better metrics of performance, looking at cricket strategy very differently in T20. I've heard you

01:31:08.080 --> 01:31:11.840
[Guest]: speak about this in some forum. And I think there's a great book waiting to be written on this one.

01:31:11.840 --> 01:31:19.040
[Guest]: I actually think it's also a mindset thing. It just goes to show how difficult it is for for us to change

01:31:19.040 --> 01:31:25.280
[Guest]: and to adapt from one to the other. And our default setting seems to be to say the old one will work,

01:31:25.920 --> 01:31:30.640
[Guest]: you know, and I can stay with it. And then just minor tweaking and we think, oh, I have adapted

01:31:30.640 --> 01:31:35.040
[Guest]: and I'm now very good for it. Whereas the reality is that you probably need to just demolish it

01:31:35.040 --> 01:31:39.280
[Guest]: and start afresh. And, you know, the value of a wicket is such a powerful idea. And I must tell

01:31:39.280 --> 01:31:45.280
[Guest]: you a little story myself. This is Rahul Dravid talking about him becoming a better T20 cricketer

01:31:45.280 --> 01:31:51.520
[Guest]: in IPL. And, you know, he says Yusuf Pathan was his teammate in the Royals. And he says,

01:31:51.520 --> 01:31:57.200
[Guest]: I used to watch Pathan play and, you know, and I was very impressed with his batting. And then

01:31:57.200 --> 01:32:00.880
[Guest]: Yusuf apparently came to Rahul one day and told him, Rahul bhai, do you know what your problem is?

01:32:01.760 --> 01:32:04.320
[Guest]: And he says, you know, you put too much of a price on your wicket.

01:32:04.320 --> 01:32:10.720
[Guest]: You know, you're too scared that I'll get out. You know, you put too much of a price on your

01:32:10.720 --> 01:32:15.600
[Guest]: wicket. And Rahul says, I spent my entire career putting a price on my wicket and being lauded for

01:32:15.600 --> 01:32:19.040
[Guest]: it. And here was this chap telling me, you're putting too much of a price on your wicket.

01:32:19.040 --> 01:32:24.960
[Guest]: He says, the rules of T20 are such that your wicket is not so important, right? It's more

01:32:24.960 --> 01:32:28.560
[Guest]: important for you to be able to score that six or four. And Pathan, he says, would go in five

01:32:28.560 --> 01:32:32.880
[Guest]: innings. In three of them, he'd throw his wicket away. He didn't care. But in the other two,

01:32:32.880 --> 01:32:36.000
[Guest]: he would win a game for you because of the way he would bat. And he says, and Rahul says, that

01:32:36.000 --> 01:32:41.440
[Guest]: opened my eyes that maybe I just need to think fundamentally differently about my game because

01:32:41.440 --> 01:32:46.080
[Guest]: the format calls for it. And maybe that's something that you, you know, you also advocate, I think so.

01:32:46.800 --> 01:32:50.960
[Amit Varma]: That's fantastic. Because, yeah, obviously, because you have 10 wickets spread out over 20

01:32:50.960 --> 01:32:56.160
[Amit Varma]: overs instead of 50. So the natural conclusion there is that the value of a wicket goes down

01:32:56.160 --> 01:33:00.320
[Amit Varma]: and the cost of a dot ball goes up. So you have to look at the EV of each action,

01:33:00.320 --> 01:33:03.760
[Amit Varma]: which as a statistical person, obviously, you're familiar with expected value.

01:33:03.760 --> 01:33:09.680
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, the expected value of aggression is just far higher. And it's therefore a tragedy

01:33:09.680 --> 01:33:14.000
[Amit Varma]: when a team places too much of a price on his wickets. And you see, they've gone through 20

01:33:14.000 --> 01:33:18.240
[Amit Varma]: overs and they've only lost three wickets, which regardless of how much they've scored is a waste

01:33:18.240 --> 01:33:22.800
[Amit Varma]: of resources, because they had hitters in the pavilion who could have, you know, lifted the

01:33:22.800 --> 01:33:26.080
[Amit Varma]: rate. And therefore, they should all have been a little more aggressive. As far as my book is

01:33:26.080 --> 01:33:30.160
[Amit Varma]: concerned, yeah, I was, Wesleyan did ask me to write a book on this, which I was supposed to

01:33:30.160 --> 01:33:35.120
[Amit Varma]: deliver months ago, some point I have to kind of get down and finish it. Final flippant question

01:33:35.120 --> 01:33:40.960
[Amit Varma]: before we continue with your personal journey, that, you know, I saw one of my friends,

01:33:40.960 --> 01:33:45.520
[Amit Varma]: Peter Griffin asked on Facebook and Twitter recently that if you are in advertising,

01:33:45.520 --> 01:33:49.440
[Amit Varma]: have you ever, you know, felt bad about working on a particular product, which

01:33:50.160 --> 01:33:55.120
[Amit Varma]: didn't gel with whatever your personal value system was and all of that. Now, for a long time,

01:33:55.120 --> 01:33:59.760
[Amit Varma]: you were in charge of Pepsi, which is basically selling sugar. And we know that sugar is poison.

01:33:59.760 --> 01:34:02.800
[Amit Varma]: Did that thought ever cross your mind? I don't want to put you on the spot.

01:34:02.800 --> 01:34:08.480
[Guest]: It's just sort of a flippant kind of. No, it's not flippant at all. I was hugely

01:34:08.480 --> 01:34:15.360
[Guest]: passionate about Pepsi. And in all honesty, I also survived, not survived as much as saying

01:34:15.360 --> 01:34:20.960
[Guest]: I was there when there was this huge crisis of seeing this pesticide in Pepsi, you know,

01:34:20.960 --> 01:34:25.840
[Guest]: and we spent a year struggling with it. And I think we took great pride in our products

01:34:25.840 --> 01:34:30.000
[Guest]: and in Pepsi. And honestly, at that time, I didn't think of it as being anything wrong.

01:34:30.000 --> 01:34:35.680
[Guest]: I guess the awareness around sugar and what it might do for you and the need to kind of

01:34:35.680 --> 01:34:38.960
[Guest]: cut it down, I think is far more now than it might have been at that time.

01:34:40.800 --> 01:34:45.680
[Guest]: The awareness now that you shouldn't be selling it to kids versus, you know, we used to target

01:34:45.680 --> 01:34:52.880
[Guest]: kids and our kids were hugely passionate about Pepsi. So I must confess that while I was there

01:34:52.880 --> 01:34:57.200
[Guest]: and while I was doing what I was doing, I didn't think of it as would I have gone and worked for

01:34:57.200 --> 01:35:00.720
[Guest]: a liquor company? Chances are no. Would I have gone and worked for a cigarette company? Chances

01:35:00.720 --> 01:35:06.720
[Guest]: are no. In my mind, did I see Pepsi that way? Honest answer, I didn't. And therefore, that

01:35:06.720 --> 01:35:09.840
[Guest]: begs the question, perhaps, that what would I do today? And would I, you know, would I look

01:35:09.840 --> 01:35:14.240
[Guest]: at it differently? I still think that Pepsi still shown that they are responsible. They try to get

01:35:14.240 --> 01:35:18.560
[Guest]: it right. And, you know, they will not advertise to children. They are trying to ensure that their

01:35:18.560 --> 01:35:24.800
[Guest]: sugar level, you know, comes down. But to answer your question, you know, I never thought of it

01:35:24.800 --> 01:35:31.280
[Guest]: that way. And for me, Pepsi was like, if there were the best years of my life, I had a blast

01:35:31.280 --> 01:35:36.240
[Guest]: while I was at Pepsi. I really enjoyed working with some fabulous people. I also discovered how

01:35:37.200 --> 01:35:41.680
[Guest]: being passionate about a business can make a huge difference to outcomes.

01:35:41.680 --> 01:35:49.360
[Guest]: And I also learned how sometimes having an enemy can actually foster that passion. We used to joke

01:35:49.360 --> 01:35:52.320
[Guest]: that apparently there was a saying in Coke that if there was no Pepsi, they would have had to

01:35:52.320 --> 01:35:57.360
[Guest]: invent it because their strategy and everything that happened in the world happened because there

01:35:57.360 --> 01:36:01.520
[Guest]: was this other, you know, the shark in the tank or an enemy at the door kind of thing. And that

01:36:01.520 --> 01:36:05.520
[Guest]: made a huge difference to the way we might be. We woke up every morning saying we've got to win.

01:36:05.520 --> 01:36:10.480
[Guest]: And you knew that, you know, you would bleed blue because you were Pepsi. And I think this whole

01:36:10.480 --> 01:36:15.280
[Guest]: idea of saying, how do you build, how do you get a team of people to be passionate about what they

01:36:15.280 --> 01:36:19.440
[Guest]: do? And in the context of what we see in our country and what's happening, maybe there are

01:36:19.440 --> 01:36:25.520
[Guest]: lessons over here, both good and bad, in terms of how, if you can get people to be excited by a

01:36:25.520 --> 01:36:34.720
[Guest]: cause, they will often suspend judgment and just do what's required. And suddenly, the fact that

01:36:34.720 --> 01:36:39.040
[Guest]: you are weak, that you're not spending as much in terms of advertising dollars as your competitor,

01:36:39.040 --> 01:36:44.080
[Guest]: the fact that your, you know, your brand salience scores are not as high as the other person,

01:36:44.080 --> 01:36:48.960
[Guest]: all that becomes irrelevant because you started believing in a cause, which is to say, you know,

01:36:48.960 --> 01:36:52.640
[Guest]: what, we're going to kill the other guy and we'll become number one, you know, or a more

01:36:52.640 --> 01:36:58.800
[Guest]: milder version of a politically correct version of that. So, you know, can work against you,

01:36:58.800 --> 01:37:00.960
[Guest]: but can work for you. I think that's the way I'd put it.

01:37:00.960 --> 01:37:05.760
[Amit Varma]: No, it strikes me that, you know, passion is a double-edged sword in more than one way. Like

01:37:05.760 --> 01:37:10.560
[Amit Varma]: one of the pieces of advice that I think I give people, which kind of came from early personal

01:37:10.560 --> 01:37:14.960
[Amit Varma]: experience in the corporate world, is that don't get too passionate about your job. My sense was

01:37:14.960 --> 01:37:19.680
[Amit Varma]: that there are people who get too passionate about their jobs, their sense of self becomes

01:37:19.680 --> 01:37:24.000
[Amit Varma]: too deep. And then when something happens, when they have to leave or something goes wrong,

01:37:24.000 --> 01:37:28.480
[Amit Varma]: then their entire lives are shattered. And my advice to them always was that save your passion

01:37:28.480 --> 01:37:32.480
[Amit Varma]: for what you do in your free time, whether it's your hobbies or whether it's something else that

01:37:32.480 --> 01:37:37.120
[Amit Varma]: you do. And when you're working, work with full intensity, give it everything, you know, that's

01:37:37.120 --> 01:37:41.680
[Amit Varma]: your dharma, you're there to do a job, work with full intensity, give it all that, but don't get

01:37:41.680 --> 01:37:48.400
[Amit Varma]: emotionally involved with it. Because if it goes bad, it is not worth going through that emotional

01:37:48.400 --> 01:37:54.160
[Amit Varma]: turmoil for over a mere job, for example, which almost seems to contradict what you're saying.

01:37:54.160 --> 01:37:58.720
[Amit Varma]: And I get what you're saying as well, because you will do anything to the best of your abilities

01:37:58.720 --> 01:38:03.840
[Amit Varma]: when you're more passionate about it. And when, you know, so what are your thoughts on this?

01:38:05.120 --> 01:38:10.160
[Guest]: The world is changing. And I'd like to believe that, you know, the kids at work today think of

01:38:10.160 --> 01:38:15.760
[Guest]: it perhaps slightly differently than we might have. I don't think when I was in, when I was at work,

01:38:15.760 --> 01:38:19.840
[Guest]: we had this luxury of thinking that, you know, this is work, and I will just treat it as a

01:38:19.840 --> 01:38:24.400
[Guest]: compartment. And then I have this other passion, and this is my free time, and this is what I will

01:38:24.400 --> 01:38:29.840
[Guest]: do. In many ways, they kind of, the lines got blurred, it all merged. If you were not happy at

01:38:29.840 --> 01:38:34.000
[Guest]: work, chances are you were not happy. It's not like you could say, I'll shut it off, and I'll

01:38:34.000 --> 01:38:38.640
[Guest]: just do what I want to do. And I think therefore getting, enjoying what you were doing, feeling

01:38:38.640 --> 01:38:43.440
[Guest]: good about it, enjoying the people you are working with, I think became a huge part of it. And I

01:38:43.440 --> 01:38:49.200
[Guest]: think you can do well, all of us will do well if we start to feel that we are enjoying what we are

01:38:49.200 --> 01:38:53.840
[Guest]: doing. Another lesson that I think I learned, and I try and tell young people is that it's not

01:38:53.840 --> 01:38:58.560
[Guest]: to suggest that there will not be moments that you won't enjoy. There won't be parts of a job

01:38:58.560 --> 01:39:03.760
[Guest]: that you won't enjoy. It's par for the course. But you need to get over those. And if you start

01:39:03.760 --> 01:39:09.040
[Guest]: saying, I don't like this little bit, so I'm out of here, chances are you'll never stay anywhere

01:39:09.040 --> 01:39:14.400
[Guest]: because there'll always be a tiny bit which you won't enjoy. And which will then make you say,

01:39:14.400 --> 01:39:17.280
[Guest]: I'm out of here, I'm out of here, I'm out of here. And then you'll suddenly struggle to say,

01:39:17.280 --> 01:39:23.760
[Guest]: why am I not getting anywhere? So for me, being passionate about what you do and as a leader,

01:39:23.760 --> 01:39:29.600
[Guest]: and I'm just saying this now, we sold Pepsi and it was easy to be passionate about Pepsi

01:39:30.160 --> 01:39:35.520
[Guest]: because in those days, if you were on a flight, the guy next to you would be this snooty guy

01:39:35.520 --> 01:39:38.400
[Guest]: reading something and he'd suddenly ask you, what do you do? And you'd say, Pepsi, and he'd shut

01:39:38.400 --> 01:39:44.000
[Guest]: the book and then tell you about, what you should do, about your taste, about how my daughter likes

01:39:44.000 --> 01:39:47.920
[Guest]: it. My son doesn't like it. Coke is better, not better. I think in your advertising, you should

01:39:47.920 --> 01:39:53.440
[Guest]: do this. Pepsi was all over. It was such a high interest category. It was easy to be passionate

01:39:53.440 --> 01:39:57.520
[Guest]: about. You had an enemy. But I must tell you that one of the challenges I had was I went and sold

01:39:57.520 --> 01:40:01.920
[Guest]: Yellow Pages after that. Now, how boring can Yellow Pages be compared to colas? And you don't

01:40:01.920 --> 01:40:07.360
[Guest]: have Shah Rukh Khan and Sachin Tendulkar telling you, use Infomedia Yellow Pages. Getting my team

01:40:07.360 --> 01:40:12.320
[Guest]: to be excited about Yellow Pages, to be excited about saying, we are doing something special.

01:40:12.320 --> 01:40:16.160
[Guest]: We're going to help that small business get it right. And getting people to believe in it,

01:40:16.880 --> 01:40:22.960
[Guest]: I think was an important step for me to get people excited to do more than they might have thought

01:40:22.960 --> 01:40:28.160
[Guest]: was possible. And therefore, for me, that's what passion might have done for them. And you're

01:40:28.160 --> 01:40:32.240
[Guest]: right. It is not to suggest that it's the end of the world. If the job goes, if something doesn't

01:40:32.240 --> 01:40:36.880
[Guest]: work out right, it's only a job after all. But while you're doing it, I think it's a good idea

01:40:36.880 --> 01:40:42.720
[Amit Varma]: to be passionate about what you do. So two questions. One, aren't Yellow Pages sort of

01:40:42.720 --> 01:40:47.200
[Amit Varma]: the Kodak of the informational world in the sense completely miss a bus and gone? And two,

01:40:47.200 --> 01:40:52.080
[Amit Varma]: when you're passionate about something, and does it create the danger that you're closed

01:40:52.080 --> 01:40:56.320
[Amit Varma]: to the possibility that what you're doing today may be completely irrelevant tomorrow?

01:40:56.320 --> 01:41:00.480
[Amit Varma]: As I guess, in the case of Yellow Pages, if I'm mistaken, please tell me.

01:41:00.480 --> 01:41:03.280
[Guest]: No, so you're absolutely right. So Yellow Pages is history. It's not there. But

01:41:03.280 --> 01:41:08.080
[Guest]: so one of the things we did when we were when I was with the Yellow Pages business was we tied

01:41:08.080 --> 01:41:12.720
[Guest]: up with Alibaba and we brought Alibaba into India. So that Alibaba's entry into India was at some

01:41:12.720 --> 01:41:17.920
[Guest]: level with us at that stage. So just to make the point that we recognized that Yellow Pages are

01:41:17.920 --> 01:41:22.960
[Guest]: not likely to last very long. We also recognize that. So we had a telephone answering system and

01:41:22.960 --> 01:41:28.400
[Guest]: you know, ask me as a service that we would do. But we recognize even that may not be future

01:41:28.400 --> 01:41:32.400
[Guest]: proof enough. And really the way to go would be to try and say, how can we leverage the internet

01:41:32.400 --> 01:41:36.400
[Guest]: to get this right? So you're right. The only difference I'd say is that it wasn't a Kodak

01:41:36.400 --> 01:41:40.320
[Guest]: moment. We tried to get Alibaba in. But then, of course, the way things work in business,

01:41:40.320 --> 01:41:47.920
[Guest]: businesses get bought and sold and get deprioritized. And, you know, it's I also say

01:41:47.920 --> 01:41:54.400
[Guest]: this, Amit, it's it's always tough when you are running Kodak to see the Kodak moment and say

01:41:54.400 --> 01:41:58.400
[Guest]: that, you know, it's very easy to look back and say, what were they thinking? What are they smoking?

01:41:58.400 --> 01:42:02.400
[Guest]: How could they do this? Right. But when you're making when you're valued as high as you are,

01:42:02.400 --> 01:42:08.240
[Guest]: and you're making all those billions in profit, it's not easy to say, let's destroy our business.

01:42:09.360 --> 01:42:13.120
[Guest]: You know, it's not easy. And I have a lot of respect for people who can do that. And I think

01:42:13.120 --> 01:42:18.400
[Guest]: Gillette is a great example of that. You know, as anyone and, you know, as all of us who might

01:42:18.400 --> 01:42:23.040
[Guest]: have used Gillette Blades, you are very happy with Gillette. And then came Mach 1. And you thought,

01:42:23.040 --> 01:42:27.920
[Guest]: wow, very nice. And you upgraded and you paid a little more. You didn't need Mach 2. And you

01:42:27.920 --> 01:42:32.400
[Guest]: didn't need Mach 3. And you didn't need Mach 3 plus. Right. But they keep doing this to make

01:42:32.400 --> 01:42:35.680
[Guest]: sure that they're still giving you a blade, which is better than what somebody else might give you.

01:42:36.480 --> 01:42:40.480
[Guest]: And even if it means killing the previous one, they will do it. And I think it takes courage

01:42:40.480 --> 01:42:46.080
[Guest]: to do it. But as we've learned, it's not about having a choice. It's just about having the

01:42:46.080 --> 01:42:50.960
[Guest]: wisdom and having having voices in the system, which will tell you that's what you need to do

01:42:50.960 --> 01:42:55.280
[Amit Varma]: and listening to those voices. True. In fact, a great example of this is actually Netflix,

01:42:55.280 --> 01:42:59.600
[Amit Varma]: which, you know, began as a DVD rental service. And then they killed that business and they did

01:42:59.600 --> 01:43:05.040
[Amit Varma]: this and you know, in a sense played a part in the massive change that has happened since.

01:43:05.040 --> 01:43:08.960
[Amit Varma]: Let's take a quick commercial break. And when we come out of the break, we'll move past your

01:43:08.960 --> 01:43:14.480
[Amit Varma]: corporate career into your role as a teacher and motivator and so on and talk about your book in

01:43:14.480 --> 01:43:22.640
[Amit Varma]: some detail as well. Long before I was a podcaster, I was a writer. In fact, chances are that many of

01:43:22.640 --> 01:43:28.640
[Amit Varma]: you first heard of me because of my blog India Uncut, which was active between 2003 and 2009

01:43:28.640 --> 01:43:33.760
[Amit Varma]: and became somewhat popular at the time. I love the freedom the form gave me. And I feel I was

01:43:33.760 --> 01:43:39.920
[Amit Varma]: shaped by it in many ways. I exercise my writing muscle every day and was forced to think about

01:43:39.920 --> 01:43:44.480
[Amit Varma]: many different things because I wrote about many different things. Well, that phase in my life

01:43:44.480 --> 01:43:50.000
[Amit Varma]: ended for various reasons. And now it is time to revive it. Only now I'm doing it through a

01:43:50.000 --> 01:43:56.400
[Amit Varma]: newsletter. I have started the India Uncut newsletter at indiancut.substack.com where I

01:43:56.400 --> 01:44:01.360
[Amit Varma]: will write regularly about whatever catches my fancy. I'll write about some of the themes I cover

01:44:01.360 --> 01:44:07.680
[Amit Varma]: in this podcast and about much else. So please do head on over to indiancut.substack.com and

01:44:07.680 --> 01:44:13.120
[Amit Varma]: subscribe. It is free. Once you sign up, each new installment that I write will land up in your

01:44:13.120 --> 01:44:19.360
[Amit Varma]: email inbox. You don't need to go anywhere. So subscribe now for free. The India Uncut newsletter

01:44:19.360 --> 01:44:22.480
[Amit Varma]: at indiancut.substack.com. Thank you.

