01:44:54.080 --> 01:44:59.840
[Amit Varma]: them is this bit where he says where he'll warn somebody against doing something. And then at the

01:44:59.840 --> 01:45:06.480
[Amit Varma]: end, he'll say ye mat kehna ki Ranveer ne bataya nahi. So you know, you're the title of your book

01:45:06.520 --> 01:45:11.040
[Amit Varma]: sort of reminded me of that. Now while talking about your corporate journey, I've tried to kind

01:45:11.040 --> 01:45:16.160
[Amit Varma]: of get you to talk about your sort of journey to the top where you became CEO and MD and led these

01:45:16.160 --> 01:45:21.080
[Amit Varma]: great companies, but I can see that you're too modest to go there yourself. Let's talk, however,

01:45:21.080 --> 01:45:26.680
[Amit Varma]: about both that phase when you're leading these companies and what you bring into it, and also

01:45:26.840 --> 01:45:33.680
[Amit Varma]: your openness to then reinventing yourself in the way that you did, like how did that transition

01:45:33.680 --> 01:45:39.120
[Amit Varma]: happen? Were these thoughts that I will do this that I will share my learnings and write books

01:45:39.120 --> 01:45:44.040
[Amit Varma]: like this, do courses like this? Was it kind of there from before? Or was it something that

01:45:44.040 --> 01:45:49.920
[Amit Varma]: happened after, you know, you you led these companies? And was there a moment where you think

01:45:49.920 --> 01:45:56.120
[Amit Varma]: about what next? And also, I have no idea if you bought a BMW in your 40s. But was this some kind

01:45:56.120 --> 01:45:58.440
[Amit Varma]: of midlife crisis? And what form did that take?

01:46:00.400 --> 01:46:05.680
[Guest]: No. So I'll tell you a couple of couple of pointers, perhaps in this direction. The first was

01:46:05.680 --> 01:46:11.720
[Guest]: that something I would do every year is make out a list of resolutions for the year or things that I

01:46:11.720 --> 01:46:17.160
[Guest]: will do this year. And I can look back maybe to 20, 25 years ago, I certainly remember, I think

01:46:17.160 --> 01:46:21.800
[Guest]: there's a 1998 version of it, there's a 2000 version of it, which will include things like have

01:46:21.800 --> 01:46:27.400
[Guest]: a waist size 32, which never happened, or have a golf handicap of 18, which has never happened, or

01:46:27.720 --> 01:46:34.600
[Guest]: write a book, which is also was a recurring part of my wish list or my, you know, what things I

01:46:34.600 --> 01:46:41.240
[Guest]: want to do this year kind of stuff. And interestingly enough, when I was leaving towards

01:46:41.240 --> 01:46:45.360
[Guest]: the end of my stint at Infomedia, which is the Yellow Pages business that I ran, it was it had

01:46:45.360 --> 01:46:51.040
[Guest]: got sold to a strategic investor. And I was just, you know, I was staying on till I finish, I used

01:46:51.040 --> 01:46:57.960
[Guest]: to write a blog over there. And, and the blog was had started to become reasonably popular, which

01:46:57.960 --> 01:47:01.680
[Guest]: means that, you know, three colleagues and four friends would read it and say good things about

01:47:01.680 --> 01:47:09.240
[Guest]: it. And suddenly, of course, I wrote something about tipping in a restaurant. And, and the

01:47:09.240 --> 01:47:14.280
[Guest]: lesson that I learned about tipping, and guess what, there was this waiter from a small town in

01:47:14.280 --> 01:47:19.160
[Guest]: the United States who wrote in to say what a good thought. And it suddenly struck me, wow, here I

01:47:19.160 --> 01:47:23.320
[Guest]: am writing a blog, which I think is restricted to, you know, friends and family, and somebody else

01:47:23.320 --> 01:47:26.880
[Guest]: is reading it and responding to it. And that said, you know, maybe there's something happening

01:47:26.880 --> 01:47:31.520
[Guest]: here. The blog kept happening, you know, I kept writing reasonably regularly, I enjoyed it, it was

01:47:31.520 --> 01:47:37.080
[Guest]: like a message to my own team. And then it struck me that maybe there's an idea here for a book. So

01:47:37.080 --> 01:47:42.480
[Guest]: of course, I, I decided that I must write that book. And I, you know, and this is that year where

01:47:42.520 --> 01:47:46.200
[Guest]: I'm about to leave a business, and then I'm not sure what I want to do, I'm thinking I'm going to

01:47:46.200 --> 01:47:50.320
[Guest]: write and speak and do all those cool things, who wants to go back to the corporate world. So we

01:47:50.320 --> 01:47:53.920
[Guest]: say, let's make a, and I've read somewhere that, you know, the way to do this is you must make a

01:47:53.920 --> 01:47:59.240
[Guest]: book proposal. So I make a book proposal, which suggests why I think, you know, the best idea

01:47:59.240 --> 01:48:03.560
[Guest]: there is, and then I send it out to three publishers, I send it to Penguin, I send it to

01:48:03.560 --> 01:48:08.080
[Guest]: Harper. And then of course, to keep it easy, I say, let me also send it to Rupa and Jaiko.

01:48:08.360 --> 01:48:13.800
[Guest]: That will be done, you know. And guess what, within a week of sending it, I get a immediate

01:48:13.800 --> 01:48:20.840
[Guest]: response from Rupa saying not interested. And then a week later, I call up Jaiko, who's in the

01:48:20.840 --> 01:48:24.800
[Guest]: same city that I live in, which I live in, which is Bombay, and I call up Jaiko and say, I'd send

01:48:24.800 --> 01:48:30.120
[Guest]: this book. And they put me through to an editor who I can swear is in the, you know, is probably

01:48:30.120 --> 01:48:34.760
[Guest]: in the kitchen, and I can hear the pressure cooker go off. And she says, you know, we do too

01:48:34.760 --> 01:48:39.320
[Guest]: many of this kind of book. Tell me what is it about? And I suddenly discover there's something

01:48:39.320 --> 01:48:44.560
[Guest]: called an elevator pitch, which I don't have. Nothing happens. And then of course, a book

01:48:44.560 --> 01:48:50.560
[Guest]: starts to happen. And Penguin responds three months later and says that, you know what, the

01:48:50.560 --> 01:48:55.000
[Guest]: editor lady, kind lady called Heather Adams writes to me and says, I've liked what I've read, I'd

01:48:55.000 --> 01:48:58.760
[Guest]: love to make it a book, and we'd love to work with you. And I think this is like a dream come

01:48:58.760 --> 01:49:04.760
[Guest]: true. So maybe that's one watershed moment of sorts where the book happens. And that starts to

01:49:04.760 --> 01:49:08.600
[Guest]: change things for me. And maybe I'll come back to what might it what it might do for me over

01:49:08.600 --> 01:49:12.800
[Guest]: there. Let me go back a little bit and say that something else that I that might have made a

01:49:12.800 --> 01:49:19.920
[Guest]: difference was that I, I know this, this is popular, icky guy, kind of the book and the idea.

01:49:19.920 --> 01:49:24.840
[Guest]: And I think the idea is pretty powerful. And, and somewhere along the way, I guess I started to

01:49:24.840 --> 01:49:30.680
[Guest]: figure this for myself that, you know, maybe what can give me happiness is if I can work in that

01:49:30.680 --> 01:49:36.640
[Guest]: sweet spot, where I'm doing something that I'm reasonably good at, that I'm uniquely good at

01:49:36.720 --> 01:49:41.800
[Guest]: something that I enjoy doing something that has value in this world and will make a difference.

01:49:41.800 --> 01:49:46.560
[Guest]: If I can kind of find the intersection of those four circles, maybe I'll be in a sweet spot. And

01:49:46.560 --> 01:49:52.640
[Guest]: that for me starts to kind of work to say this might just be an interesting space to be. And I

01:49:52.640 --> 01:49:57.040
[Guest]: still remember that, you know, from conferences in businesses from many years ago, I would, I

01:49:57.040 --> 01:50:01.760
[Guest]: would be that I would speak and people would think, wow, that was, no one came and told me, I

01:50:01.760 --> 01:50:05.840
[Guest]: think that was such a great strategic decision. This is going to change our market share, but

01:50:05.840 --> 01:50:09.960
[Guest]: they would probably come and tell me that was, you know, that people, bottlers or

01:50:09.960 --> 01:50:14.080
[Guest]: distributors would come and say, that was very interesting. So again, looking back, I would feel

01:50:14.080 --> 01:50:18.000
[Guest]: that maybe there's something that I have over there as a strength. I met a man called Brian

01:50:18.000 --> 01:50:23.040
[Guest]: Tracy, when I was running Infomedia, Brian Tracy is this, you know, is an American motivational speaker,

01:50:23.120 --> 01:50:27.000
[Guest]: but of those, one of those guru kind of guys been around for a long time, written like a million

01:50:27.000 --> 01:50:32.600
[Guest]: books and, and a few million tapes sold, et cetera, et cetera. And I told him, I want to be a

01:50:32.600 --> 01:50:37.240
[Guest]: speaker. I want to quit all this corporate world and become a speaker and become a motivational

01:50:37.240 --> 01:50:43.120
[Guest]: speaker. Like, you know, so, so he said to me, he said, you know what, don't do that. Don't be in

01:50:43.120 --> 01:50:50.040
[Guest]: a hurry to quit and do this. You start to speak, you speak 200 times, speak at the Rotary Club,

01:50:50.040 --> 01:50:55.840
[Guest]: speak in your school, speak in your local complex, speak wherever you get invited, just speak.

01:50:56.360 --> 01:51:00.960
[Guest]: And if you've spoken 200 times, two things would have happened. One, see if you still enjoy it

01:51:00.960 --> 01:51:05.840
[Guest]: after you've spoken 200 times. And two, see if 200 people call you. And it's quite likely that you

01:51:05.840 --> 01:51:09.920
[Guest]: don't get to that 200 number. But if both these happen, then you're probably in a place where you

01:51:09.920 --> 01:51:14.240
[Guest]: can say, yep, I still want to do it. And what happened for me was when I, when the book was

01:51:14.240 --> 01:51:20.280
[Guest]: out, it got me a lot of opportunities to speak around the book. So lots of friends and other

01:51:20.280 --> 01:51:24.280
[Guest]: companies, HR folks would all call me and say, come speak to colleges would call me and say, speak

01:51:24.280 --> 01:51:28.240
[Guest]: about the book. And the book started, you know, the book was the habit of winning. And I just

01:51:28.280 --> 01:51:33.040
[Guest]: enjoyed sharing stories about winning, which is big stories from Pepsi, from soap, from cricket,

01:51:33.040 --> 01:51:38.240
[Guest]: whatever it was. And I started to speak. And I actually literally took that 200 speaking

01:51:38.240 --> 01:51:42.920
[Guest]: engagement seriously. And I did that. And I started to enjoy it. And then by then, of course,

01:51:42.920 --> 01:51:47.360
[Guest]: the second book happened, and then there started being conflict. I got invited to speak at a TEDx

01:51:47.360 --> 01:51:52.640
[Guest]: event. And it clashed with my global CEO's visit to India, which happened, you know, and therefore

01:51:52.640 --> 01:51:56.440
[Guest]: I couldn't do the TEDx talk, which at that time, TEDx was still happening. And it's still something

01:51:56.440 --> 01:52:02.160
[Guest]: special in that sense. And I thought, oh, gosh, missing an opportunity. And I guess, somewhere

01:52:02.160 --> 01:52:07.800
[Guest]: along the way, this, you know, a second book happened, speaking was giving me great joy. I'd be

01:52:07.800 --> 01:52:11.880
[Guest]: at an airport with some guy would come up to me and say, sir, you remember, or you had come to our

01:52:11.880 --> 01:52:15.800
[Guest]: company event, or you came and spoke, and you know, we need to repeat something I might have

01:52:15.800 --> 01:52:21.800
[Guest]: said. I thought this is this is so cool. This is what I want to do. And literally, you know, I

01:52:21.800 --> 01:52:25.360
[Guest]: really asked myself that question, if I was to be run over by a bus tomorrow morning, what is it

01:52:25.360 --> 01:52:31.360
[Guest]: that I would really regret not having done, you know, and I didn't think I'd answer wasn't that I

01:52:31.360 --> 01:52:37.200
[Guest]: wish I'd bought a bigger BMW or a bigger house or a big or more stock options or more money. I

01:52:37.200 --> 01:52:41.960
[Guest]: that didn't. And this is not trying to sound immodest. I didn't have a BMW to start with. But

01:52:41.960 --> 01:52:46.360
[Guest]: that was not the point. It didn't, didn't excite me. It wasn't why I thought, wow, that's what's

01:52:46.360 --> 01:52:50.560
[Guest]: going to be cool. For me, the cool bit was, wow, I'd love to go out and be this guy who writes a

01:52:50.560 --> 01:52:57.360
[Guest]: lot more, who speaks a lot more. My ideal, my world had this, this lovely image of my grandchild

01:52:57.360 --> 01:53:01.000
[Guest]: climbing up an attic and pulling out a book and saying, you know what, my granddad wrote this, you

01:53:01.000 --> 01:53:06.520
[Guest]: know, just that feeling of saying, maybe there's a legacy there. The fact that, you know, market

01:53:06.520 --> 01:53:11.400
[Guest]: cap went up in my business and our investors made more money or that market share went up or that

01:53:11.400 --> 01:53:16.200
[Guest]: we launched this terrific product. All of that seemed to pale into insignificance in a sense to

01:53:16.200 --> 01:53:20.800
[Guest]: say that. And this is not to say that's not important. It's just that to me, that didn't seem

01:53:20.800 --> 01:53:25.880
[Guest]: like the big deal. For me, it felt like what a life it could be. I'd have so much fun. It wouldn't

01:53:25.880 --> 01:53:31.720
[Guest]: be work for me if I could just go out and speak about stuff that I'm passionate about. Life would

01:53:31.720 --> 01:53:37.080
[Guest]: be so good for me if I could go out and write the stuff that I seem to be enjoying. And if I can use

01:53:37.080 --> 01:53:42.200
[Guest]: some of what I've learned to help other people get just a bit better. And that's where perhaps this

01:53:42.200 --> 01:53:46.080
[Guest]: coaching bit, you know, it was a bug that had bitten me much earlier. And I trained to become a

01:53:46.080 --> 01:53:51.440
[Guest]: coach just to say that, can I help formalize a process by which I can help other people to get

01:53:51.440 --> 01:53:56.320
[Guest]: just a bit better than they might be? So this really looked like what I want to do. And then, of

01:53:56.320 --> 01:54:00.480
[Guest]: course, you know, came the conversation with the spouse, with my wife, and she was usually

01:54:00.480 --> 01:54:04.160
[Guest]: supportive. And I did tell her, look, I'm going to do this not because it's going to make money for

01:54:04.160 --> 01:54:10.840
[Guest]: us. I'm assuming that I, if I don't make a penny from here, my CA has told me that, look, don't

01:54:10.840 --> 01:54:14.400
[Guest]: worry, you know, we wouldn't have to kind of be on the, you know, we don't worry about food,

01:54:14.400 --> 01:54:19.440
[Guest]: clothing, and shelter. And indeed, that little holiday and that little whatever else that is our

01:54:19.440 --> 01:54:23.440
[Guest]: indulgence. Don't worry about it. But it's not like we can suddenly say, now I want a bigger

01:54:23.440 --> 01:54:27.120
[Guest]: home and I want more and more and more. That's not going to happen. But I'm going to have fun. I

01:54:27.120 --> 01:54:32.200
[Guest]: think I love this. Yeah. And that's how I think the transition. So the transition happened by the

01:54:32.200 --> 01:54:38.080
[Guest]: time there were two books out. I had been speaking for nothing. I mean, I wouldn't make a penny out

01:54:38.080 --> 01:54:42.840
[Guest]: of my speaking, but I could see that what I was doing could also could also get me, you know,

01:54:42.840 --> 01:54:48.520
[Guest]: could pay the bills, could make some money. But really the driver was that's what I thought I

01:54:48.520 --> 01:54:55.040
[Guest]: wanted to be. You know, my chance at being Prakash Iyer, that one that one little purpose for

01:54:55.040 --> 01:54:58.800
[Guest]: which maybe, maybe I was meant to do. That's that's what it sounded like for me.

01:55:00.160 --> 01:55:04.160
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's a that's a lovely story about your passion shifting from one P to another, from

01:55:04.160 --> 01:55:09.360
[Amit Varma]: Pepsi to Prakash. And it strikes me that just in this story of your life, there are life lessons

01:55:09.360 --> 01:55:14.800
[Amit Varma]: for people to learn. In fact, one of which is a chapter in your book and is also something

01:55:15.280 --> 01:55:19.800
[Amit Varma]: coincidentally that I spoke about last week when I did an episode on creators with Roshan Abbas,

01:55:19.800 --> 01:55:25.360
[Amit Varma]: where one of the things we chatted about was the importance of quantity over quality, not in so

01:55:25.360 --> 01:55:30.960
[Amit Varma]: many words. This is, you know, I got these exact words from your chapter on the subject. And, you

01:55:30.960 --> 01:55:35.320
[Amit Varma]: know, you spoke about the advice you got to speak 200 times. And similarly, I mentioned to Roshan

01:55:35.320 --> 01:55:42.320
[Amit Varma]: how I was struck by the YouTuber Ali Abdaal's advice to young YouTubers that for you know, make

01:55:42.320 --> 01:55:48.360
[Amit Varma]: 200 videos, literally two videos a week for two years. Before you look at the metrics, just do

01:55:48.360 --> 01:55:53.640
[Amit Varma]: that and just the constant iteration will make you better. And you've got a great chapter on this,

01:55:53.800 --> 01:55:58.360
[Amit Varma]: which you begin with a lovely quote by GK Chesterton, quote, anything worth doing is worth

01:55:58.360 --> 01:56:04.520
[Amit Varma]: doing badly, stop quote. And then you give a great example of the ceramic pots. You know, you read

01:56:04.520 --> 01:56:09.000
[Amit Varma]: it as did I a long time ago from this book called Art and Fear by David Bales and Ted Orland, as

01:56:09.000 --> 01:56:15.400
[Amit Varma]: you pointed out. And it's a fantastic experiment with a key lesson at the end of it. So you want

01:56:15.400 --> 01:56:20.280
[Amit Varma]: to repeat for my listeners what it is and the lesson that we then arrive at?

01:56:21.360 --> 01:56:27.520
[Guest]: Yeah, so one of the things that fascinates me is this, we all get told that something is better

01:56:27.520 --> 01:56:31.760
[Guest]: than something else. And that becomes like a norm. And what I want to do is to tell ourselves that

01:56:32.120 --> 01:56:36.840
[Guest]: maybe that's the norm, but learn to challenge it. And it may not always be the case and look for

01:56:36.880 --> 01:56:41.320
[Guest]: where the outliers might be. And an example of that was this thing that we've always heard, right?

01:56:41.320 --> 01:56:47.080
[Guest]: Quality is better than quantity. I mean, we've used it to our own advantage. I'm sure, you know,

01:56:47.080 --> 01:56:52.680
[Guest]: we can all relate to this quality over quantity. And this is an experiment in a ceramics class,

01:56:52.680 --> 01:56:58.440
[Guest]: apparently, where the teacher decides that she does an experiment. She says that you'd be judged

01:56:58.440 --> 01:57:03.640
[Guest]: in this class at the end of the term on one of two parameters. You could either go for the quality

01:57:03.640 --> 01:57:08.760
[Guest]: route or for the quantity route, which is very simple. If you take the quality option, you can

01:57:08.760 --> 01:57:15.240
[Guest]: spend the next term making your best pot and come back. And at the end of it, if your pot is perfect,

01:57:15.240 --> 01:57:19.720
[Guest]: you'll get an A. If it's good, you'll get a B. If it's not so good, a C. And if it's terrible, a D.

01:57:20.520 --> 01:57:25.240
[Guest]: And in the other case, if you had to go the quantity route, what you would need to do is,

01:57:25.240 --> 01:57:28.920
[Guest]: I'll bring a weighing machine at the end of the term. And all the pots you've made will be put

01:57:28.920 --> 01:57:33.720
[Guest]: on the weighing machine. If you've made more than 70 kilos, you get an A. If it's 50 kilos,

01:57:33.720 --> 01:57:38.360
[Guest]: you get a B. If it's 30, you get a C, etc, etc. The interesting bit, of course, is that some

01:57:38.360 --> 01:57:41.560
[Guest]: students chose the quality route and some the quantity route. And at the end of the term,

01:57:41.560 --> 01:57:47.640
[Guest]: what they found was that the finest pot that emerged in class, the finest set of pots that

01:57:47.640 --> 01:57:53.240
[Guest]: emerged were not from the quality group. They were from the quantity group. The kids who were

01:57:53.240 --> 01:57:58.120
[Guest]: focused on delivering this great pot were thinking of the great pot, dreaming of that great pot,

01:57:58.840 --> 01:58:02.840
[Guest]: idealizing what's the right material, reading up on it and trying to say, how do I make that

01:58:02.840 --> 01:58:09.080
[Guest]: perfect pot? And that pot was nowhere near as good as the kids who chose the quantity route,

01:58:09.080 --> 01:58:15.160
[Guest]: who said, make it, it's going to take 70 kilos. So like, you keep making pot after pot after pot,

01:58:15.160 --> 01:58:19.640
[Guest]: and as you do it, you get better. And as you get better, your pots suddenly start to look

01:58:19.640 --> 01:58:25.080
[Guest]: even better. So that by the time you're getting to that 60 and 70 kilos, your pots were far better

01:58:25.080 --> 01:58:30.120
[Guest]: than the group that had set out to make the perfect pot. And I think it's such a powerful

01:58:30.120 --> 01:58:36.280
[Guest]: lesson for us. And whether it's videos on YouTube, as Ali Abdaal will tell you, whether it is writing,

01:58:36.280 --> 01:58:39.960
[Guest]: as the great Amit Verma will tell you, or whether it's speaking, as Brian Tracy might have told,

01:58:40.520 --> 01:58:44.360
[Guest]: you know, I think just going after quantity, being willing to make mistakes,

01:58:44.920 --> 01:58:50.360
[Guest]: being willing to get it horribly wrong, but just learning from it can actually help us to get

01:58:50.360 --> 01:58:55.640
[Amit Varma]: to get to a better place. Yeah. And as you've said in the book, quantity leads to quality.

01:58:55.640 --> 01:59:01.160
[Amit Varma]: So my advice to any creator out there is don't don't overthink it. Like on one hand, it is,

01:59:01.160 --> 01:59:05.240
[Amit Varma]: of course, true what Lincoln says that if I am going to cut a tree, I'll spend six hours

01:59:05.240 --> 01:59:09.720
[Amit Varma]: sharpening the axe. And again, you quote that in your book, and I use that in some of my slides as

01:59:09.720 --> 01:59:14.920
[Amit Varma]: well. But so preparation and all of that is important. But at some point, there is a balance

01:59:14.920 --> 01:59:19.080
[Amit Varma]: to be drawn between getting it done and getting it right. And I keep talking about the straight

01:59:19.080 --> 01:59:24.040
[Amit Varma]: off in our lives. And I think in my own life, in fact, for most of it, I have made the mistake of,

01:59:24.040 --> 01:59:27.640
[Amit Varma]: you know, thinking about getting it right, and therefore never getting anything done.

01:59:27.640 --> 01:59:32.600
[Amit Varma]: And I think what's important is that you have to first get it done and getting it done again and

01:59:32.600 --> 01:59:40.120
[Amit Varma]: again and again is actually the route to sort of getting it right. The other thing that struck me

01:59:40.120 --> 01:59:45.160
[Amit Varma]: as very interesting is that when you made your year end list 99 2000, whatever, all these year

01:59:45.160 --> 01:59:51.560
[Amit Varma]: end lists that you're making, you said you would put things like waistline 32, or golf handicap,

01:59:51.560 --> 01:59:57.640
[Amit Varma]: x number, or write a book. And those are all goals. And as we both know, by now,

01:59:58.600 --> 02:00:04.760
[Amit Varma]: you know, it's thinking in terms of goals doesn't help you thinking in terms of processes does,

02:00:04.760 --> 02:00:09.080
[Amit Varma]: where you're, you know, you build a process and the goals kind of happen by themselves, and they

02:00:09.800 --> 02:00:16.120
[Amit Varma]: fall into place. I'm very curious to know what your processes were like, not just in this later

02:00:16.120 --> 02:00:21.000
[Amit Varma]: phase of your career. But even earlier, when you were in the corporate world, like in terms of work

02:00:21.000 --> 02:00:25.320
[Amit Varma]: ethic, what kind of processes do you build for yourself? Are you building similar processes in

02:00:25.320 --> 02:00:31.320
[Amit Varma]: terms of reading and taking ideas? You know, what do you do for knowledge management at a time where

02:00:31.320 --> 02:00:37.080
[Amit Varma]: perhaps there weren't any apps or fancy software for it? What do you do now? What are your processes

02:00:37.080 --> 02:00:41.800
[Amit Varma]: through which, you know, you write these books, do these courses, you're obviously constantly

02:00:41.800 --> 02:00:45.640
[Amit Varma]: modifying your content. You've just started a YouTube channel as well, which I'll link from

02:00:45.640 --> 02:00:50.040
[Amit Varma]: the show notes. So Godspeed for that. What will you tell me about your processes? That's what

02:00:50.040 --> 02:00:57.000
[Guest]: really interests me. I like the point you make about how those lists that I had were goals and

02:00:57.000 --> 02:01:04.120
[Guest]: not processes. And clearly, I didn't know better as it were. And that's probably why I put them

02:01:04.120 --> 02:01:09.960
[Guest]: there. And I didn't actually put down that, you know, write four times every week or take golf

02:01:09.960 --> 02:01:15.320
[Guest]: lessons every week or watch your diet, which is really the better way to get to the goals that I

02:01:15.320 --> 02:01:20.120
[Guest]: might have had. But I guess the goals were at least served a purpose, which is they kept me in

02:01:20.120 --> 02:01:25.480
[Guest]: focus of saying, what do I need to do to get there and maybe just get better with it. In terms of

02:01:25.480 --> 02:01:30.440
[Guest]: processes, maybe there are a couple of things that have become habits. So as a young manager,

02:01:30.440 --> 02:01:36.120
[Guest]: I remember if you walked into a boss's in the good old days when laptops were still, you know,

02:01:36.120 --> 02:01:42.120
[Guest]: not yet around us. If you walked into your boss's room for a meeting or a discussion,

02:01:42.120 --> 02:01:45.960
[Guest]: if you walked to any meeting, it was expected that you would carry a pen and a pad with you.

02:01:46.760 --> 02:01:50.120
[Guest]: You couldn't be walking in, flaring your hands and sitting over there and looking at the world.

02:01:50.120 --> 02:01:54.120
[Guest]: You had to have that pen and paper because if there was something that you needed to do,

02:01:54.120 --> 02:01:56.840
[Guest]: you would write it down. If there was something interesting you found, you'd write it down. If

02:01:56.840 --> 02:02:00.760
[Guest]: you saw a statistic, which was interesting, you'd put that down on a piece of paper. And I think

02:02:00.760 --> 02:02:07.160
[Guest]: that is something in some ways that has stayed with me. I don't trust my memory. And I guess

02:02:07.160 --> 02:02:11.320
[Guest]: over time, it just seems to be getting worse. And therefore, I think the need to write down

02:02:11.320 --> 02:02:17.880
[Guest]: something is a big one for me. And what I've done, Amit, is often if I see something interesting,

02:02:17.880 --> 02:02:23.480
[Guest]: or if I see a line, which might be an interesting one, or I hear something which is interesting,

02:02:23.480 --> 02:02:28.120
[Guest]: I will write it down. And I will then try and figure out, I may not even write everything,

02:02:28.120 --> 02:02:34.280
[Guest]: but I'll write enough of that line to be able to say, I know what this was. And very often,

02:02:34.280 --> 02:02:39.880
[Guest]: stories that I might share or ideas that I might propagate come from those little lines that might

02:02:39.880 --> 02:02:44.280
[Guest]: have actually cropped up somewhere. So this is really the crudest form. And then that became

02:02:45.080 --> 02:02:50.440
[Guest]: notes. And then, you know, I use Evernote, which I find is useful. I know that there are,

02:02:50.440 --> 02:02:57.080
[Guest]: you know, I'm a big fan of the idea of building a second brain, but I just find it too complicated.

02:02:57.080 --> 02:03:01.880
[Guest]: And I want to tell myself that maybe at this stage of my life, I don't want the process to hijack

02:03:01.880 --> 02:03:06.680
[Guest]: my agenda. And I don't want to be so caught up in saying I must get the better process.

02:03:06.680 --> 02:03:11.000
[Guest]: So long as I have something that works for me, and serves my purpose, I'm saying, you know,

02:03:11.640 --> 02:03:17.640
[Guest]: this is good enough, you know, and I don't really need to move to Notion or, you know,

02:03:18.280 --> 02:03:22.200
[Guest]: or something. That's the way I see it. The other thing I've done in terms of processes,

02:03:22.200 --> 02:03:29.400
[Guest]: and I said this to you earlier, that I like the idea of being able to kind of share what I have

02:03:29.400 --> 02:03:35.480
[Guest]: heard or learned, which is new for me. And therefore, a lot of my conversations with friends,

02:03:35.480 --> 02:03:41.400
[Guest]: with other people who might be around me, family, whoever I meet, I will often share. Very often,

02:03:41.400 --> 02:03:45.320
[Guest]: I'll tell my, if I'm driving in a car, I'll tell the driver, something that I might have read,

02:03:45.320 --> 02:03:50.520
[Guest]: because I think it might be interesting. And maybe this is again, good old Hindustan

02:03:50.520 --> 02:03:54.920
[Guest]: lever training at work, which is to say, test your ideas, test market new launches.

02:03:55.480 --> 02:03:59.960
[Guest]: You know, don't try and suddenly say you've got this great idea. And one day I'll go and say,

02:03:59.960 --> 02:04:04.840
[Guest]: big bang, here it is. So I like the idea of being able to test it out. So I might even make a,

02:04:04.840 --> 02:04:10.520
[Guest]: I might even put it out on a LinkedIn post and just put out the kernel of an idea and say,

02:04:10.520 --> 02:04:15.160
[Guest]: see, how do people respond? Sometimes you'll figure that you got it wrong, or that there's

02:04:15.160 --> 02:04:19.560
[Guest]: a logical error in what you're saying, or people think this is rubbish, but you learn that bit

02:04:19.560 --> 02:04:23.400
[Guest]: before you actually take it out to the larger world. So that's something else that I find

02:04:23.400 --> 02:04:29.880
[Guest]: extremely useful, which is to share whatever I have. And that helps me to get some kind of

02:04:29.880 --> 02:04:34.520
[Guest]: instant feedback, test market results, as it were, in terms of saying, does this make sense?

02:04:34.520 --> 02:04:39.480
[Guest]: Is there an idea here? Very often, putting an idea out actually gets back a bigger idea.

02:04:40.760 --> 02:04:44.600
[Guest]: You put out something which you don't know how it will work, and you just put it out there,

02:04:44.600 --> 02:04:49.560
[Guest]: and somebody else will make something else out of it. Maybe people will see it very differently

02:04:49.560 --> 02:04:53.240
[Guest]: from the way you might have seen it. And just getting that fresh perspective, just getting a

02:04:53.240 --> 02:04:57.880
[Guest]: new idea, suddenly says, hey, I had an idea, I can put these two together, and now I have an

02:04:57.880 --> 02:05:02.200
[Guest]: even better idea than what I might have had. So that's something else that works.

02:05:03.080 --> 02:05:04.280
[Amit Varma]: Can you give me an example of that?

02:05:04.920 --> 02:05:13.160
[Guest]: So I'm just thinking, I wrote something in my second book, I think, about lessons from a tea

02:05:13.160 --> 02:05:19.160
[Guest]: bag. And I think I had like, you know, leadership lessons from a tea bag. And this was born out of

02:05:19.160 --> 02:05:24.840
[Guest]: a line somewhere about how I read something is like a tea bag, put it in hot water, and you'll

02:05:24.840 --> 02:05:29.560
[Guest]: know how strong it really is. And that's such a powerful idea. And I said, now this is like

02:05:29.560 --> 02:05:34.760
[Guest]: sounding like a leadership idea. And then I kind of looked at what are the other lessons from it.

02:05:34.760 --> 02:05:38.760
[Guest]: And I had five lessons. And I'm just thinking aloud now, but it would be things like, you know,

02:05:38.760 --> 02:05:43.960
[Guest]: the bag of the tea bag needs to be porous. You can have the best tea inside, but if the bag is

02:05:43.960 --> 02:05:48.040
[Guest]: not porous, it won't work. Suggesting therefore, as a leader that you might have all the ideas and

02:05:48.040 --> 02:05:51.640
[Guest]: knowledge, but you need to be porous, need to share, need to get it right. I had things like

02:05:51.640 --> 02:05:56.920
[Guest]: saying at the end of a cup of tea, nobody ever said, wow, what a great tea bag that was. We'd

02:05:56.920 --> 02:06:02.120
[Guest]: say it was good tea. So, you know, as a leader, don't worry about being recognized as this great

02:06:02.120 --> 02:06:05.880
[Guest]: leader. Don't worry about being, you know, 40 under 40 cover of the magazine, et cetera, et

02:06:05.880 --> 02:06:10.760
[Guest]: cetera, focus on building great teams, focus on building great organizations, focus on impacting

02:06:10.760 --> 02:06:15.240
[Guest]: other people. That's what people will remember. No one's going to say, wow, that is a great tea

02:06:15.240 --> 02:06:19.560
[Guest]: bag. So, you know, I had these four or five lessons. What I discovered was that as I started

02:06:19.560 --> 02:06:24.280
[Guest]: talking about it, you know, in the early years, people got fascinated. And suddenly when I finished,

02:06:24.280 --> 02:06:27.160
[Guest]: somebody will come and say, you know what, I can think of one more lesson, sir.

02:06:27.720 --> 02:06:31.320
[Guest]: And somebody will come up with another one and another one. And today I probably have like 10

02:06:31.320 --> 02:06:35.240
[Guest]: lessons from it, which are probably very different from the four I might have started off with when

02:06:35.240 --> 02:06:39.800
[Guest]: I, when I, when I got this going. So it's just a case of literally now the word became popular

02:06:39.800 --> 02:06:44.600
[Guest]: much later, but, you know, crowdsourcing ideas suddenly started to happen. Wow. Fascinating.

02:06:44.600 --> 02:06:48.840
[Amit Varma]: Tell me now about your writing process, because you've mentioned that you were a reader when you

02:06:48.840 --> 02:06:54.360
[Amit Varma]: were a kid, you like to write, you know, you enjoyed writing essays, when you were in IAMA,

02:06:54.360 --> 02:06:58.920
[Amit Varma]: you did your, the magazine that you edited, and which I presume you also wrote for.

02:06:58.920 --> 02:07:04.680
[Amit Varma]: How did your writing develop over this period of time? Like right now, it's very crisp, it's clear

02:07:04.680 --> 02:07:10.520
[Amit Varma]: writing it, you know, it does a wonderful job of communicating ideas of storytelling, there is no

02:07:10.520 --> 02:07:16.360
[Amit Varma]: jargon, it's simple, everyone can understand. Was it always like this? Is there a journey that you

02:07:16.360 --> 02:07:22.120
[Amit Varma]: took to arriving at this? Did you consciously think about what your writing voice should be like?

02:07:22.120 --> 02:07:27.800
[Guest]: Give me a bit of insight into that part of your process. First up, of course, getting a writing

02:07:27.800 --> 02:07:32.600
[Guest]: guru to say that he thinks this writing is pretty good is like, I'll take that. Amit, thanks so much.

02:07:32.600 --> 02:07:39.640
[Guest]: Thanks for those kind words. I must confess, I didn't read too much fiction as a kid.

02:07:39.640 --> 02:07:46.840
[Guest]: A lot of my reading was magazines, was nonfiction, newspapers. So if you ask me who were some of my

02:07:46.840 --> 02:07:54.200
[Guest]: favorite writers as a kid growing up, I would like to say I was a big fan of Dilip Bobb,

02:07:54.200 --> 02:07:58.680
[Guest]: who would write for India Today, you know, and I thought he wrote such a great job of it, or

02:07:59.320 --> 02:08:04.280
[Guest]: a lot of Arun Shourie and his research and his writing in newspapers at that time, I was a big

02:08:04.280 --> 02:08:10.760
[Guest]: fan of that kind of stuff. So for me, reading some of this was what got me excited. And I think at

02:08:10.760 --> 02:08:16.600
[Guest]: some level, keeping it simple was important. I like to say this, I give a lot of credit to my

02:08:16.600 --> 02:08:21.720
[Guest]: English teachers in school, perhaps, and I'd probably call out, you know, there was a lady

02:08:21.720 --> 02:08:28.920
[Guest]: called Ottie D'Souza, and there was Sujata Mitra. And what they did for me was to say that, look,

02:08:28.920 --> 02:08:37.080
[Guest]: it's the idea that matters. It's not about using big words. It's about how can you get that idea

02:08:37.080 --> 02:08:41.000
[Guest]: across to people who may not be familiar with what you're trying to say. And I think for me,

02:08:41.000 --> 02:08:47.960
[Guest]: simplicity therefore became pretty much what I wanted to do. And I'd like to say this, that I

02:08:47.960 --> 02:08:52.840
[Guest]: sometimes think it's actually very self-serving. If it was complicated, I wouldn't understand it.

02:08:52.840 --> 02:08:58.360
[Guest]: If I use big words, I probably wouldn't understand it. And that has kept me on track.

02:08:58.360 --> 02:09:02.440
[Guest]: It kept me on track to say that, you know, use words that you understand, use words that

02:09:02.440 --> 02:09:09.720
[Guest]: your reader would understand. I also think that, I don't think I consciously thought of my writing

02:09:09.720 --> 02:09:16.840
[Guest]: voice, but because I also speak, and I, like I said, a lot of my writing also stems from having

02:09:16.840 --> 02:09:22.280
[Guest]: shared that story or having told something. So I often think that I write like I speak.

02:09:22.280 --> 02:09:28.520
[Guest]: And, and therefore, when I'm writing, I'm not thinking, oh, I'm now writing a book or now this

02:09:28.520 --> 02:09:35.000
[Guest]: has to be serious. I still think I'm talking to someone and I picture my reader, which could be

02:09:35.000 --> 02:09:39.800
[Guest]: when my first book, when I wrote my first book, I thought of my 18 or 20 year old kids to say,

02:09:39.800 --> 02:09:44.360
[Guest]: I'm talking to them. What would I do? I would not use, I wouldn't use big words if I'm talking to

02:09:44.360 --> 02:09:48.760
[Guest]: them. And I kept it that way. I like short sentences because it keeps it simple for me

02:09:48.760 --> 02:09:54.680
[Guest]: to ensure that I don't have to worry about grammar and syntax and saying, have you got this right?

02:09:54.680 --> 02:09:58.680
[Guest]: Or is that last part of the sentence fitting into the first, keep your sentences shorter,

02:09:58.680 --> 02:10:03.880
[Guest]: and you take away the problem of trying to figure that out. So I think my writing style, therefore,

02:10:03.880 --> 02:10:10.520
[Guest]: has always been about keeping it simple, keeping, making it sound like you're listening to me.

02:10:10.520 --> 02:10:16.120
[Guest]: And maybe without, like I said, without consciously realizing it, I, I'd like to believe that that's

02:10:16.120 --> 02:10:20.440
[Guest]: the way it should be for me. If, if someone reads what I've written, they must feel that I'm

02:10:20.440 --> 02:10:26.520
[Guest]: talking to them. And I'm, I'm, I'm having a chat with them, not even talking to them. I'm having,

02:10:26.520 --> 02:10:30.120
[Guest]: we're having this conversation. I'm trying to tell them a story. And that's really what you'll

02:10:30.120 --> 02:10:36.440
[Guest]: get over here. I probably learned this also earlier on that this is the idea of why am I

02:10:36.440 --> 02:10:42.360
[Guest]: writing? This was not to try and impress somebody. It was not to try and tell somebody, look,

02:10:42.360 --> 02:10:47.320
[Guest]: everyone, look, I'm so cool. I can write so well, or, you know, look, everyone, I can use such big

02:10:47.320 --> 02:10:53.080
[Guest]: words. That was not the intent. The intent was to say, you know what, I have something interesting

02:10:53.080 --> 02:10:57.320
[Guest]: to tell you. And let me try and tell you something, which I think is interesting. Now that was the

02:10:57.320 --> 02:11:02.680
[Guest]: brief in a sense to say, keep it interesting. You have an interesting story to tell, make sure it's

02:11:02.680 --> 02:11:06.840
[Guest]: interesting for the other person. The other person doesn't have to tax her head and scratch your

02:11:06.840 --> 02:11:11.160
[Guest]: brains to figure out what happened. Oh, sorry. What was this? What's, how does this fit in?

02:11:11.160 --> 02:11:17.960
[Guest]: And keep it simple for them. One last thought, which is, and I think I'm trying to now trace

02:11:17.960 --> 02:11:22.280
[Guest]: this back and, you know, it's easy to keep looking back and saying, where did this start? But

02:11:24.440 --> 02:11:29.400
[Guest]: I wonder if as a little kid, being this kid who would try and pun too much, you know,

02:11:29.400 --> 02:11:33.400
[Guest]: would try and, you know, and everyone hates a punster and it can be a pain in the neck.

02:11:33.400 --> 02:11:37.240
[Guest]: And, you know, you can be, your pun is indeed lowest form of humor and all of that.

02:11:37.240 --> 02:11:42.280
[Guest]: But I used to be this kind of guy who would always see something else in that word. And I would

02:11:42.280 --> 02:11:46.280
[Guest]: always see another, if somebody said something, I would probably say, that's what you're saying,

02:11:46.280 --> 02:11:53.560
[Guest]: but here's what it could mean. And I think this, this tendency to listen to that song in Hindi and

02:11:53.560 --> 02:11:58.840
[Guest]: to quickly try and say, how would this sound if it had English lyrics, right? What would it do?

02:11:59.480 --> 02:12:03.320
[Guest]: This ability to look at something and say, what does this tell us about the larger world? Maybe

02:12:03.320 --> 02:12:10.120
[Guest]: that is something else that has kind of become what gets me going in my writing, where I try and say

02:12:10.120 --> 02:12:13.240
[Guest]: that, look, maybe there's a lesson to be learned here. Maybe there's something that's important

02:12:13.240 --> 02:12:18.840
[Guest]: here, but it comes from something else which is happening. And I try and bring that to life and

02:12:18.840 --> 02:12:24.440
[Guest]: say, hey, if that's what it is, how does this, what does this tell us about, about life, about

02:12:24.440 --> 02:12:30.120
[Guest]: relationships, about leadership, about the way we are, about the way we behave, the way we think.

02:12:30.120 --> 02:12:33.720
[Guest]: I try and see if I can find lessons in that. And maybe that's something else that that's kind of

02:12:33.720 --> 02:12:38.760
[Guest]: seeped into the storytelling that I, that I enjoy doing. Yeah. Yeah. That's, that's kind of

02:12:38.760 --> 02:12:43.480
[Amit Varma]: fascinating number of things to take away there. And one which I find particularly interesting is

02:12:43.480 --> 02:12:48.360
[Amit Varma]: this notion that your mindfulness of language can increase because you were a punner. Like I also,

02:12:48.360 --> 02:12:52.360
[Amit Varma]: of course, don't approve of puns and very often it's just the writer drawing attention to their

02:12:52.360 --> 02:12:57.080
[Amit Varma]: writing, which detracts from the narrative and you don't really want that. But at the same time,

02:12:57.080 --> 02:13:02.840
[Amit Varma]: it's important and it's important for writers, especially to look at with granular detail at

02:13:02.840 --> 02:13:08.520
[Amit Varma]: the language that they are using and to have a sense of what effect their language has on the

02:13:08.520 --> 02:13:12.200
[Amit Varma]: reader, because every choice that is made in a particular piece has an effect on the reader and

02:13:12.200 --> 02:13:17.080
[Amit Varma]: you want to be mindful of that. So this is an interesting angle, that tendency for sort of

02:13:17.080 --> 02:13:22.600
[Amit Varma]: fancy writing, doing, you know, writerly florid prose. I think perhaps I have often mused comes

02:13:22.600 --> 02:13:28.120
[Amit Varma]: from that old post-colonial hangover, where for decades, and to some extent, even now,

02:13:28.120 --> 02:13:33.400
[Amit Varma]: English was a marker of class and, you know, in India, and if you wanted to signal your

02:13:33.400 --> 02:13:38.920
[Amit Varma]: sophistication, you do it with these big, fancy, pompous phrases, instead of saying,

02:13:38.920 --> 02:13:44.120
[Amit Varma]: you know, stop this nonsense, you'll say, put an end to this pontificatory blah, blah, blah, and

02:13:44.120 --> 02:13:48.680
[Amit Varma]: so on and so forth. And again, right as you speak is something I talk a lot about, because I think

02:13:48.680 --> 02:13:53.960
[Amit Varma]: people misunderstand it. People think that right as you speak means that the way that we are speaking,

02:13:53.960 --> 02:13:58.440
[Amit Varma]: you write like that. And obviously, that won't work, because there'll be all these long run

02:13:58.440 --> 02:14:04.200
[Amit Varma]: on sentences, there'll be these sort of pauses and ums and ahs and words like like and whatever,

02:14:04.200 --> 02:14:08.200
[Amit Varma]: because when we are speaking, there's no filter between our brains and what we are saying, which

02:14:08.200 --> 02:14:12.600
[Amit Varma]: is fine, because we are saying it in the moment. What right as you speak really means is that when

02:14:12.600 --> 02:14:17.960
[Amit Varma]: you read something out, it should sound as if it is something that you would say in conversation,

02:14:17.960 --> 02:14:22.680
[Amit Varma]: it should sound natural to you, which is why for most of the writers that I read, including you,

02:14:22.680 --> 02:14:26.280
[Amit Varma]: most of the writers that I know personally, rather, including you, you know, when I read

02:14:26.280 --> 02:14:32.440
[Amit Varma]: something by them, I can actually hear it in their voice, because it is so sort of natural to them.

02:14:32.440 --> 02:14:37.880
[Amit Varma]: And I think people lose this people try to be like, too writerly and like I think William Zinsser

02:14:37.880 --> 02:14:43.400
[Amit Varma]: once said that if there is a word that you would not use in conversation, never use it in your

02:14:43.400 --> 02:14:49.800
[Amit Varma]: writing. And I agree with that, you know, so all great points and great lessons in there.

02:14:49.800 --> 02:14:54.920
[Guest]: I must ask you a question here Amit and something that I've not really thought too deeply about,

02:14:54.920 --> 02:15:01.160
[Guest]: but I've sometimes wondered. So when I went to school in and I learned English, I've never

02:15:01.160 --> 02:15:08.680
[Guest]: studied Ren and Martin and grammar and I've I didn't really understand what, you know, past

02:15:08.680 --> 02:15:14.280
[Guest]: perfect and, you know, all the terms that we use to describe, I've never studied or learned that.

02:15:14.280 --> 02:15:19.640
[Guest]: And I find it fascinating that without having learned that, as it were, I learned how to read

02:15:19.640 --> 02:15:24.360
[Guest]: and write a little bit. And I'm just wondering, how does this fit in with this whole thing about

02:15:24.360 --> 02:15:28.360
[Guest]: saying that if you need to know something, you need to understand the science behind it, perhaps,

02:15:28.360 --> 02:15:34.280
[Amit Varma]: or is how does this work? I actually think that taking Ren and Martin too seriously, for example,

02:15:34.280 --> 02:15:39.000
[Amit Varma]: might be counterproductive, because what each of these grammar books or write like this books will

02:15:39.000 --> 02:15:44.920
[Amit Varma]: give you is an ossified version of language is a convention of a previous time. I think the way we

02:15:44.920 --> 02:15:49.800
[Amit Varma]: learn everything is by reading a lot. There's no substitute for that we learn how to write by

02:15:49.800 --> 02:15:55.480
[Amit Varma]: osmosis by reading a lot. And that reading can be mindful, where you know, Arundhati Roy,

02:15:55.480 --> 02:15:59.720
[Amit Varma]: after she won the Booker in 96 for the God of small things once said that the quality of a

02:15:59.720 --> 02:16:05.160
[Amit Varma]: reading changed when she became a writer, which means that you're looking for all the things that

02:16:05.160 --> 02:16:09.880
[Amit Varma]: writers do, the tricks they use, how they build rhythm, how they do transitions, how they tell

02:16:09.880 --> 02:16:15.000
[Amit Varma]: their stories, all of those things. But for me, any kind of reading is great, even mindless reading,

02:16:15.000 --> 02:16:20.200
[Amit Varma]: like I'll often tell participants of my course that do not become very conscious about what you

02:16:20.200 --> 02:16:24.600
[Amit Varma]: are reading or think that some things are infrared and some things are things that you should read,

02:16:24.600 --> 02:16:29.080
[Amit Varma]: read anything that you enjoy reading, because anything that you enjoy reading is by default

02:16:29.080 --> 02:16:33.160
[Amit Varma]: doing something right. And you learn osmosis from that. So whenever somebody asked me, how do I

02:16:33.160 --> 02:16:38.840
[Amit Varma]: improve my grammar? How do I improve my vocabulary? The answer always is that there is no instruction

02:16:38.840 --> 02:16:43.880
[Amit Varma]: book which will teach you all of this, you just read a lot. And you kind of learn it by osmosis,

02:16:43.880 --> 02:16:49.720
[Amit Varma]: which is why I'm never critical of a person whose grammar isn't great, who are making grammatical

02:16:49.720 --> 02:16:54.360
[Amit Varma]: errors, or who's may not know many big words, I'm never critical of them, because those are

02:16:54.360 --> 02:16:59.640
[Amit Varma]: things that you pick up along the way. What is more important is the honesty in your storytelling

02:16:59.640 --> 02:17:04.120
[Amit Varma]: that are you putting yourself at the service of your narrative? Or are you trying to impress

02:17:04.120 --> 02:17:08.840
[Amit Varma]: somebody with Oh, look what a good writer I am, I know all these big words and fancy phrases.

02:17:08.840 --> 02:17:13.560
[Amit Varma]: So yeah, so my short answer, I gave a long answer. But the short answer would really be

02:17:13.560 --> 02:17:19.960
[Amit Varma]: that we learn by osmosis. So tell me about this particular book, you know, you've referred in

02:17:19.960 --> 02:17:25.320
[Amit Varma]: this book to things that at some points, you'll say April 2020, this happened, or, you know,

02:17:25.320 --> 02:17:29.720
[Amit Varma]: you've referred to the lockdown and the pandemic times and all of that. How did the idea for this

02:17:29.720 --> 02:17:36.440
[Amit Varma]: book kind of come about, you know, and what was the process of writing it like? And is there

02:17:36.440 --> 02:17:42.200
[Amit Varma]: something that this book has gained from being written after the pandemic began? When let us say

02:17:42.200 --> 02:17:46.280
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, the old normal became the new normal, that is such a cliche, I even feel embarrassed

02:17:46.280 --> 02:17:52.680
[Amit Varma]: using these phrases. But you know, is there something in the book that was formed because of

02:17:52.680 --> 02:18:00.520
[Guest]: that period? The first bit is that as my Penguin editor will tell you that the pandemic ensured

02:18:00.520 --> 02:18:08.600
[Guest]: that I wrote the book. So it's been a fairly long time in the works. And it's been an idea.

02:18:08.600 --> 02:18:13.800
[Guest]: But I guess when the pandemic hit, and you suddenly realize that you have a little more

02:18:13.800 --> 02:18:19.480
[Guest]: time on your hands, you're at home, I think it just took away one more excuse. And as I looked at,

02:18:20.360 --> 02:18:26.280
[Guest]: so if I flashback to April last year, and I told myself that the world is changing a little bit,

02:18:26.280 --> 02:18:30.040
[Guest]: no more travel, no more having to be on flights all the time, you're at home, you're doing everything

02:18:30.040 --> 02:18:34.280
[Guest]: sitting in front of a computer. So it's a great opportunity to do a few things. And those few

02:18:34.280 --> 02:18:38.520
[Guest]: things included learning new stuff. So I said, Hey, what can you learn? So I tried to learn two

02:18:38.520 --> 02:18:43.000
[Guest]: or three things that that might have helped. And I told myself, not a bad idea to say, let's finish

02:18:43.000 --> 02:18:48.040
[Guest]: the book now. So let's get that book out and start writing. So I think that the discipline probably

02:18:48.040 --> 02:18:55.800
[Guest]: got a little got some impetus, thanks to the pandemic. Did that in any other way, influence

02:18:55.800 --> 02:19:04.200
[Guest]: what I do? I think a lot of it goes back to my little attempt to try and say that I actually

02:19:04.200 --> 02:19:11.480
[Guest]: think there are things people need to know. And we don't get taught those things. And sometimes

02:19:11.480 --> 02:19:16.440
[Guest]: just being just a little thing someone tells you can make it so much more powerful. I'll give an

02:19:16.440 --> 02:19:21.720
[Guest]: example. And I'm not saying this because I'm on your podcast, Amit. But just this, it never struck

02:19:21.720 --> 02:19:27.560
[Guest]: me that adverbs are bad until I took that course. And, you know, and to answer that question about

02:19:27.560 --> 02:19:32.280
[Guest]: Atul Berede and Sachin Tendulkar and all of that, I think if you don't get your hand in line with

02:19:32.280 --> 02:19:36.920
[Guest]: your foot, no matter who you are, you're going to be in trouble. And I just think that one little

02:19:36.920 --> 02:19:42.920
[Guest]: thing told me so much about my own writing. And I used to feel bad when I'd get rid of those

02:19:42.920 --> 02:19:49.640
[Guest]: adverbs. I thought they were adding so much to my writing, to realizing that, you know,

02:19:49.640 --> 02:19:54.360
[Guest]: it's such a drag, just take it off. Horror of horrors. I did a count once after I wrote something

02:19:54.360 --> 02:20:02.280
[Guest]: and I had something like in a 700 word piece, I used the word just 14 times, you know, just like

02:20:02.280 --> 02:20:09.720
[Guest]: that. And I thought it sounded just right. And anybody who said it's not right, I'd say, you

02:20:09.720 --> 02:20:15.080
[Guest]: know, you must be just kidding. You know, and I didn't realize it. So that's my point. Sometimes

02:20:15.080 --> 02:20:20.040
[Guest]: you're not aware of some of these things and it's not. And I could turn around and say that this

02:20:20.040 --> 02:20:23.480
[Guest]: isn't rocket science. And, you know, surely someone I could have picked it up, et cetera,

02:20:23.480 --> 02:20:29.160
[Guest]: et cetera. But the problem is there are some simple things that we need to know about what we do.

02:20:29.160 --> 02:20:34.920
[Guest]: And no one tells us that yet. And it just so happens that no one tells us. If we knew it,

02:20:35.720 --> 02:20:39.480
[Guest]: it could make a difference to our life. And it's not to suggest that this is the one thing you need

02:20:39.480 --> 02:20:44.840
[Guest]: to do and this will change your world. That's not the intent. These are small things that I think we

02:20:44.840 --> 02:20:47.960
[Guest]: all need to know. And that's really what got me started on saying, so what are some of the things

02:20:47.960 --> 02:20:52.520
[Guest]: that I might have learned, which I think could be useful? And that's how I started to write.

02:20:52.520 --> 02:20:58.280
[Guest]: Um, I think a good, a good practice in this was also to say that push yourself to write.

02:20:58.840 --> 02:21:02.680
[Guest]: And I wish I'd be a little more consistent, but some of the best moments I've had or the best

02:21:02.680 --> 02:21:07.640
[Guest]: months I've had are when I would tell myself that I will write something every day on LinkedIn,

02:21:08.440 --> 02:21:12.360
[Guest]: you know, I would just post something. And here's the interesting bit, and this is true,

02:21:12.360 --> 02:21:16.840
[Guest]: whether you're, you know, if you want to write a book or if you tell yourself that you will write

02:21:16.840 --> 02:21:21.240
[Guest]: posts on whatever's your medium of choice, if you sit down on the first day to write,

02:21:21.240 --> 02:21:25.240
[Guest]: you will say, I have nothing to write about. There are no ideas and there will be no ideas.

02:21:25.240 --> 02:21:28.520
[Guest]: And then you can get up and go and say, I have no idea. So I'm not going to write today.

02:21:28.520 --> 02:21:34.600
[Guest]: But if you force yourself to sit there and say, failure is not an option. You, there is no cop

02:21:34.600 --> 02:21:39.880
[Guest]: out. Okay. You have to write that piece today, which could be a hundred words or 200 words or

02:21:39.880 --> 02:21:44.840
[Guest]: whatever it is, but you have to write it. And suddenly something will come to your mind and

02:21:44.840 --> 02:21:48.920
[Guest]: you'll write a 30, 40 words, which will be rubbish. But those 30, 40 words will tell you

02:21:48.920 --> 02:21:53.480
[Guest]: that actually there is another idea coming from here and that will then become a piece.

02:21:53.480 --> 02:21:57.960
[Guest]: And by the time you're finishing, you don't want to get up because you think you've got something

02:21:57.960 --> 02:22:01.160
[Guest]: really nice happening over here and you want to kind of stay with it. And there is another idea

02:22:01.160 --> 02:22:06.280
[Guest]: that you've got from here. And, and I think that can become a great way to tell yourself that,

02:22:06.280 --> 02:22:10.360
[Guest]: Hey, this book can happen. And for me, very often, if I sat there and said, I need to write a book,

02:22:10.360 --> 02:22:15.240
[Guest]: I can't decide what to write about. And it's not like the book started by saying,

02:22:15.240 --> 02:22:19.720
[Guest]: I have a great title. How come no one told me that all I have to do is to think of stories

02:22:19.720 --> 02:22:23.320
[Guest]: that will fit into that. That's not how it happened. I just had to think of what can I say.

02:22:23.320 --> 02:22:26.760
[Guest]: And gradually I think one thing leads to another and to another and to another,

02:22:26.760 --> 02:22:31.240
[Guest]: and all of that happens because you tell yourself you have to sit and write.

02:22:32.280 --> 02:22:36.040
[Guest]: And I think to anybody out there who wants to write a book, and I often, you know,

02:22:36.040 --> 02:22:39.960
[Guest]: I'm sure this is advice you also gave us and you give everybody, which is to say,

02:22:39.960 --> 02:22:47.320
[Guest]: if you want to write a book first, just write. We worry about, will I find a publisher?

02:22:47.320 --> 02:22:51.640
[Guest]: Will the book sell? You know, how is distribution? What are royalties? How much margin?

02:22:52.280 --> 02:22:56.840
[Guest]: Forget all of that. If you want to write a book first, just write. The rest of it will take care

02:22:56.840 --> 02:23:01.400
[Guest]: of itself. And I think if we can do anything, and maybe this is true, not just for writing,

02:23:01.400 --> 02:23:05.800
[Guest]: it's true for anything else. I'll give you another one, Amit. And, you know, after one of my books,

02:23:05.800 --> 02:23:12.600
[Guest]: I was in Kathmandu for a Nepal Lit Fest. Rare occasion when someone who's written an ordinary

02:23:12.600 --> 02:23:17.960
[Guest]: book on non-fiction gets called to a Lit Fest. But for me, the high point was that Shobha Dey

02:23:17.960 --> 02:23:22.760
[Guest]: was there. And she was a fellow speaker at that Lit Fest, which also meant that, you know,

02:23:22.760 --> 02:23:26.840
[Guest]: the budget's being small for the organizer. They had one car to ferry us from one place to another.

02:23:27.640 --> 02:23:31.800
[Guest]: You know, I wasn't complaining and I'm hoping Shobha wasn't either. But as I was talking to

02:23:31.800 --> 02:23:36.600
[Guest]: her, she said something, you know, we all, you know, and again, I'm saying this as a young kid,

02:23:36.600 --> 02:23:40.600
[Guest]: I thought Shobha Dey was this great, you know, was a fabulous woman. And whether it was Celebrity

02:23:40.600 --> 02:23:45.320
[Guest]: Magazine, which she started, or just Neeta's Natter and Stardust, and all of that. Forget

02:23:45.320 --> 02:23:50.040
[Guest]: the books. I thought she was just terrific. And a big fan of all that she did. And you know,

02:23:50.040 --> 02:23:55.720
[Guest]: a little bit about her, you know, the books she writes, her husband, society, she's obviously

02:23:55.720 --> 02:23:59.960
[Guest]: this, you know, socialite, all of that. And I'm sitting over there with her and we're talking

02:23:59.960 --> 02:24:04.920
[Guest]: about something and she tells me something. She says, you know what, Prakash, I write 3,000 words

02:24:04.920 --> 02:24:12.200
[Guest]: every day. It is a must. It could be a column. It could be a book. It could be a piece that

02:24:12.200 --> 02:24:17.880
[Guest]: somebody has commissioned. It could be notes to myself. But I will write 3,000 words every day.

02:24:17.880 --> 02:24:22.920
[Guest]: I will not go to bed if I haven't written 3,000 words. And then I can picture her saying this.

02:24:22.920 --> 02:24:29.160
[Guest]: And she says, it's like Riyaz for a singer. You know, if you have to be a singer, you have to do

02:24:29.160 --> 02:24:35.960
[Guest]: your Riyaz. For me, this is my Riyaz. And here I am running a company and writing a book and

02:24:35.960 --> 02:24:40.680
[Guest]: thinking, you know, this is all cool. And I say, wow, this is such a powerful thought. And every

02:24:40.680 --> 02:24:46.040
[Guest]: time I tell my, now when I try to write and I'm thinking of an excuse, I think of saying,

02:24:46.040 --> 02:24:52.120
[Guest]: my diary is not half as busy as Shobha's diary might be. And if she can find time to write those

02:24:52.120 --> 02:24:58.600
[Amit Varma]: 3,000 words, you know, what's my excuse? Yeah. And in fact, that's both something to learn from

02:24:58.600 --> 02:25:02.120
[Amit Varma]: and something not to learn from there. And what one can learn from there is, of course, the

02:25:02.120 --> 02:25:07.640
[Amit Varma]: importance of Riyaz. Like I keep saying, like, to me, the facility to write is like, it's akin

02:25:07.640 --> 02:25:12.360
[Amit Varma]: to a muscle. So if you want to grow your writing muscle, you know, you have to do what you do to

02:25:12.360 --> 02:25:17.480
[Amit Varma]: grow your other muscles. You don't take a gym membership and without going to the gym by having

02:25:17.480 --> 02:25:21.560
[Amit Varma]: an intellectual understanding of how the body works, grow your muscles. You got to go to the

02:25:21.560 --> 02:25:26.840
[Amit Varma]: gym every day and get the job done. Similar thing with writing. However, 3,000 words a day is

02:25:26.840 --> 02:25:31.560
[Amit Varma]: intimidating. Like the advice that I give in my course, and I have a slide just for this,

02:25:33.160 --> 02:25:38.200
[Amit Varma]: spoiler for those who haven't attended it yet, is set a really modest target. Like what I say is

02:25:38.200 --> 02:25:43.960
[Amit Varma]: 300 words a day or even 200 words a day. You know, just write 200 words a day. And the thing with

02:25:43.960 --> 02:25:49.080
[Amit Varma]: that is that many days you'll write more than that. Many days you will be in a difficult situation

02:25:49.080 --> 02:25:52.760
[Amit Varma]: where you have fever and you're in bed or you have flights to catch in a post-COVID world,

02:25:52.760 --> 02:25:58.760
[Amit Varma]: obviously. And you know, but you can still take out your phone and write those 200 words on your

02:25:58.760 --> 02:26:03.560
[Amit Varma]: smartphone. And in fact, since I started speaking after you finished, I've probably spoken twice as

02:26:03.560 --> 02:26:09.240
[Amit Varma]: much. We speak around 200 words in a minute. It's very easy to write. But what it does, and even if

02:26:09.240 --> 02:26:13.000
[Amit Varma]: you have nothing to write about, write a daily journal, write about what's been happening in

02:26:13.000 --> 02:26:18.680
[Amit Varma]: your life. The point is, number one, the juices are flowing, the muscle is working out. Number two,

02:26:18.680 --> 02:26:23.400
[Amit Varma]: it accumulates. Even if you write exactly 200 a day, and nobody will obviously stop at the 200th

02:26:23.400 --> 02:26:28.280
[Amit Varma]: word if it's and or but. But even if you were to write that much, that's 75,000 words in a year.

02:26:28.280 --> 02:26:33.560
[Amit Varma]: That's like a novel length thing, you know. So the important thing is, like you correctly said,

02:26:33.560 --> 02:26:38.840
[Amit Varma]: just get out there, just do it every day. The process is what matters. The goals will happen

02:26:38.840 --> 02:26:43.880
[Guest]: by themselves. I know you said this, Amit, and I remember you telling us in this course,

02:26:43.880 --> 02:26:49.480
[Guest]: why 200 words is an important one was, I remember you said, even if you're going back to the airport

02:26:49.480 --> 02:26:54.600
[Guest]: after a meeting, you know, 200 words is something you can type out onto your phone, right? So you

02:26:54.600 --> 02:27:00.280
[Guest]: just take away the excuse for not writing. And I think that's a great start. But here's the

02:27:00.280 --> 02:27:05.000
[Guest]: interesting bit. I have found that once you get into the swim of things, once you get into the

02:27:05.000 --> 02:27:11.080
[Guest]: habit, you start saying, wow, there is more to say, there is more you want to do, and that 200

02:27:11.080 --> 02:27:16.440
[Guest]: will soon become 500. And once you become class five, it'll become 700. And then if you become

02:27:16.440 --> 02:27:22.280
[Guest]: postgraduate, like Shobha probably is, it becomes 3000 words. But the second bit I want to say here

02:27:22.280 --> 02:27:27.960
[Guest]: is that apart from the writing bit, the big problem most of us have is when you sit down,

02:27:27.960 --> 02:27:33.160
[Guest]: you wonder, I have nothing to say, I have nothing to write, what will I write about? Right? And

02:27:33.160 --> 02:27:38.920
[Guest]: that becomes a reason. So we wait for once I have something to write about, then I will sit and

02:27:38.920 --> 02:27:44.840
[Guest]: write. And I'm saying, maybe you want to switch that, sit to write, and something will come to

02:27:44.840 --> 02:27:50.440
[Guest]: you. It may not have been there. I have found this happens to me so many times, you know, and

02:27:50.440 --> 02:27:53.720
[Guest]: there'll be days when I say, gosh, I haven't written, I must write today, I'll get up in the

02:27:53.720 --> 02:27:57.480
[Guest]: morning, and I'll tell my wife, I have to write, I'm not going for a walk in the morning, 5am,

02:27:57.480 --> 02:28:02.200
[Guest]: I'm sitting at my desk here. I don't know what I'm going to do. But I'm sitting over there,

02:28:02.200 --> 02:28:07.000
[Guest]: and I'm saying, I need to write. And surprise, surprise, something will come. And I think that's

02:28:07.000 --> 02:28:11.000
[Guest]: something else that maybe, you know, anybody who wants to write to try and figure this don't wait

02:28:11.560 --> 02:28:16.680
[Guest]: for that idea. And I'll tell you another little story. I mean, I once was, I was on a flight,

02:28:16.680 --> 02:28:20.520
[Guest]: and the gentleman sitting next to me and this is the good old days when you know, I'm still

02:28:20.520 --> 02:28:25.720
[Guest]: corporate and jet airways is still a thing and business class is still a thing. And I surprise,

02:28:25.720 --> 02:28:30.760
[Guest]: surprise, there's this man sitting next to me who looks very much like Gulzar. And, you know,

02:28:30.760 --> 02:28:35.720
[Guest]: before I know it, the lady who's serving us gives him the glass of fresh lime and says,

02:28:35.720 --> 02:28:40.360
[Guest]: is there anything I can get you, Gulzar sahib? And I think my flight is made, I'm gonna really

02:28:40.360 --> 02:28:45.960
[Guest]: gonna enjoy this one. And I find that, you know, Gulzar sahib has this diary, like a loose leaf

02:28:45.960 --> 02:28:50.680
[Guest]: diary, a handbook of sorts, which he's got with him. And he plonks that into the pocket in front,

02:28:50.680 --> 02:28:55.400
[Guest]: as even as he settles into a seat. And I'm curious, and I asked him, you know,

02:28:55.400 --> 02:28:59.320
[Guest]: why have you got that diary? And he's got a pen, nice looking fountain pens. And I said,

02:28:59.320 --> 02:29:05.160
[Guest]: is that because mid flight, you might have this great idea, or a line might occur to you and you

02:29:05.160 --> 02:29:09.320
[Guest]: don't want to lose it, so you want to write it down? Is that why you have that? He says,

02:29:12.120 --> 02:29:17.960
[Guest]: I have to deliver three songs by the end of the day. And I have work to do. So, I have to sit

02:29:17.960 --> 02:29:23.160
[Guest]: and write. It's not like I'll wait for an idea. If I write, I might get an idea. You know,

02:29:23.160 --> 02:29:28.280
[Guest]: and I think that's a, if it happens to someone as great as Gulzar, maybe it's an interesting one

02:29:28.280 --> 02:29:32.360
[Guest]: for all of us to consider that don't wait for inspiration to strike before you write. Sit

02:29:32.360 --> 02:29:35.960
[Amit Varma]: down to write and I think inspiration will find you. Yeah, in fact, in my course, I have a slide

02:29:35.960 --> 02:29:40.680
[Amit Varma]: which has a quote by Joan Didion where she says, quote, I don't know what I think until I write it

02:29:40.680 --> 02:29:45.800
[Amit Varma]: down. Stop quote. So, you know, even if you have nothing to write about, just, just, you know,

02:29:45.800 --> 02:29:51.320
[Amit Varma]: sit, exercise that muscle, and magic will eventually happen. You've got to kind of have

02:29:51.320 --> 02:29:55.480
[Amit Varma]: that faith. But don't start with a big target. Start with a small target. The big targets will

02:29:55.480 --> 02:29:59.480
[Amit Varma]: happen. 3000 words a day can also happen more than that can happen. Like one of my favorite

02:29:59.480 --> 02:30:04.440
[Amit Varma]: writers is a French novelist, Georges Simenon, who wrote some 400 novels in his time, created

02:30:04.440 --> 02:30:08.920
[Amit Varma]: the Detective Magret, but also wrote a bunch of I think they're called Roman Adours, which are

02:30:08.920 --> 02:30:14.520
[Amit Varma]: these wonderful novels about everyday life. And he gave an interview to Paris Review when he was,

02:30:14.520 --> 02:30:19.640
[Amit Varma]: I think, around 50 years old. And his process then was he would call his doc, when he felt ready to

02:30:19.640 --> 02:30:23.800
[Amit Varma]: write a novel, the doc would take the blood pressure, give the go ahead. And Simenon would

02:30:23.800 --> 02:30:28.360
[Amit Varma]: then lock himself up in a room for seven days, like his wife would leave food outside the door.

02:30:28.360 --> 02:30:32.840
[Amit Varma]: And he'd write 7000 words a day. And at the end of a week, he's got around 50,000 words,

02:30:32.840 --> 02:30:37.160
[Amit Varma]: send it off to the publisher calls the doctor, doctor comes takes his blood pressure says,

02:30:37.160 --> 02:30:42.680
[Amit Varma]: okay, you need to rest till so and so date. And then I will come and check you again. But this

02:30:42.680 --> 02:30:47.240
[Amit Varma]: is one of those things which I would say, please do not try this at home. You know, start small

02:30:47.240 --> 02:30:51.480
[Amit Varma]: start achievable. Otherwise, you know what a big target does to finish that thought is,

02:30:51.480 --> 02:30:55.320
[Amit Varma]: let's say you set yourself a big target, I'll write 1000 words a day also, okay, you set yourself

02:30:55.320 --> 02:31:00.120
[Amit Varma]: that target, then you will fall off the wagon, there will be days when you just can't. And then

02:31:00.120 --> 02:31:03.960
[Amit Varma]: you start beating yourself up. And then you say, yeah, writing life is not for me,

02:31:03.960 --> 02:31:08.040
[Amit Varma]: ya mere se nahi hoga, like my corporate mein toh achcha kama raha ho, why should I do this?

02:31:08.040 --> 02:31:12.520
[Amit Varma]: And that affects your self image. And it becomes a vicious cycle, where because you don't write,

02:31:12.520 --> 02:31:17.880
[Amit Varma]: you tell yourself you can't write, and that feeds into itself. So the one way to break that is

02:31:18.600 --> 02:31:24.040
[Amit Varma]: modest targets. Let's start by talking about your book. And when I read the book, in my mind,

02:31:24.040 --> 02:31:30.040
[Amit Varma]: I was sort of dividing it into personal lessons, that is self actualization kind of lessons,

02:31:30.040 --> 02:31:34.120
[Amit Varma]: and other lessons, outward facing lessons, like leadership lessons, and team building lessons,

02:31:34.120 --> 02:31:38.920
[Amit Varma]: and all of that. And some of it struck me. And what I again, love the how you bring your own

02:31:38.920 --> 02:31:43.480
[Amit Varma]: personal stories into these, like to give you a point of feedback for your next book,

02:31:43.480 --> 02:31:47.960
[Amit Varma]: the entire book is filled with stories. But there were stories that I really enjoyed were the

02:31:47.960 --> 02:31:52.200
[Amit Varma]: personal ones, and not so much, you know, the ones of other people and other things, because

02:31:52.200 --> 02:31:56.840
[Amit Varma]: there's just so much charm to them. And one of those stories was, you talk about how you've gone

02:31:56.840 --> 02:32:01.080
[Amit Varma]: on a drive with your twins, I think their nicknames are Abby and Toots, I hope they don't

02:32:01.080 --> 02:32:05.960
[Amit Varma]: mind, I'm just quoting you. So at one point, when you're going back to the car, your daughter says

02:32:05.960 --> 02:32:09.800
[Amit Varma]: that, hey, I want to sit on the right side, because we both sit at the back. And then the

02:32:09.800 --> 02:32:14.600
[Amit Varma]: son immediately says, No, no, I want to sit on the right side. And back and forth kind of happens,

02:32:14.600 --> 02:32:18.680
[Amit Varma]: and you find a compromise and you get to the car. And when you get to the car, your son says,

02:32:18.680 --> 02:32:23.400
[Amit Varma]: by the way, which is the right side, which is such a remarkable story, and which tells you so much

02:32:23.400 --> 02:32:28.440
[Amit Varma]: about human nature, that he just wanted to sit on the right side, because that's what his sister

02:32:28.440 --> 02:32:33.960
[Amit Varma]: wanted. He didn't even know what the right side was. And similarly, in our lives, we set our goals

02:32:33.960 --> 02:32:40.280
[Amit Varma]: and our benchmarks and our desires by what other people around us are doing. And your point there

02:32:40.280 --> 02:32:46.520
[Amit Varma]: is be mindful of this and avoid this trap, and so on. Tell me a little bit more about this. And

02:32:46.520 --> 02:32:51.080
[Amit Varma]: does this have personal resonance beyond this little story about your kids? Like,

02:32:52.280 --> 02:32:57.080
[Amit Varma]: do you think you made this mistake sometimes? And you know, what was the nature of the mistake?

02:32:57.080 --> 02:33:04.680
[Guest]: How did you get past it? I think it's such a small, a tiny little story. It actually,

02:33:04.680 --> 02:33:10.200
[Guest]: you know, it certainly has reverberations across everything that we do. And it certainly it has

02:33:10.200 --> 02:33:15.080
[Guest]: for me, personally speaking, it has for all of us. I think if you look at the number of people who

02:33:15.080 --> 02:33:19.960
[Guest]: end up doing engineering, you know, why do they do engineering? And if you look at the way we

02:33:19.960 --> 02:33:27.640
[Guest]: select careers, jobs, it's almost like, and I said this at some level, that as a kid, if you're first

02:33:27.640 --> 02:33:32.920
[Guest]: in class or second in class, you don't, and like I said, South Indian middle class home, Bombay

02:33:32.920 --> 02:33:38.600
[Guest]: school, you don't do arts. You don't do arts. Why? Because it's not the done thing. It's not,

02:33:38.600 --> 02:33:42.840
[Guest]: you know, it's not, you do it because everybody wants it. Why do people want something? Because

02:33:42.840 --> 02:33:48.840
[Guest]: everybody else wants it. You have hot jobs, you have hot careers, you have employers who are

02:33:48.840 --> 02:33:54.520
[Guest]: being sought after, courses being sought after because everybody wants it. We forget whether

02:33:54.520 --> 02:33:59.880
[Guest]: it's something that suits our, is that what's going to make me happy? We don't even pause to

02:33:59.880 --> 02:34:05.080
[Guest]: think about it. And I think it's, I'm sure it's happened to me in my life. There have been

02:34:05.080 --> 02:34:09.800
[Guest]: decisions where you do things because everybody's doing it. You don't want to miss the bus. You

02:34:09.800 --> 02:34:15.880
[Guest]: worry that you might miss the bus. I also think that, again, optimist, positive and all of that.

02:34:15.880 --> 02:34:20.840
[Guest]: So I don't have too many regrets in my life. And I keep thinking that jo hua, it's taught me

02:34:20.840 --> 02:34:25.000
[Guest]: something which has helped me to be where I am today. And therefore, that's been, you know,

02:34:25.000 --> 02:34:31.000
[Guest]: value for time and money spent over there. But I do think that in a lot of my decisions, a lot

02:34:31.000 --> 02:34:37.960
[Guest]: of our decisions, it's not, I wasn't this young person who kind of said, I don't care. I will do

02:34:37.960 --> 02:34:42.520
[Guest]: what my heart says. I will, you know, I don't care. I don't think I was that kind of person.

02:34:42.520 --> 02:34:48.120
[Guest]: And it's not easy. I think there are a lot of pressures, but I think just being aware of it

02:34:48.120 --> 02:34:52.440
[Guest]: can sometimes make it, you know, if you took 10 decisions, which were of that kind, maybe

02:34:52.440 --> 02:34:58.760
[Guest]: awareness that don't do something because other people want it. Don't do something just because

02:34:59.320 --> 02:35:02.680
[Guest]: if other people want it, you don't want them to get it. You want to get it before them. If they're,

02:35:02.680 --> 02:35:09.400
[Guest]: you know, very often you see this happen in so many ways in our lives that people will get

02:35:09.400 --> 02:35:16.440
[Guest]: possessive about something the minute they realize somebody else wants it. They may not have any use

02:35:16.440 --> 02:35:23.080
[Guest]: for it, but if somebody else wants it, it suddenly becomes something that we need. You know, and I'm

02:35:23.080 --> 02:35:28.440
[Guest]: just imagining in a middle-class home, you know, if you went to your, I hope it doesn't happen too

02:35:28.440 --> 02:35:34.440
[Guest]: much, but you know, you can imagine this where you go and say, you know, can I borrow your toaster

02:35:34.440 --> 02:35:39.960
[Guest]: for a few? No, just now my daughter's doing a course in making sado bread and all of that. So

02:35:39.960 --> 02:35:43.720
[Guest]: we are eating a lot of bread now, so I can't give you the toaster. Actually, I only realized I have

02:35:43.720 --> 02:35:48.680
[Guest]: a toaster at home and you asked me for it. But that tells me that I need it. And maybe there's

02:35:48.680 --> 02:35:54.600
[Guest]: a mindset thing here that if you want it, maybe it's got value I hadn't seen, and I want to hold

02:35:54.600 --> 02:35:59.000
[Guest]: on to it. And that came through for me in something as simple as this to say like, you know, and it

02:35:59.000 --> 02:36:03.640
[Guest]: happens to all of us. I think there's, like I say in the book, there's a little bit of that baby Abby

02:36:03.640 --> 02:36:09.560
[Guest]: in all of us, you know, who's looking for things without knowing why he wants them, who wants them

02:36:09.560 --> 02:36:14.680
[Amit Varma]: because somebody else wants them. No, it's part of human nature. Like there's another story in

02:36:14.680 --> 02:36:19.640
[Amit Varma]: your book where you talk about hanging around outside Churchgate just to see how the markets

02:36:19.640 --> 02:36:25.000
[Amit Varma]: are functioning. And you look at this textile shop where there are these three, four busy buyers and

02:36:25.000 --> 02:36:29.080
[Amit Varma]: they buy something and then many others come and they buy the same things. And on the second day,

02:36:29.080 --> 02:36:33.560
[Amit Varma]: you realize that these guys aren't buyers, they're actually pretending to be buyers so that other

02:36:33.560 --> 02:36:39.000
[Amit Varma]: people imitate them. And it's kind of worth thinking about these aspects of human nature,

02:36:39.000 --> 02:36:43.560
[Amit Varma]: because the moment someone like you points them out, then someone like me can actually

02:36:43.560 --> 02:36:50.200
[Amit Varma]: absorb that tendency in myself and can correct for it. So that's kind of invaluable. Another

02:36:50.200 --> 02:36:56.840
[Amit Varma]: of the really interesting personal lessons that you have in here is about alteration tailors.

02:36:56.840 --> 02:36:59.320
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about this insight and how it struck you.

02:37:00.280 --> 02:37:05.640
[Guest]: So it acts like a lot of these ideas or articles, they can stem from a simple,

02:37:05.640 --> 02:37:09.800
[Guest]: a silly line I might have read somewhere. And I still remember this was I think in ET.

02:37:09.800 --> 02:37:14.360
[Guest]: ET used to have this glossy supplement called Panache, which would have, you know,

02:37:14.360 --> 02:37:18.360
[Guest]: good looking people with the top five suit brands and all of that happening in it,

02:37:18.360 --> 02:37:22.920
[Guest]: nothing to do with business, but all about this, the glamorous side of business as it were.

02:37:23.480 --> 02:37:28.680
[Guest]: There was a column there by a stylist and she talked about her five top tips for,

02:37:29.400 --> 02:37:35.560
[Guest]: you know, as style tips. And one of those five tips was get yourself an alteration tailor.

02:37:35.560 --> 02:37:40.360
[Guest]: And I thought that was strange, you know, never thought about it. And the rest of it was more

02:37:40.360 --> 02:37:44.920
[Guest]: standard stuff about, you know, dressing for the occasion, color, all of that.

02:37:44.920 --> 02:37:49.800
[Guest]: Get yourself an alteration tailor sounded odd. And the point she made, and I think in very brief was

02:37:49.800 --> 02:37:54.680
[Guest]: that, you know, that alteration tailor will make sure that that shirt sleeve, which is slightly

02:37:54.680 --> 02:37:59.400
[Guest]: longer, gets shortened so that it looks smarter with your jacket. That was the kind of thing.

02:38:00.040 --> 02:38:02.920
[Guest]: And I thought of that, I said, you know, wow, great idea here.

02:38:02.920 --> 02:38:07.880
[Guest]: And how important it is. And in many ways, how we all need an alteration tailor. So it could be to

02:38:07.880 --> 02:38:12.360
[Guest]: say sometimes, you know, we all have that shirt lying in our wardrobe, which we don't wear because

02:38:12.360 --> 02:38:17.800
[Guest]: one button has gone missing. And therefore, all we wear it and we ensure we fold up, roll up our

02:38:17.800 --> 02:38:22.280
[Guest]: sleeves because I can't keep them down because that button is missing. And all it took was maybe

02:38:22.280 --> 02:38:26.120
[Guest]: someone who could be an alteration tailor and fix that. It could be this thing about,

02:38:26.120 --> 02:38:29.320
[Guest]: you have a trouser, which is, you know, just that half inch too long.

02:38:29.320 --> 02:38:34.040
[Guest]: And if it therefore doesn't fall as well as it, it doesn't make you look as smart as it could.

02:38:34.040 --> 02:38:40.840
[Guest]: All it takes is someone to just point it out and reduce that half inch. And I took that now to say

02:38:40.840 --> 02:38:46.840
[Guest]: that, you know, it's not only about our clothes, it's about us here. We need an alteration tailor

02:38:46.840 --> 02:38:52.200
[Guest]: in our lives who will tell us about those little things that we're probably not doing right.

02:38:53.240 --> 02:38:56.920
[Guest]: You know, and it's not this grand fix. It's not saying, oh, if I need to get better,

02:38:56.920 --> 02:39:01.240
[Guest]: I need to now enroll for the advanced management program at Harvard. That's going to change me. No.

02:39:01.880 --> 02:39:07.880
[Guest]: What you sometimes need is a friend, someone close to you who can point out, you know what,

02:39:07.880 --> 02:39:12.040
[Guest]: might be a good idea to just pause a little before you kind of lose your cool.

02:39:12.040 --> 02:39:16.600
[Guest]: Just relax, you know, or you may not realize it, but you know, the way you say it,

02:39:16.600 --> 02:39:21.320
[Guest]: you might be sounding like you are, you know, you are being arrogant about what you know.

02:39:21.320 --> 02:39:26.600
[Guest]: These may be small fixes, but you need someone who will tell you that, you know what, there's a

02:39:26.600 --> 02:39:31.880
[Guest]: half inch that needs to be adjusted. And here's how you can do it. And having that alteration

02:39:31.880 --> 02:39:37.560
[Guest]: tailor in your life is such a powerful thing because you will have somebody who's kind of

02:39:37.560 --> 02:39:41.800
[Guest]: watching out for you, who's telling you. And it's sometimes it could also be to say that,

02:39:41.800 --> 02:39:45.160
[Guest]: you know what, that shirt you haven't worn because you think it's too tight.

02:39:45.160 --> 02:39:47.960
[Guest]: Let me make it all right for you. You can wear it. It's like saying,

02:39:47.960 --> 02:39:51.880
[Guest]: maybe you have strengths you haven't leveraged. You're not sure of yourself.

02:39:51.880 --> 02:39:55.080
[Guest]: And I'll tell you, you know what, you're very good at that. Every time I've seen you do it,

02:39:55.080 --> 02:40:00.120
[Guest]: you do it well. So maybe you want to do more of it. So I just think that little line about saying

02:40:00.120 --> 02:40:05.720
[Guest]: an alteration tailor is a good style tip, I think for me was terrific advice. And I would,

02:40:05.720 --> 02:40:10.520
[Guest]: I'm grateful for it. And if you now look back, I'm sure we can all relate to the fact that, hey,

02:40:11.320 --> 02:40:13.800
[Guest]: there was an alteration tailor in my life who made a difference.

02:40:13.800 --> 02:40:18.120
[Guest]: And maybe you want to make sure you still have that person. You know, it's, it's, it's never,

02:40:18.120 --> 02:40:20.920
[Guest]: we're never finished products in that sense. And it's a great idea to say,

02:40:20.920 --> 02:40:25.640
[Guest]: I have an alteration tailor who will help me to identify what are those small tweaks that need to

02:40:25.640 --> 02:40:30.120
[Guest]: be made and who will help me to get it right. So that was really the story around the alteration.

02:40:31.560 --> 02:40:35.080
[Guest]: That's a lovely thought and a lovely phrase behind it. And I'm just thinking aloud that

02:40:35.080 --> 02:40:39.480
[Amit Varma]: the kind of alteration tailor that I need right now is really a gym instructor.

02:40:39.480 --> 02:40:44.920
[Amit Varma]: Who can make me fit my clothes, rather than make my clothes fit me. This lockdown has really,

02:40:44.920 --> 02:40:50.280
[Amit Varma]: you know, some of us have expanded in unexpected ways. You know, I've taken,

02:40:50.280 --> 02:40:54.600
[Amit Varma]: I took copious notes on your books, but if we go through all of them, we'll take like,

02:40:54.600 --> 02:40:58.440
[Amit Varma]: you know, another three hours just to get through the insights. And I would rather that people

02:40:58.440 --> 02:41:03.320
[Amit Varma]: listening to this go out and buy the book and sort of learn from it themselves. I mean, in a sense,

02:41:03.320 --> 02:41:07.320
[Amit Varma]: I'm just thinking aloud, you are an alteration tailor. You are an alteration tailor.

02:41:07.320 --> 02:41:13.640
[Amit Varma]: You are an alteration tailor for so many ways at scale, you know, in a remote kind of way,

02:41:14.280 --> 02:41:19.480
[Amit Varma]: sharing these sort of insights, which is wonderful. So you know, there are plenty of

02:41:19.480 --> 02:41:25.000
[Amit Varma]: insights in your book, which are great for personal growth, which are great for leadership,

02:41:25.000 --> 02:41:30.520
[Amit Varma]: building teams, you know, making better decisions, all of those things. I'll leave it to the readers

02:41:30.520 --> 02:41:33.880
[Amit Varma]: to head over to the book and discover that they've got a taste of it. I'll end with two

02:41:33.880 --> 02:41:40.920
[Amit Varma]: final questions. And one is that something that I spoke about in my last episode with Roshan is how

02:41:40.920 --> 02:41:46.360
[Amit Varma]: we live in this brave new world for creators. And for some of us, certainly for me, I realized so

02:41:46.360 --> 02:41:51.560
[Amit Varma]: much more of this after the pandemic happened, where serendipitously, you know, I started the

02:41:51.560 --> 02:41:57.240
[Amit Varma]: course and I started consuming much more content that creators were putting up on YouTube and

02:41:57.240 --> 02:42:04.280
[Amit Varma]: elsewhere. And just the way the possibilities had expanded, and you know, the landscape had changed,

02:42:04.280 --> 02:42:09.640
[Amit Varma]: all of it kind of blew my mind. Now you are a creator yourself. You're a creator in the sense

02:42:09.640 --> 02:42:13.320
[Amit Varma]: that you've done these books, you've created these courses, you've got a YouTube channel,

02:42:13.320 --> 02:42:19.960
[Amit Varma]: so on and so forth, incredibly exciting times. And so so for you, while you might look back to mine,

02:42:19.960 --> 02:42:24.520
[Amit Varma]: what has happened in your life for content, a lot more of it is basically just going to

02:42:24.520 --> 02:42:28.760
[Amit Varma]: be looking forward because hey, it's so exciting. Tell me a little bit about this.

02:42:29.480 --> 02:42:34.840
[Amit Varma]: You know, what do you think of this new landscape for creators from a personal point of view from

02:42:34.840 --> 02:42:38.200
[Amit Varma]: the things that you are going to do and that you're looking forward to?

02:42:38.200 --> 02:42:44.600
[Guest]: Oh, I completely agree with you. I think these are exciting times for creators. I think the

02:42:44.600 --> 02:42:50.280
[Guest]: opportunities, the platforms available, it's become so much easier to do stuff.

02:42:50.280 --> 02:42:55.560
[Guest]: And you don't have to be terribly tech-savvy or, you know, clued in or have the most expensive

02:42:55.560 --> 02:43:01.640
[Guest]: equipment to do stuff. I think very simple tools can help you to kind of produce. And

02:43:02.200 --> 02:43:07.480
[Guest]: I think it's truly exciting times. What fascinates me is, of course, you know, I'm super excited

02:43:07.480 --> 02:43:11.960
[Guest]: about the next 60 years of my life. I think there is so much to do. I'd love to write a lot more.

02:43:13.320 --> 02:43:17.480
[Guest]: I'm only half, not even halfway through Ali Abdaal's recommendation as far as YouTube,

02:43:17.480 --> 02:43:22.280
[Guest]: you know, videos are concerned. But I'm super excited by that. And I just think that

02:43:23.800 --> 02:43:28.040
[Guest]: it comes back to you in several ways. And there are times when I do something and I figure that

02:43:28.040 --> 02:43:32.120
[Guest]: it hasn't really, you know, I think it's a great idea and it just doesn't work.

02:43:32.120 --> 02:43:36.920
[Guest]: And there's something else that I talked about. And suddenly you'll find that your

02:43:36.920 --> 02:43:41.560
[Guest]: neighbor, neighboring auntie is sending it to you on WhatsApp saying, you know, my son in the US

02:43:41.560 --> 02:43:45.400
[Guest]: sent it to me and I told him that I know this man. Why? Because that little video was so

02:43:45.400 --> 02:43:50.200
[Guest]: viral and has a life of its own. Now, I think it's just fascinating to see how this might happen,

02:43:50.200 --> 02:43:56.360
[Guest]: what it might do. And I think it tells you that, look, just do it. Put out that video. You never

02:43:56.360 --> 02:44:01.880
[Guest]: know what might happen with it. Something else that I've tried to do, and you must check this

02:44:01.880 --> 02:44:08.440
[Guest]: out, I must say, I try to say that, hey, is there an opportunity to reach out to more people,

02:44:08.440 --> 02:44:12.600
[Guest]: and not for any other reason, but to say that, look, maybe there are other people out there

02:44:12.600 --> 02:44:17.880
[Guest]: who need to hear this. And how can I reach them? So I tried to do a chai with pie, which is the

02:44:17.880 --> 02:44:25.720
[Guest]: video that I do on YouTube in Hindi. And I just loved it. And I could worry about how many views

02:44:25.720 --> 02:44:29.880
[Guest]: will I get. And it's not as if suddenly, you know, I've hit gold dust or any such thing. But I think

02:44:29.880 --> 02:44:34.040
[Guest]: I suddenly touched different people. And there are another set of people saying, you know,

02:44:34.040 --> 02:44:37.400
[Guest]: that they liked it. And maybe there's an opportunity here to say, look, I could do

02:44:37.400 --> 02:44:42.680
[Guest]: something over here. I've learned, I, like I said, I learned, I signed up to learn writing in your

02:44:42.680 --> 02:44:46.920
[Guest]: writing course, which I loved. I signed up for a standup comedy course. And I just think that,

02:44:46.920 --> 02:44:51.960
[Guest]: you know, that's another place where you have this ability to look at something and find another

02:44:51.960 --> 02:44:55.640
[Guest]: meaning to it. You take people down one path and take them, suddenly take them somewhere else.

02:44:55.640 --> 02:44:58.840
[Guest]: And, you know, in some ways I think it's similar and maybe that's something else.

02:44:58.840 --> 02:45:02.840
[Guest]: So I wouldn't be, you know, I wouldn't bet against myself. And maybe a year from now,

02:45:02.840 --> 02:45:06.680
[Guest]: maybe two, you'll probably find something else. And I think that's another place where

02:45:06.680 --> 02:45:12.760
[Guest]: you'll probably find something else happening as far as I'm concerned. I'd like something else

02:45:12.760 --> 02:45:16.840
[Guest]: that you've mentioned, and I'm mindful of it, which is, you know, there's only so much that

02:45:16.840 --> 02:45:22.120
[Guest]: I want to do in terms of mining from the past. Because, you know, there is only so much that

02:45:22.120 --> 02:45:28.920
[Guest]: is, but I do think that there is so much I learn about, I see around me every day. And there's so

02:45:28.920 --> 02:45:34.040
[Guest]: much to learn and so much to kind of make sense out of. And therefore, what I see is, what do I

02:45:34.040 --> 02:45:38.760
[Guest]: see my role? It's not to say that, you know what, I was working in this organization, I learned

02:45:38.760 --> 02:45:42.600
[Guest]: something and here's what I want to share. That's maybe one part of it. Maybe it's a bit of it is

02:45:42.600 --> 02:45:49.160
[Guest]: done. What I really want to do is to try and say, let me try and make this simple for you to

02:45:49.160 --> 02:45:54.600
[Guest]: understand. Here's a powerful lesson, but let me try and tell it to you in a manner that you will

02:45:54.600 --> 02:46:01.400
[Guest]: remember, in a manner that you will relate to. And to me, that becomes then the role that I see

02:46:01.400 --> 02:46:06.440
[Guest]: myself playing. This is not about saying, look, everybody, look, I've done it. That's never been

02:46:06.440 --> 02:46:10.680
[Guest]: the intent. I don't think I've, and I've not done half the things that a lot of successful people in

02:46:10.680 --> 02:46:16.040
[Guest]: the corporate world have done. So I can't even lay claim to that. But what I try and do is to say,

02:46:16.040 --> 02:46:19.960
[Guest]: hey, here's something simple, you know, it's important. And let me explain it to you in a

02:46:19.960 --> 02:46:24.120
[Guest]: manner which you will relate to. And there is so much that's happening in our world now,

02:46:24.840 --> 02:46:30.920
[Guest]: which still needs for someone to try and make sense of and make simple sense of, in a sense,

02:46:30.920 --> 02:46:35.720
[Guest]: to make it easy to understand, make it easy to remember, and make it palatable to say that

02:46:36.360 --> 02:46:40.840
[Guest]: I'm not here to tell you that this is how you should succeed in life. Or if this is the creator

02:46:40.840 --> 02:46:45.080
[Guest]: economy, here are the five rules to succeed. That's not what I want to do. But I want to try

02:46:45.080 --> 02:46:49.640
[Guest]: and make it intuitive, try and say, here's something simple. Maybe it struck you, maybe it

02:46:49.640 --> 02:46:54.360
[Guest]: didn't. But you know, if you, if this kind of gets into your head, it might find residence there,

02:46:54.360 --> 02:46:59.880
[Guest]: and it might change the way you think. It might change the way you look at the world. And for me,

02:46:59.880 --> 02:47:05.480
[Guest]: I think that is perhaps the biggest piece here, which is that a lot of times, what you need to

02:47:05.480 --> 02:47:11.000
[Guest]: change is not to tell people how to do it, and here's how you do it, but to get them to think

02:47:11.000 --> 02:47:16.600
[Guest]: differently about it. And often it could be to say, you can do it, which sounds like such a boring

02:47:16.600 --> 02:47:20.200
[Guest]: motivation line, you know, you can do it and all of that. But I think it's simply to say,

02:47:20.760 --> 02:47:25.080
[Guest]: we all tend to think of our limitations, we tend to think of why it can't be done,

02:47:25.080 --> 02:47:28.840
[Guest]: we tend to think of what's wrong with the world and why it would prevent me from doing it.

02:47:28.840 --> 02:47:33.640
[Guest]: And if you do that, what happens is that you, you know, very soon you become a fabulous lawyer

02:47:33.640 --> 02:47:38.440
[Guest]: for that and you build such a strong case that they win. And you end up saying, oh, you know,

02:47:38.440 --> 02:47:43.080
[Guest]: I could have been the guy who did it, I could have achieved so much if this was a different world.

02:47:43.720 --> 02:47:47.560
[Guest]: But you know what, the world is what it is, you can change and you can make things happen. And

02:47:47.560 --> 02:47:52.840
[Guest]: I think just reclaiming the power, which is what I think the creator economy is doing in many ways,

02:47:52.840 --> 02:47:59.080
[Guest]: is helping people reclaim the power to make a difference. And I think it's there for all of us

02:47:59.080 --> 02:48:04.920
[Amit Varma]: to claim. Yeah, exactly. Inspiring words. And one of the things that I keep pointing out to,

02:48:04.920 --> 02:48:08.760
[Amit Varma]: you know, everyone who signs up for my writing course is that there are some things which

02:48:08.760 --> 02:48:12.280
[Amit Varma]: require natural talent. Like if you want to be a fast bowler, you've got to have fast twitch

02:48:12.280 --> 02:48:17.640
[Amit Varma]: muscles, a batsman will need some hand-eye coordination. But for a writer, I don't believe

02:48:17.640 --> 02:48:23.160
[Amit Varma]: that you need any natural talent at all. I think anyone can learn to write. It's just a question

02:48:23.160 --> 02:48:28.200
[Amit Varma]: of hard work, applying yourself, you know, having the right approach to writing. And that's again

02:48:28.200 --> 02:48:34.920
[Amit Varma]: something that you just sort of spoke about, that people don't know how far their own capacities

02:48:34.920 --> 02:48:40.760
[Amit Varma]: can extend if they just have the right mindset. So more power to you for, you know, achieving all

02:48:40.760 --> 02:48:46.120
[Amit Varma]: of these things. My final question and almost a predictable one is that, you know, listeners of

02:48:46.120 --> 02:48:51.880
[Amit Varma]: my show are always hungry for book recommendations. Now, you have written books which some people

02:48:51.880 --> 02:48:57.640
[Amit Varma]: would say have touched their lives or even changed them and so on. If I were to throw the onus back

02:48:57.640 --> 02:49:01.960
[Amit Varma]: on you, that what are the books that, you know, maybe changed the way you think about the world

02:49:01.960 --> 02:49:07.800
[Amit Varma]: or meant a lot to you or that you learned from or that you're simply so enthusiastic about that

02:49:07.800 --> 02:49:12.040
[Amit Varma]: you are like, I have to share this with the world. You know, do you have any recommendations?

02:49:12.040 --> 02:49:19.000
[Guest]: So I'm a big fan of Malcolm Gladwell. I love his storytelling style and his ability to pull

02:49:19.000 --> 02:49:24.360
[Guest]: together strands of research from, you know, from all kinds of places and then suddenly magically

02:49:24.360 --> 02:49:30.360
[Guest]: weave them into a narrative. So I'm a big fan of his writing, his podcasts, and I'd highly

02:49:30.360 --> 02:49:38.360
[Guest]: recommend Malcolm Gladwell to people. And maybe I also like the idea of, you know,

02:49:38.360 --> 02:49:44.840
[Guest]: writing not because of, not only for the manner in which it's been put together, but for the idea

02:49:44.840 --> 02:49:49.160
[Guest]: there. And I think it's so well done that you forget to look at the writing. And, you know,

02:49:49.160 --> 02:49:55.640
[Guest]: this is something I know, Amit, you put very eloquently, W and not the WP, you know,

02:49:55.640 --> 02:49:58.920
[Guest]: window and not the window pane. And I think that's something that's such a powerful idea where you

02:49:58.920 --> 02:50:02.920
[Guest]: don't try and draw attention to the writing, but you try and look at the ideas over there.

02:50:02.920 --> 02:50:07.560
[Guest]: So I'm a big fan of Malcolm Gladwell. I love his writing style. I love the way he

02:50:07.560 --> 02:50:14.040
[Guest]: so I'm a big fan of this half psychology, half in, you know, so Dan Arely, for example,

02:50:14.040 --> 02:50:16.280
[Guest]: big fan of the kind of stuff that he writes.

02:50:16.920 --> 02:50:22.120
[Amit Varma]: Though he's gotten into trouble recently, you read about that in the sort of the data in his

02:50:22.120 --> 02:50:27.160
[Amit Varma]: research. Anyway, the jury's out on whose fault exactly it is, but it's a lot of these behavioral

02:50:27.160 --> 02:50:32.680
[Amit Varma]: psychology experiments have turned out to not be replicable. But anyway, I think even the ones that

02:50:32.680 --> 02:50:38.520
[Amit Varma]: aren't replicable point to interesting core insights that one should at least think about.

02:50:38.520 --> 02:50:41.720
[Guest]: That's right. That's right. And I'll tell you something else. As a kid growing up,

02:50:41.720 --> 02:50:43.320
